{"title_page": "Defence Intelligence", "text_new": "{{About|the British intelligence organisation|other uses|Defense intelligence (disambiguation)}}\n{{Redirect|Chief of Defence Intelligence|the Canadian office|Chief of Defence Intelligence (Canada)|the Nigerian office|Chief of Defence Intelligence (Nigeria)}}\n{{use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox government agency\n| name = Defence Intelligence\n| native_name = \n| native_name_a = \n| native_name_r = \n| type = Organisation\n| seal = File:MinistryofDefence.svg\n| seal_width = 90\n| seal_caption = \n| logo = \n| logo_width = \n| logo_caption = \n| image = Pathfinder Building - Wyton.jpg\n| image_size = \n| image_caption = The Pathfinder Building at [[RAF Wyton]]\n| formed = {{Start date|1964|04|01|df=yes}} (as Defence Intelligence Staff)\n| preceding1 = [[RAF Intelligence|Air Intelligence]]\n| preceding2 = [[Directorate of Military Intelligence (United Kingdom)|Military Intelligence]]\n| preceding3 = [[Naval Intelligence Division|Naval Intelligence]]\n| dissolved = \n| superseding1 = \n| superseding2 = <!-- up to |superseding6= -->\n| jurisdiction = [[Government of the United Kingdom|HM Government]]\n| headquarters = MOD Main Building London\n| coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LATITUDE|LONGITUDE|type:landmark_region:US|display=inline,title}} -->\n| motto = \"Quaesitum est scire\"  (To Know is To Conquer)\n| employees = {{formatnum:3697}}<small> (31 March 2015)</small><ref name=\"ISC_2015-2016\">House of Commons (5 July 2016). [http://isc.independent.gov.uk/files/2015-2016_ISC_AR.pdf ''Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament Annual Report 2015\u20132016''], page 16. Retrieved 23 October 2016.</ref>\n| budget = \n| minister1_name = \n| minister1_pfo = \n| minister2_name = \n| minister2_pfo = <!-- up to |minister8_name= -->\n| deputyminister1_name = \n| deputyminister1_pfo = \n| deputyminister2_name = \n| deputyminister2_pfo = <!-- up to |deputyminister8_name= -->\n| chief1_name = Lieutenant-General [[James Hockenhull]]\n| chief1_position = Chief of Defence Intelligence\n| chief2_name = \n| chief2_position = \n| chief3_name = \n| chief3_position = \n| chief4_name = \n| chief4_position = \n| chief5_name = \n| chief5_position = \n| chief6_name = \n| public_protector = \n| deputy = \n| chief6_position = \n| chief7_name = \n| chief7_position = \n| chief8_name = \n| chief8_position = \n| chief9_name = \n| chief9_position = \n| parent_department = [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]]\n| parent_agency = [[Strategic Command]]\n| child1_agency = \n| child2_agency = <!-- up to |child25_agency= -->\n| keydocument1 = <!-- up to |keydocument6= -->\n| website = {{URL|https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/defence-intelligence}}\n| agency_id = \n| map = \n| map_size = \n| map_caption = \n| footnotes = \n| embed = \n}}\n'''Defence Intelligence''' ('''DI''') is an organisation within the [[United Kingdom intelligence community|United Kingdom Intelligence Community]] which focuses on collecting and analysing [[military intelligence]]. It differs from the other UK intelligence agencies ([[Secret Intelligence Service|MI6]], [[GCHQ]] and [[MI5]]) in that it is an integral part of the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] (MoD) rather than a stand-alone organisation. The organisation employs a mixture of civilian and military staff and is funded within the UK's defence budget. The organisation was formerly known as the Defence Intelligence Staff (DIS), but changed its name in 2009.\n\nThe primary role of Defence Intelligence is that of '[[All-source intelligence|all-source]]' [[intelligence analysis]]. This discipline draws information from a variety of overt and covert sources to provide the intelligence needed to support military operations, contingency planning, and to inform defence policy and procurement decisions. The maintenance of the ability to give timely strategic warning of politico-military and scientific and technical developments with the potential to affect UK interests is a vital part of the process. DI's assessments are used outside the MoD to support the work of the [[Joint Intelligence Committee (United Kingdom)|Joint Intelligence Committee (JIC)]] and to assist the work of other Government departments (OGDs) and international partners (such as [[NATO]] and the [[European Union]]). It is this 'all-source' function which distinguishes Defence Intelligence from other organisations such as SIS and GCHQ which focus on the collection of 'single-source' Human Intelligence ([[HUMINT]]) and Signals Intelligence ([[SIGINT]]) respectively. As such Defence Intelligence occupies a unique position within the UK intelligence community.\n\n==History==\n\n=== Early Years ===\nDefence Intelligence can trace its history back to 1873 and the formation Intelligence Branch of the British [[War Office]], which later became the [[Directorate of Military Intelligence (United Kingdom)|Directorate of Military Intelligence]]. The [[Admiralty]], responsible for the command of the [[Royal Navy]], subsequently formed the Foreign Intelligence Committee in 1882, which evolved into the [[Naval Intelligence Department (United Kingdom)|Naval Intelligence Department]] (NID) in 1887 while the [[Committee of Imperial Defence]], established in 1902, was responsible for co-ordination between the different armed services of on issues of [[military strategy]] intelligence assessments and estimates. During [[World War I]], British [[Secret service|secret services]] were divided into numbered sections named ''Military Intelligence'' together with a department number, such as MI1 for the secretariat of the Director of Military Intelligence. Many of the original MI departments, such as MI4 (Aerial Photography) were eventually subsumed into Defence Intelligence, while the more famous [[MI5]] and [[Secret Intelligence Service|MI6]] denoted the liaison sections with the Security Service and Secret Intelligence Service respectively.\n\n=== Post-war years ===\nShortly after the Second World War, the topographical department of the [[War Office]] was transformed into the Joint Intelligence Bureau (JIB), and its director, [[Kenneth Strong|Sir Kenneth Strong]], became a full member of the [[Joint Intelligence Committee (United Kingdom)|Joint Intelligence Committee]] (JIC) in January 1947.\u00a0 The JIB was a high-powered research unit collating topographic and economic intelligence with political background so as to serve possible future military operations. It was not loved by the armed services, where its mingling of services and uniformed and civilian experts was seen as a threat to the traditional forms of service intelligence but it represented a first step in the direction of full integration of defence intelligence<ref>{{Cite book|last=Craddock|first=Percy|title=Know Your Enemy: How the Joint Intelligence Committee Saw the World.|publisher=John Murray Ltd|year=2002|isbn=|location=|pages=p.261}}</ref>.\n\n==Organisation==\nDefence Intelligence is headed by the Chief of Defence Intelligence (CDI) who is a serving [[three-star rank|three-star military officer]] and who, as the MOD's 'intelligence process owner', is also responsible for the overall co-ordination of intelligence activities throughout the Armed Forces and single Service Commands. He is supported by two deputies\u2014one civilian and one military. The civilian Deputy Chief of Defence Intelligence (DCDI) is responsible for Defence Intelligence analysis and production and the military Director of Cyber Intelligence and Information Integration (DCI3) is responsible for intelligence collection and capability.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/defence-intelligence|title=Defence Intelligence|publisher=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Deputy Chief of Defence Intelligence (DCDI)===\nDCDI manages the intelligence analysis and production directorates of Defence Intelligence. These include directorates for:\n* Strategic Assessments (regional and thematic)\n* Capability Assessments (weapons systems and platforms)\n* Counter Proliferation\n* Counter Intelligence\n\nDCDI is responsible for intelligence analysis and production, providing global defence intelligence assessments and strategic warning on a wide range of issues including, intelligence support for operations; proliferation and arms control; conventional military capabilities; strategic warning and technical evaluations of weapons systems. These intelligence assessments draw upon classified information provided by GCHQ, SIS, the Security Service, Allied intelligence services and military collection assets, in addition to diplomatic reporting and a wide range of publicly available or \u2018open source\u2019 information such as media reporting and the internet.<ref name=\"DIS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/defence-intelligence-services|title=Defence Intelligence: Roles|date=12 December 2012|work=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Director of Cyber Intelligence and Information Integration (DCI3)===\nDCI3 is responsible for the provision of specialised intelligence, imagery and geographic support services, and for the intelligence and security training of the Armed Forces. In addition to a Head Office policy staff he is responsible for two major groupings within Defence Intelligence:\n\n====Joint Forces Intelligence Group (JFIG)====\nThe JFIG was established in 2012 under the new Joint Forces Command and superseded the Intelligence Collection Group (ICG). Making up the largest sub-element of Defence Intelligence, JFIG is responsible for the collection of [[Signals intelligence|signals]], [[Geospatial intelligence|geospatial]], [[Imagery intelligence|imagery]] and [[measurement and signature intelligence]] and comprises:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/news/archive/joint-forces-intelligence-group-achieves-full-operating-capability-22092014|title=Joint Forces Intelligence Group Achieves Full Operating Capability|publisher=Ministry of Defence|date=22 September 2014|accessdate=7 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304075857/http://www.raf.mod.uk/news/archive/joint-forces-intelligence-group-achieves-full-operating-capability-22092014|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* The National Centre for Geospatial Intelligence (NCGI) formerly known as the Defence Geospatial Intelligence Fusion Centre (DGIFC) and prior to that JARIC (the National Imagery Exploitation Centre)\n*The Defence Geographic Centre (DGC)\n* Joint Services Signals Organisation (JSSO)\n* Defence HUMINT Unit (DHU)\n\nThe National Centre for Geospatial Intelligence (NCGI) is based at [[RAF Wyton]] in Cambridgeshire (since moving from [[RAF Brampton]] in 2013) and provides specialist imagery intelligence to the armed forces and other UK government customers. They deliver this through the exploitation of satellite imaging systems, as well as airborne and ground-based collection systems. DIFC uses these sources, together with advanced technologies, to provide regional intelligence assessments and support to strategic intelligence projections.<ref name=\"DIS\"/>\n\nThe Defence HUMINT Organisation (DHO) is a Tri-Service organisation that provides specialist support to military operations. The DHO manages strategic aspects of defence human intelligence and is under the command of a Colonel. It draws staff from across the three services.<ref name=\"DIS\"/>\n\nThe Joint Services Signals Organisation (JSSO) conducts research into new communications systems and techniques in order to provide operational support to static and deployed units. The JSSO is based at [[RAF Digby]] in Lincolnshire under the command of a Group Captain with some 1,600 staff drawn from all three services.<ref name=\"DIS\"/>\n\nIn 2013, JFIG HQ moved from Feltham in Middlesex to RAF Wyton.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-defence-intelligence-buildings-handed-over-to-mod--2 |title=New Defence Intelligence buildings handed over to MOD |publisher=Ministry of Defence |date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nga.mil/MediaRoom/Publications/Documents/Pathfinder%20Magazines/2012/2012_nov-dec.pdf |title=UK JARIC Transitions to Defence Geospatial and Intelligence Fusion Centre |date=November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130216175819/https://www1.nga.mil/MediaRoom/Publications/Documents/Pathfinder%20Magazines/2012/2012_nov-dec.pdf |archivedate=February 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Joint Intelligence Training Group (JITG)===\nThe [[Joint Intelligence Training Group]] (JITG), at [[Chicksands]], [[Bedfordshire]], provides a single defence focal point for intelligence, security, languages and photography training in the UK, though photography training is carried out at the [[Defence School of Photography]] (DSoP) off site at [[RAF Cosford]].<ref>{{cite web|title=RAF - Defence School of Photography|url=https://www.raf.mod.uk/rafcosford/aboutus/dsop.cfm|website=www.raf.mod.uk|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref> The organisation consists of a headquarters, the Defence College of Intelligence and a specialist operational intelligence capability. JITG is co-located with the headquarters of the [[British Army]]'s [[Intelligence Corps (United Kingdom)|Intelligence Corps]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/intelligence/32259.aspx|title=Defence Intelligence and Security Centre|publisher=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Bedfordshire - Joint Intelligence Training Group Chicksands|journal=Sanctuary|date=2015|issue=44|page=74|issn=0959-4132}}</ref>\n\n==Defence intelligence roles==\nTo support its mission, Defence Intelligence has four essential roles:\n\n'''Support to operations''': DI plays an integral part in the planning process throughout all stages of military operations, by providing intelligence collection and analysis at the tactical, operational and strategic levels. Examples of the support DI has provided to operations are:<ref name=\"DIS\"/>\n* Coalition action in Iraq\n* NATO led forces in Afghanistan and Bosnia\n* UN humanitarian and peace-support operations in Sierra Leone, Liberia, Cyprus, Eritrea and the Democratic Republic of Congo\nDI has deployed intelligence analysts, linguists and reservists overseas, and provide geographic support by supplying both standard and specialised mapping to overseas theatres.<ref name=\"DIS\"/>\n\n'''Support to contingency planning for operations''': DI provides intelligence data and all source assessments that assist in preparations for future situations with the potential to require the commitment of UK Armed Forces. These products, which cover political and military developments, country and cultural information, critical infrastructure and internal security, all aid contingency planning.<ref name=\"DIS\"/>\n\n'''Provision of early warning''': A fundamental responsibility of Defence Intelligence is to alert ministers, chiefs of staff, senior officials and defence planners to impending crises around the world. Such warning is vital for short and medium term planning. DI meets this responsibility by focusing on current areas and topics of concern, highlighting the effects of changing circumstances, predicting security and stability trends, and assessing how these trends may develop. The assessments are distributed to decision-makers throughout the MOD, the Armed Forces, other government departments, allies, and UK Embassies and High Commissions.<ref name=\"DIS\"/>\n\n'''Provision of longer-term analysis of emerging threats''': Defence Intelligence provides longer-term assessments of likely scenarios around the world where UK Armed Forces might need to operate and of the equipment that they might face. It also provides technical support to the development of future military equipment and to the development of countermeasures against potentially hostile systems.<ref name=\"DIS\"/>\n\n==How Defence Intelligence carries out its work==\n'''Direction''': The Chief of Defence Intelligence (CDI) receives direction from the Chief of Defence Staff (CDS) and Permanent Under Secretary (PUS) on MOD's Intelligence needs and draws national guidance from the Cabinet Office Joint Intelligence Committee (JIC).\n\n'''Analysis and production''': Intelligence assessments are written to meet the needs of customers and must be timely and relevant. The assessment process involves judging the authenticity and reliability of new information and its relevance to existing intelligence. Assessments focus on probable and possible outcomes, to provide the best available advice for developing a response or resolution. They are continually adjusted in light of new intelligence or events.\n\n==Chiefs of Defence Intelligence==\nThe Chiefs have been as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Ministry%20of%20Defence%20Senior%20Posts.pdf |title=Ministry of Defence Senior Posts |accessdate=7 November 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117033054/http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Ministry%20of%20Defence%20Senior%20Posts.pdf |archivedate=17 November 2015 }}</ref><br>\n'''Director-General Intelligence'''\n* Major-General Sir [[Kenneth Strong]], 1964\u20131966\n* Air Chief Marshal Sir [[Alfred Earle]], rtd 1966\u20131968\n* Air Marshal Sir [[Harold Maguire]], rtd 1968\u20131972\n* Vice-Admiral Sir [[Louis Le Bailly]] rtd 1972\u20131975\n* Lieutenant-General Sir [[David Willison]], rtd 1975\u20131978\n* Air Chief Marshal Sir [[John Aiken (RAF officer)|John Aiken]], rtd 1978\u20131981\n* Vice-Admiral Sir [[Roy Halliday]], rtd 1981\u20131984\n\n'''Chiefs of Defence Intelligence'''\n* Air Marshal Sir [[Michael Armitage (RAF officer)|Michael Armitage]] 1984\u20131986\n* Lieutenant-General Sir [[Derek Boorman]] 1986\u20131988\n* Vice-Admiral Sir [[John Kerr (Royal Navy officer)|John Kerr]] 1988\u20131991\n* Air Marshal Sir [[John Walker (RAF officer)|John Walker]], 1991\u20131994\n* Lieutenant-General Sir [[John Foley (British Army general)|John Foley]], 1994\u20131997\n* Vice-Admiral [[Alan West, Baron West of Spithead|Sir Alan West]], 1997\u20132000\n* Air Marshal Sir [[Joe French]], 2000\u20132003\n* Lieutenant-General Sir [[Andrew Ridgway]], 2003\u20132006\n* Air Marshal Sir [[Stuart Peach]] 2006\u20132009\n* Air Marshal [[Chris Nickols|Christopher Nickols]] 2009\u20132012\n* Vice-Admiral [[Alan Richards]] 2012\u20132015\n* Air Marshal [[Philip Osborn]] 2015\u20132018\n* Lieutenant-General [[James Hockenhull]] 2018\u2013present\n\n==See also==\n* [[Defense Intelligence Agency]] \u2013 United States counterpart\n* [[JARIC]]\n* [[List of intelligence agencies]]\n* [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]]\n* [[Operation Rockingham]]\n* [[RAF Intelligence]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book|last=Dylan|first=Huw |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sSTSBAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=twopage&q&f=false|title=Defence Intelligence and the Cold War: Britain's Joint Intelligence Bureau 1945\u20131964|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2014|isbn=978-0199657025}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/defence-intelligence#defence-intelligence Defence Intelligence]\n* [https://www.gov.uk/guidance/defence-intelligence Defence Intelligence Staff] (last updated 2012)\n* [http://www.archive.official-documents.co.uk/document/caboff/nim/0114301808.pdf/ National Intelligence Machinery]\n* [https://www.gov.uk/guidance/defence-intelligence-services#defence-geospatial-intelligence-fusion-centre/ Defence Intelligence] (last updated 2012; withdrawn 2014)\n\n{{Military intelligence agencies}}\n{{UK_Intelligence_Agencies}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:British intelligence agencies]]\n[[Category:Huntingdonshire]]\n[[Category:Military communications of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Military intelligence agencies]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1964]]\n[[Category:Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in Cambridgeshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the British intelligence organisation|other uses|Defense intelligence (disambiguation)}}\n{{Redirect|Chief of Defence Intelligence|the Canadian office|Chief of Defence Intelligence (Canada)|the Nigerian office|Chief of Defence Intelligence (Nigeria)}}\n{{use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox government agency\n| name = Defence Intelligence\n| native_name = \n| native_name_a = \n| native_name_r = \n| type = Organisation\n| seal = File:MinistryofDefence.svg\n| seal_width = 90\n| seal_caption = \n| logo = \n| logo_width = \n| logo_caption = \n| image = Pathfinder Building - Wyton.jpg\n| image_size = \n| image_caption = The Pathfinder Building at [[RAF Wyton]]\n| formed = {{Start date|1964|04|01|df=yes}} (as Defence Intelligence Staff)\n| preceding1 = [[RAF Intelligence|Air Intelligence]]\n| preceding2 = [[Directorate of Military Intelligence (United Kingdom)|Military Intelligence]]\n| preceding3 = [[Naval Intelligence Division|Naval Intelligence]]\n| dissolved = \n| superseding1 = \n| superseding2 = <!-- up to |superseding6= -->\n| jurisdiction = [[Government of the United Kingdom|HM Government]]\n| headquarters = MOD Main Building London\n| coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LATITUDE|LONGITUDE|type:landmark_region:US|display=inline,title}} -->\n| motto = \"Quaesitum est scire\"  (To Know is To Conquer)\n| employees = {{formatnum:3697}}<small> (31 March 2015)</small><ref name=\"ISC_2015-2016\">House of Commons (5 July 2016). [http://isc.independent.gov.uk/files/2015-2016_ISC_AR.pdf ''Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament Annual Report 2015\u20132016''], page 16. Retrieved 23 October 2016.</ref>\n| budget = \n| minister1_name = \n| minister1_pfo = \n| minister2_name = \n| minister2_pfo = <!-- up to |minister8_name= -->\n| deputyminister1_name = \n| deputyminister1_pfo = \n| deputyminister2_name = \n| deputyminister2_pfo = <!-- up to |deputyminister8_name= -->\n| chief1_name = Lieutenant-General [[James Hockenhull]]\n| chief1_position = Chief of Defence Intelligence\n| chief2_name = \n| chief2_position = \n| chief3_name = \n| chief3_position = \n| chief4_name = \n| chief4_position = \n| chief5_name = \n| chief5_position = \n| chief6_name = \n| public_protector = \n| deputy = \n| chief6_position = \n| chief7_name = \n| chief7_position = \n| chief8_name = \n| chief8_position = \n| chief9_name = \n| chief9_position = \n| parent_department = [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]]\n| parent_agency = [[Strategic Command]]\n| child1_agency = \n| child2_agency = <!-- up to |child25_agency= -->\n| keydocument1 = <!-- up to |keydocument6= -->\n| website = {{URL|https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/defence-intelligence}}\n| agency_id = \n| map = \n| map_size = \n| map_caption = \n| footnotes = \n| embed = \n}}\n'''Defence Intelligence''' ('''DI''') is an organisation within the [[United Kingdom intelligence community|United Kingdom Intelligence Community]] which focuses on collecting and analysing [[military intelligence]]. It differs from the UK's intelligence agencies ([[Secret Intelligence Service|MI6]], [[GCHQ]] and [[MI5]]) in that it is an integral part of the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] (MoD) rather than a stand-alone organisation. The organisation employs a mixture of civilian and military staff and is funded within the UK's defence budget. The organisation was formerly known as the Defence Intelligence Staff (DIS), but changed its name in 2009.\n\nThe primary role of Defence Intelligence is that of '[[All-source intelligence|all-source]]' [[intelligence analysis]]. This discipline draws information from a variety of overt and covert sources to provide the intelligence needed to support military operations, contingency planning, and to inform defence policy and procurement decisions. The maintenance of the ability to give timely strategic warning of politico-military and scientific and technical developments with the potential to affect UK interests is a vital part of the process. DI's assessments are used outside the MoD to support the work of the [[Joint Intelligence Committee (United Kingdom)|Joint Intelligence Committee (JIC)]] and to assist the work of other Government departments (OGDs) and international partners (such as [[NATO]] and the [[European Union]]). It is this 'all-source' function which distinguishes Defence Intelligence from other organisations such as SIS and GCHQ which focus on the collection of 'single-source' Human Intelligence ([[HUMINT]]) and Signals Intelligence ([[SIGINT]]) respectively. As such Defence Intelligence occupies a unique position within the UK intelligence community.\n\n==History==\n\n=== Early Years ===\nDefence Intelligence can trace its history back to 1873 and the formation Intelligence Branch of the British [[War Office]], which later became the [[Directorate of Military Intelligence (United Kingdom)|Directorate of Military Intelligence]]. The [[Admiralty]], responsible for the command of the [[Royal Navy]], subsequently formed the Foreign Intelligence Committee in 1882, which evolved into the [[Naval Intelligence Department (United Kingdom)|Naval Intelligence Department]] (NID) in 1887 while the [[Committee of Imperial Defence]], established in 1902, was responsible for co-ordination between the different armed services of on issues of [[military strategy]] intelligence assessments and estimates. During [[World War I]], British [[Secret service|secret services]] were divided into numbered sections named ''Military Intelligence'' together with a department number, such as MI1 for the secretariat of the Director of Military Intelligence. Many of the original MI departments, such as MI4 (Aerial Photography) were eventually subsumed into Defence Intelligence, while the more famous [[MI5]] and [[Secret Intelligence Service|MI6]] denoted the liaison sections with the Security Service and Secret Intelligence Service respectively.\n\n=== Post-war years ===\nShortly after the Second World War, the topographical department of the [[War Office]] was transformed into the Joint Intelligence Bureau (JIB), and its director, [[Kenneth Strong|Sir Kenneth Strong]], became a full member of the [[Joint Intelligence Committee (United Kingdom)|Joint Intelligence Committee]] (JIC) in January 1947.\u00a0 The JIB was a high-powered research unit collating topographic and economic intelligence with political background so as to serve possible future military operations. It was not loved by the armed services, where its mingling of services and uniformed and civilian experts was seen as a threat to the traditional forms of service intelligence but it represented a first step in the direction of full integration of defence intelligence<ref>{{Cite book|last=Craddock|first=Percy|title=Know Your Enemy: How the Joint Intelligence Committee Saw the World.|publisher=John Murray Ltd|year=2002|isbn=|location=|pages=p.261}}</ref>.\n\n==Organisation==\nDefence Intelligence is headed by the Chief of Defence Intelligence (CDI) who is a serving [[three-star rank|three-star military officer]] and who, as the MOD's 'intelligence process owner', is also responsible for the overall co-ordination of intelligence activities throughout the Armed Forces and single Service Commands. He is supported by two deputies\u2014one civilian and one military. The civilian Deputy Chief of Defence Intelligence (DCDI) is responsible for Defence Intelligence analysis and production and the military Director of Cyber Intelligence and Information Integration (DCI3) is responsible for intelligence collection and capability.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/defence-intelligence|title=Defence Intelligence|publisher=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Deputy Chief of Defence Intelligence (DCDI)===\nDCDI manages the intelligence analysis and production directorates of Defence Intelligence. These include directorates for:\n* Strategic Assessments (regional and thematic)\n* Capability Assessments (weapons systems and platforms)\n* Counter Proliferation\n* Counter Intelligence\n\nDCDI is responsible for intelligence analysis and production, providing global defence intelligence assessments and strategic warning on a wide range of issues including, intelligence support for operations; proliferation and arms control; conventional military capabilities; strategic warning and technical evaluations of weapons systems. These intelligence assessments draw upon classified information provided by GCHQ, SIS, the Security Service, Allied intelligence services and military collection assets, in addition to diplomatic reporting and a wide range of publicly available or \u2018open source\u2019 information such as media reporting and the internet.<ref name=\"DIS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/defence-intelligence-services|title=Defence Intelligence: Roles|date=12 December 2012|work=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Director of Cyber Intelligence and Information Integration (DCI3)===\nDCI3 is responsible for the provision of specialised intelligence, imagery and geographic support services, and for the intelligence and security training of the Armed Forces. In addition to a Head Office policy staff he is responsible for two major groupings within Defence Intelligence:\n\n====Joint Forces Intelligence Group (JFIG)====\nThe JFIG was established in 2012 under the new Joint Forces Command and superseded the Intelligence Collection Group (ICG). Making up the largest sub-element of Defence Intelligence, JFIG is responsible for the collection of [[Signals intelligence|signals]], [[Geospatial intelligence|geospatial]], [[Imagery intelligence|imagery]] and [[measurement and signature intelligence]] and comprises:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/news/archive/joint-forces-intelligence-group-achieves-full-operating-capability-22092014|title=Joint Forces Intelligence Group Achieves Full Operating Capability|publisher=Ministry of Defence|date=22 September 2014|accessdate=7 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304075857/http://www.raf.mod.uk/news/archive/joint-forces-intelligence-group-achieves-full-operating-capability-22092014|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* The National Centre for Geospatial Intelligence (NCGI) formerly known as the Defence Geospatial Intelligence Fusion Centre (DGIFC) and prior to that JARIC (the National Imagery Exploitation Centre)\n*The Defence Geographic Centre (DGC)\n* Joint Services Signals Organisation (JSSO)\n* Defence HUMINT Unit (DHU)\n\nThe National Centre for Geospatial Intelligence (NCGI) is based at [[RAF Wyton]] in Cambridgeshire (since moving from [[RAF Brampton]] in 2013) and provides specialist imagery intelligence to the armed forces and other UK government customers. They deliver this through the exploitation of satellite imaging systems, as well as airborne and ground-based collection systems. DIFC uses these sources, together with advanced technologies, to provide regional intelligence assessments and support to strategic intelligence projections.<ref name=\"DIS\"/>\n\nThe Defence HUMINT Organisation (DHO) is a Tri-Service organisation that provides specialist support to military operations. The DHO manages strategic aspects of defence human intelligence and is under the command of a Colonel. It draws staff from across the three services.<ref name=\"DIS\"/>\n\nThe Joint Services Signals Organisation (JSSO) conducts research into new communications systems and techniques in order to provide operational support to static and deployed units. The JSSO is based at [[RAF Digby]] in Lincolnshire under the command of a Group Captain with some 1,600 staff drawn from all three services.<ref name=\"DIS\"/>\n\nIn 2013, JFIG HQ moved from Feltham in Middlesex to RAF Wyton.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-defence-intelligence-buildings-handed-over-to-mod--2 |title=New Defence Intelligence buildings handed over to MOD |publisher=Ministry of Defence |date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nga.mil/MediaRoom/Publications/Documents/Pathfinder%20Magazines/2012/2012_nov-dec.pdf |title=UK JARIC Transitions to Defence Geospatial and Intelligence Fusion Centre |date=November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130216175819/https://www1.nga.mil/MediaRoom/Publications/Documents/Pathfinder%20Magazines/2012/2012_nov-dec.pdf |archivedate=February 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Joint Intelligence Training Group (JITG)===\nThe [[Joint Intelligence Training Group]] (JITG), at [[Chicksands]], [[Bedfordshire]], provides a single defence focal point for intelligence, security, languages and photography training in the UK, though photography training is carried out at the [[Defence School of Photography]] (DSoP) off site at [[RAF Cosford]].<ref>{{cite web|title=RAF - Defence School of Photography|url=https://www.raf.mod.uk/rafcosford/aboutus/dsop.cfm|website=www.raf.mod.uk|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref> The organisation consists of a headquarters, the Defence College of Intelligence and a specialist operational intelligence capability. JITG is co-located with the headquarters of the [[British Army]]'s [[Intelligence Corps (United Kingdom)|Intelligence Corps]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/intelligence/32259.aspx|title=Defence Intelligence and Security Centre|publisher=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Bedfordshire - Joint Intelligence Training Group Chicksands|journal=Sanctuary|date=2015|issue=44|page=74|issn=0959-4132}}</ref>\n\n==Defence intelligence roles==\nTo support its mission, Defence Intelligence has four essential roles:\n\n'''Support to operations''': DI plays an integral part in the planning process throughout all stages of military operations, by providing intelligence collection and analysis at the tactical, operational and strategic levels. Examples of the support DI has provided to operations are:<ref name=\"DIS\"/>\n* Coalition action in Iraq\n* NATO led forces in Afghanistan and Bosnia\n* UN humanitarian and peace-support operations in Sierra Leone, Liberia, Cyprus, Eritrea and the Democratic Republic of Congo\nDI has deployed intelligence analysts, linguists and reservists overseas, and provide geographic support by supplying both standard and specialised mapping to overseas theatres.<ref name=\"DIS\"/>\n\n'''Support to contingency planning for operations''': DI provides intelligence data and all source assessments that assist in preparations for future situations with the potential to require the commitment of UK Armed Forces. These products, which cover political and military developments, country and cultural information, critical infrastructure and internal security, all aid contingency planning.<ref name=\"DIS\"/>\n\n'''Provision of early warning''': A fundamental responsibility of Defence Intelligence is to alert ministers, chiefs of staff, senior officials and defence planners to impending crises around the world. Such warning is vital for short and medium term planning. DI meets this responsibility by focusing on current areas and topics of concern, highlighting the effects of changing circumstances, predicting security and stability trends, and assessing how these trends may develop. The assessments are distributed to decision-makers throughout the MOD, the Armed Forces, other government departments, allies, and UK Embassies and High Commissions.<ref name=\"DIS\"/>\n\n'''Provision of longer-term analysis of emerging threats''': Defence Intelligence provides longer-term assessments of likely scenarios around the world where UK Armed Forces might need to operate and of the equipment that they might face. It also provides technical support to the development of future military equipment and to the development of countermeasures against potentially hostile systems.<ref name=\"DIS\"/>\n\n==How Defence Intelligence carries out its work==\n'''Direction''': The Chief of Defence Intelligence (CDI) receives direction from the Chief of Defence Staff (CDS) and Permanent Under Secretary (PUS) on MOD's Intelligence needs and draws national guidance from the Cabinet Office Joint Intelligence Committee (JIC).\n\n'''Analysis and production''': Intelligence assessments are written to meet the needs of customers and must be timely and relevant. The assessment process involves judging the authenticity and reliability of new information and its relevance to existing intelligence. Assessments focus on probable and possible outcomes, to provide the best available advice for developing a response or resolution. They are continually adjusted in light of new intelligence or events.\n\n==Chiefs of Defence Intelligence==\nThe Chiefs have been as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Ministry%20of%20Defence%20Senior%20Posts.pdf |title=Ministry of Defence Senior Posts |accessdate=7 November 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117033054/http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Ministry%20of%20Defence%20Senior%20Posts.pdf |archivedate=17 November 2015 }}</ref><br>\n'''Director-General Intelligence'''\n* Major-General Sir [[Kenneth Strong]], 1964\u20131966\n* Air Chief Marshal Sir [[Alfred Earle]], rtd 1966\u20131968\n* Air Marshal Sir [[Harold Maguire]], rtd 1968\u20131972\n* Vice-Admiral Sir [[Louis Le Bailly]] rtd 1972\u20131975\n* Lieutenant-General Sir [[David Willison]], rtd 1975\u20131978\n* Air Chief Marshal Sir [[John Aiken (RAF officer)|John Aiken]], rtd 1978\u20131981\n* Vice-Admiral Sir [[Roy Halliday]], rtd 1981\u20131984\n\n'''Chiefs of Defence Intelligence'''\n* Air Marshal Sir [[Michael Armitage (RAF officer)|Michael Armitage]] 1984\u20131986\n* Lieutenant-General Sir [[Derek Boorman]] 1986\u20131988\n* Vice-Admiral Sir [[John Kerr (Royal Navy officer)|John Kerr]] 1988\u20131991\n* Air Marshal Sir [[John Walker (RAF officer)|John Walker]], 1991\u20131994\n* Lieutenant-General Sir [[John Foley (British Army general)|John Foley]], 1994\u20131997\n* Vice-Admiral [[Alan West, Baron West of Spithead|Sir Alan West]], 1997\u20132000\n* Air Marshal Sir [[Joe French]], 2000\u20132003\n* Lieutenant-General Sir [[Andrew Ridgway]], 2003\u20132006\n* Air Marshal Sir [[Stuart Peach]] 2006\u20132009\n* Air Marshal [[Chris Nickols|Christopher Nickols]] 2009\u20132012\n* Vice-Admiral [[Alan Richards]] 2012\u20132015\n* Air Marshal [[Philip Osborn]] 2015\u20132018\n* Lieutenant-General [[James Hockenhull]] 2018\u2013present\n\n==See also==\n* [[Defense Intelligence Agency]] \u2013 United States counterpart\n* [[JARIC]]\n* [[List of intelligence agencies]]\n* [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]]\n* [[Operation Rockingham]]\n* [[RAF Intelligence]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book|last=Dylan|first=Huw |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sSTSBAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=twopage&q&f=false|title=Defence Intelligence and the Cold War: Britain's Joint Intelligence Bureau 1945\u20131964|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2014|isbn=978-0199657025}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/defence-intelligence#defence-intelligence Defence Intelligence]\n* [https://www.gov.uk/guidance/defence-intelligence Defence Intelligence Staff] (last updated 2012)\n* [http://www.archive.official-documents.co.uk/document/caboff/nim/0114301808.pdf/ National Intelligence Machinery]\n* [https://www.gov.uk/guidance/defence-intelligence-services#defence-geospatial-intelligence-fusion-centre/ Defence Intelligence] (last updated 2012; withdrawn 2014)\n\n{{Military intelligence agencies}}\n{{UK_Intelligence_Agencies}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:British intelligence agencies]]\n[[Category:Huntingdonshire]]\n[[Category:Military communications of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Military intelligence agencies]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1964]]\n[[Category:Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in Cambridgeshire]]\n", "name_user": "Kenstrong", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Defence_Intelligence"}
{"title_page": "Holistic grading", "text_new": "'''Holistic grading''', in [[Outcome-based education|standards-based education]], is an approach to scoring [[essay]]s using a simple grading structure that bases a grade on a paper's overall quality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/holistic-grading-composition-1690838|title=What Is Holistic Grading?|last=Nordquist|first=Richard|date=March 7, 2017|website=ThoughtCo|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref> This type of grading, which is also described as nonreductionist grading<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Bishop|first=Alan|title=International Handbook of Mathematics Education|last2=Clements|first2=M. A. (Ken)|last3=Keitel-Kreidt|first3=Christine|last4=Kilpatrick|first4=Jeremy|last5=Laborde|first5=Colette|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|year=2012|isbn=978-94-010-7155-0|location=Dordrecht|pages=354-355}}</ref>, contrasts with analytic grading,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cultofpedagogy.com/holistic-analytic-single-point-rubrics/|title=Know Your Terms: Holistic, Analytic, and Single-Point Rubrics|date=2014-05-01|website=Cult of Pedagogy|language=en|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref> which takes more factors into account when assigning a grade. Holistic grading can also be used to assess classroom-based work. Rather than counting errors, a paper is judged holistically and often compared to an [[anchor paper]] to evaluate if it meets a writing standard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://writing.colostate.edu/guides/teaching/commenting/holistic.cfm|title=Holistic Scoring in More Detail|website=writing.colostate.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref>\n\n== Model ==\nWhile analytic grading involves criterion-by-criterion judgments, holistic grading appraises student works as integrated entities. In holistic grading, the learner's performance is approached as one and cannot be reduced or divided into several component performances. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Joughin|first=Gordon|title=Assessment, Learning and Judgement in Higher Education|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|year=2008|isbn=978-1-4020-8904-6|location=Cham|pages=48}}</ref> Here, teachers are required to consider specific aspects of the student's answer as well as the quality of the whole.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Franck|first=Olof|title=Assessment in Ethics Education: A Case of National Tests in Religious Education|publisher=Springer|year=2017|isbn=978-3-319-50768-2|location=Cham, Switzerland|pages=72}}</ref> \n\nHolistic grading operates by distinguishing satisfactory performance from one that is simply adequate or outstanding.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Projects using holistic grading==\nMany institutions use holistic grading when evaluating student writing as part of a graduation requirement.<ref name=\":0\" /> Some examples include:\n\n* The [[National Certificate of Educational Achievement]] is the New Zealand graduation certificate, which bases its score on holistic grading.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nzqa.govt.nz/ncea/ncea-exams-and-portfolios/external/grade-score-marking/|title=NCEA External Assessment: Grade Score Marking|website=www.nzqa.govt.nz|language=en-NZ|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref>\n* In the United States, the [[Graduate Record Examination]] (GRE) uses holistic grading.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ets.org/gre/revised_general/scores/how/|title=How the GRE General Test is Scored (For Test Takers)|website=www.ets.org|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Standards-based Education Reform}}\n\n[[Category:School terminology]]\n[[Category:Standards-based education]]\n[[Category:Standardized tests]]\n[[Category:Student assessment and evaluation]]\n[[Category:Civil rights of students]]\n{{edu-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Holistic grading''', in [[Outcome-based education|standards-based education]], is an approach to scoring [[essay]]s using a simple grading structure that bases a grade on a paper's overall quality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/holistic-grading-composition-1690838|title=What Is Holistic Grading?|last=Nordquist|first=Richard|date=March 7, 2017|website=ThoughtCo|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref> This type of grading, which is also described as nonreductionist grading<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Bishop|first=Alan|title=International Handbook of Mathematics Education|last2=Clements|first2=M. A. (Ken)|last3=Keitel-Kreidt|first3=Christine|last4=Kilpatrick|first4=Jeremy|last5=Laborde|first5=Colette|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|year=2012|isbn=978-94-010-7155-0|location=Dordrecht|pages=354-355}}</ref>, contrasts with analytic grading,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cultofpedagogy.com/holistic-analytic-single-point-rubrics/|title=Know Your Terms: Holistic, Analytic, and Single-Point Rubrics|date=2014-05-01|website=Cult of Pedagogy|language=en|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref> which takes more factors into account when assigning a grade. Holistic grading can also be used to assess classroom-based work. Rather than counting errors, a paper is judged holistically and often compared to an [[anchor paper]] to evaluate if it meets a writing standard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://writing.colostate.edu/guides/teaching/commenting/holistic.cfm|title=Holistic Scoring in More Detail|website=writing.colostate.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref>\n\n== Model ==\nWhile analytic grading involves criterion-by-criterion judgments, holistic grading appraises student works as integrated entities. In holistic grading, the learner's performance is approached as a whole entity and it cannot be reduced or divided into several component performances. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Joughin|first=Gordon|title=Assessment, Learning and Judgement in Higher Education|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|year=2008|isbn=978-1-4020-8904-6|location=Cham|pages=48}}</ref> Here, teachers are required to consider specific aspects of the student's answer as well as the quality of the whole.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Franck|first=Olof|title=Assessment in Ethics Education: A Case of National Tests in Religious Education|publisher=Springer|year=2017|isbn=978-3-319-50768-2|location=Cham, Switzerland|pages=72}}</ref> \n\nHolistic grading operates by distinguishing satisfactory performance from one that is simply adequate or outstanding.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Projects using holistic grading==\nMany institutions use holistic grading when evaluating student writing as part of a graduation requirement.<ref name=\":0\" /> Some examples include:\n\n* The [[National Certificate of Educational Achievement]] is the New Zealand graduation certificate, which bases its score on holistic grading.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nzqa.govt.nz/ncea/ncea-exams-and-portfolios/external/grade-score-marking/|title=NCEA External Assessment: Grade Score Marking|website=www.nzqa.govt.nz|language=en-NZ|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref>\n* In the United States, the [[Graduate Record Examination]] (GRE) uses holistic grading.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ets.org/gre/revised_general/scores/how/|title=How the GRE General Test is Scored (For Test Takers)|website=www.ets.org|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Standards-based Education Reform}}\n\n[[Category:School terminology]]\n[[Category:Standards-based education]]\n[[Category:Standardized tests]]\n[[Category:Student assessment and evaluation]]\n[[Category:Civil rights of students]]\n{{edu-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Darwin Naz", "label": "safe", "comment": "m", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Holistic_grading"}
{"title_page": "Belal Muhammad (fighter)", "text_new": "{{for|the Bangladesh independence activist|Belal Muhammad}}\n{{short description|Palestinian-American mixed martial arts fighter}}\n{{Infobox martial artist\n| name = Belal Muhammad\n| other_names = Remember the Name\n| image =  \n| image_size = \n| alt =\n| caption = \n| birth_name = Belal Muhammad\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1988|07|09}}\n| birth_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]], United States\n| residence =\n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=10}}\n| weight = {{convert|170|lb|kg st|abbr=on}}\n| weight_class =  [[Welterweight (MMA)|Welterweight]]\n| reach = 72 in<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ufc.com/fighter/Belal-Muhammad?id=|title=Belal Muhammad - Official UFC Profile|publisher=UFC.com|accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n| style = \n| stance = \n| fighting_out_of = [[Chicago, Illinois]], United States\n| team = Roufousport MMA Academy and Chicago fight team\n| rank = Brown belt in [[Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu]] <small>under Daniel Wanderley</small><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BUfCXCngQnC|title=\"(...) I was promoted to purple belt today!!!! (...)\"|publisher=Instagram|author=Belal Muhammad (@bullyb170)|date=May 24, 2017|accessdate=July 9, 2017}}</ref>\n| years_active = 2012-''present''\n| mma_kowin =  4\n| mma_subwin = 1\n| mma_decwin = 11\n| mma_koloss = 1\n| mma_subloss = \n| mma_decloss = 2\n| mma_draw = \n| mma_nc = \n| url =\n| university = [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]]\n| sherdog = 108315\n| footnotes =\n| updated =\n}}\n\n'''Belal Muhammad''' ({{lang-ar|\u0628\u0644\u0627\u0644 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f}} <ref>https://ar.arabsmma.com/\u0628\u0644\u0627\u0644-\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f-\u0645\u0642\u0627\u062a\u0644-ufc-\u064a\u0623\u0645\u0644-\u0623\u0646-\u064a\u0639\u0637\u064a-\u0635\u0648\u0631\u0629-\u0625\u064a\u062c\u0627/</ref>; born July 9, 1988) is an American [[mixed martial arts|mixed martial artist]] currently competing in the UFC [[Welterweight (MMA)|Welterweight]] division. A professional since 2012, he has also competed for [[Bellator MMA|Bellator]] and [[Titan Fighting Championship|Titan FC]].\n\n==Background==\nBorn and raised in [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]], to [[State of Palestine|Palestinian]] parents.<ref>https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2019/09/ufc-242-belal-muhammad-fighting-faith-family</ref>\n\n==Mixed martial arts career==\n\nShortly after a TKO victory over [[Steve Carl]] to become the [[Titan Fighting Championships]] Welterweight Champion, and push his record to 9-0, Muhammad signed with the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bloodyelbow.com/2016/5/27/11799514/welcome-to-the-ufc-belal-muhammad |title=Welcome to the UFC, Belal Muhammad|publisher=bloodyelbow.com |author=Zane Simon|date=2016-05-27|accessdate=2016-05-27}}</ref>\n\n===Ultimate Fighting Championship===\nOn July 7, 2016, at [[UFC Fight Night 90]], Muhammad made his UFC debut, as a short-notice replacement, against [[Alan Jouban]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Alan-Jouban-Gets-New-Opponent-Belal-Muhammad-for-UFC-Fight-Night-on-July-7-106175|title=Alan Jouban gets new opponent Belal Muhammad for UFC Fight Night on July 7|publisher=sherdog.com|author=Tristen Critchfield|date=2016-06-08|accessdate=2016-06-08}}</ref> He lost the fight via unanimous decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2016/07/ufc-fight-night-90-results-alan-jouban-outworks-gutsy-belal-muhammad-for-decision-win|title=UFC Fight Night 90 results: Alan Jouban outworks gutsy Belal Muhammad for decision win|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Brent Brookhouse|date=2016-07-07|accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref> Both participants were awarded ''Fight of the Night'' honors for their performances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/UFC-Fight-Night-Bonuses-Alvarez-Jouban-Muhammad-Munhoz-Collect-3650K-107639|title=UFC Fight Night bonuses: Alvarez, Jouban, Muhammad, Munhoz collect $50K|publisher=sherdog.com|author=Tristen Critchfield|date=2016-07-07|accessdate=2016-07-07}}</ref>\n\nMuhammad next faced [[Augusto Monta\u00f1o]] on September 17, 2016 at [[UFC Fight Night 94]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2016/07/augusto-montano-vs-belal-muhammad-added-to-ufc-fight-night-94-in-texas|title=Augusto Montano vs. Belal Muhammad added to UFC Fight Night 94 in Texas|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=2016-07-21|accessdate=2016-07-21}}</ref> He won the fight via TKO in the third round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2016/09/ufc-fight-night-94-results-belal-muhammad-drops-hands-on-augusto-montano-for-late-stoppage|title=UFC Fight Night 94 results: Belal Muhammad drops hands on Augusto Montano for late stoppage|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Ben Fowlkes|date=2016-09-17|accessdate=2016-09-17}}</ref>\n\nMuhammad was expected to face [[Lyman Good]] on November 12, 2016 at [[UFC 205]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2016/9/23/13034664/ufc-205-fight-card-belal-muhammad-gets-quick-turnaround-fights-lyman-good|title=Belal Muhammad gets quick turnaround, fights Lyman Good at UFC 205|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Shaun Al-Shatti|date=2016-09-23|accessdate=2015-09-23}}</ref> However, on October 24, Good was pulled from the card after being notified by [[USADA]] of a potential anti-doping violation stemming from an out-of-competition drug test sample collected ten days earlier.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2016/10/lyman-good-receives-usada-notice-pulled-from-ufc-205|title=Lyman Good receives USADA notice, pulled from UFC 205|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=2016-10-24|accessdate=2016-10-24}}</ref> He was replaced by [[Vicente Luque]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmamania.com/2016/10/25/13411294/vicente-luque-finds-good-reason-fight-belal-muhammad-ufc-205-mma|title=Vicente Luque has Good reason to face Belal Muhammad at UFC 205|publisher=mmamania.com|author=Jesse Holland|accessdate=2016-10-25|date=2016-10-25}}</ref> Muhammad lost the fight via knockout in the first round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2016/11/ufc-205-results-vicente-luque-ends-belal-muhammads-night-in-79-seconds-with-vicious-ko|title=UFC 205 results: Vicente Luque ends Belal Muhammad's night in 79 seconds with vicious KO|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Steven Marrocco|date=2016-11-12|accessdate=2016-11-12}}</ref>\n\nMuhammad was a short notice replacement and stepped in to face [[Randy Brown (fighter)|Randy Brown]] on February 11, 2017 at [[UFC 208]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/02/with-sullivan-out-randy-brown-now-meets-belal-muhammad-at-ufc-208-in-brooklyn|title=With Sullivan out, Randy Brown now meets Belal Muhammad at UFC 208 in Brooklyn|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=2017-02-04|accessdate=2017-02-04}}</ref> He won the fight by unanimous decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/02/ufc-208-results-belal-muhammad-cruises-past-new-yorks-randy-brown-for-decision-win|title=UFC 208 results: Belal Muhammad cruises past New York's Randy Brown for decision win|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Ben Fowlkes|date=2017-02-11|accessdate=2017-02-11}}</ref>\n\nMuhammad faced [[Jordan Mein]] on July 8, 2017 at [[UFC 213]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://calgaryherald.com/sports/ufc/lethbridge-fighter-jordan-mein-to-battle-belal-muhammad-in-ufc-213|title=Lethbridge fighter Jordan Mein to battle Belal Muhammad in UFC 213|publisher=calgaryherald.com|author=Daniel Austin|date=2017-05-25|accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref> He won the fight by unanimous decision.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/07/ufc-213-results-belal-muhammad-soundly-defeats-jordan-mein-by-unanimous-decision|title=UFC 213 results: Belal Muhammad soundly defeats Jordan Mein by unanimous decision|date=2017-07-09|work=MMAjunkie|access-date=2017-07-09|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nMuhammad was expected to face [[Jesse Taylor]] on November 19, 2017 at [[UFC Fight Night: Werdum vs. Tybura]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/08/belal-muhammad-jesse-taylor-ufc-fight-night-121-australia|title=Belal Muhammad says he's fighting Jesse Taylor at UFC Fight Night 121 in Australia|publisher=mmajunkie.com|date=2017-08-17|accessdate=2017-08-17|author=Staff}}</ref> However, on September 13, it was announced that Taylor was pulled from the card after being notified by [[USADA]] of a potential doping violation stemming from an out-of-competition drug test conducted on August 22.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/TUF-25-Winner-Jesse-Taylor-Facing-AntiDoping-Violation-Removed-from-UFC-Fight-Night-121-126905|title=\u2018TUF 25\u2019 winner Jesse Taylor facing anti-doping violation, removed from UFC Fight Night 121\n|website=sherdog.com|author=Tristen Critchfield|date=2017-09-13|accessdate=2017-09-13}}</ref> He was replaced by [[Tim Means]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mma-today.com/exclusive-tim-means-vs-belal-muhammad-works-ufc-Sydney|title=Tim Means vs. Belal Muhammad in the works for UFC Sydney |author=Shawn Bitter|publisher=mma-today.com|date=2017-10-11|accessdate=2017-10-11}}</ref> Muhammad won the fight via split decision.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/11/ufc-sydney-belal-muhammad-takes-split-tim-means-calls-out-colby-covington|title=UFC Fight Night 121 results: Belal Muhammad takes split from Tim Means, calls out Colby Covington|date=2017-11-19|work=MMAjunkie|access-date=2017-11-19|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nMuhammad was expected to face [[Niko Price]] on June 1, 2018 at [[UFC Fight Night 131]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2018/04/fc-fight-night-131-utica-belal-muhammad-niko-price-julio-arce-daniel-teymur-mma|title=UFC Fight Night 131 in Utica gets two new bouts|website=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=2018-04-11|accessdate=2018-04-11}}</ref> However, Price was removed from the bout on May 22 for undisclosed reasons and replaced by promotional newcomer Chance Rencountre.<ref name=\"Muhammad/Rencountre\">{{cite news|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2018/05/belal-muhammad-chance-rencountre-replaces-niko-price-ufc-fight-night-131-utica-mma|title=Belal Muhammad gets new opponent for UFC Fight Night 131 in Utica|website=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=2018-05-22|accessdate=2018-05-22}}</ref> Muhammad won the fight via unanimous decision.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2018/06/ufc-fight-night-131-results-belal-muhammad-unanimous-decision-chance-rencountre-utica|title=UFC Fight Night 131 results: Belal Muhammad makes easy work of Chance Rencountre|date=2018-06-02|work=MMAjunkie|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nMuhammad was scheduled to meet [[Elizeu Zaleski dos Santos]] on September 22, 2018 at [[UFC Fight Night 137]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2018/07/belal-muhammad-vs-elizeu-zaleski-dos-santos-added-to-ufc-fight-night-137-in-brazil|title=Belal Muhammad vs. Elizeu Zaleski dos Santos added to UFC Fight Night 137 in Brazil|date=2018-07-13|work=MMAjunkie|access-date=2018-07-13|language=en-US}}</ref> However, on September 14, 2018 Muhammad was pulled from the bout and he was replaced by newcomer Luigi Vendramini.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2018/9/14/17862058/undefeated-newcomer-luigi-vendramini-belal-muhammad-elizeu-zaleski-ufc-sao-paulo|title=Undefeated newcomer Luigi Vendramini replaces Belal Muhammad at UFC Sao Paulo|work=MMA Fighting|access-date=2018-09-17}}</ref>\n\nMuhammad faced [[Geoff Neal]] on January 19, 2019 at [[UFC on ESPN+ 1|UFC Fight Night 143]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newsday.com/sports/mixed-martial-arts/ufc-espn-brooklyn-belal-muhammad-1.22980655|title=UFC on ESPN+ in Brooklyn gets its first scheduled bout|publisher=newsday.com|author=Mark La Monica|date=2018-11-06|accessdate=2018-11-06}}</ref> He lost the fight by unanimous decision.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/1/19/18189942/ufc-brooklyn-results-geoff-neal-scores-impressive-win-over-belal-muhammad|title=UFC Brooklyn results: Geoff Neal scores impressive win over Belal Muhammad|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Dave Doyle|date=2019-01-19|accessdate=2019-01-21}}</ref>\n\nMuhammad faced [[Curtis Millender]] on April 13, 2019 at [[UFC 236]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mmadna.nl/snelle-terugkeer-voor-curtis-millender-tegen-belal-muhammad-tijdens-ufc-236-in-atlanta/|title=Snelle terugkeer voor Curtis Millender tegen Belal Muhammad tijdens UFC 236 in Atlanta|last=DNA|first=MMA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-15}}</ref> He won the fight by unanimous decision.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2019/04/ufc-236-results-belal-muhammad-outpoints-curtis-millender|title=UFC 236 results: Belal Muhammad relentless pressure too much for Curtis Millender|date=2019-04-14|website=MMA Junkie|language=en|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n\nMuhammad faced Takashi Sato on September 7, 2019 at [[UFC 242]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmadna.nl/belal-muhammad-vs-takashi-sato-eerste-gevecht-voor-ufc-242-in-abu-dhabi/|title=Belal Muhammad vs. Takashi Sato eerste gevecht voor UFC 242 in Abu Dhabi|last=DNA|first=MMA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref> He won the fight via a rear-naked choke submission in the third round.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cagesidepress.com/2019/09/07/ufc-242-results-muhammad-vs-sato/|title=UFC 242 Results: Belal Muhammad Wraps Up Win Over Takeshi Sato With Third-Round Submission|last=Anderson|first=Jay|date=2019-09-07|website=Cageside Press|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref> This win earned Muhammad his first ''[[List of UFC bonus award recipients|Performance of the Night]]'' award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/9/7/20854693/khabib-nurmagemodov-leads-quartet-of-ufc-242-performance-bonuses|title=Khabib Nurmagemodov leads quartet of UFC 242 performance bonuses|last=Lee|first=Alexander K.|date=2019-09-07|website=MMA Fighting|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref>\n\nMuhammad was expected to face [[Lyman Good]] on April 18, 2020 at [[UFC 249]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/sports/mixed-martial-arts/ufc-239-lyman-good-belal-muhammad-1.41729566|title=UFC 249: Lyman Good vs. Belal Muhammad set for welterweight bout at Barclays Center|author= Mark La Monica|website=newsday.com|access-date=2020-02-11|date=2020-02-12}}</ref> However on April 4, Good pulled out due to injury and it is unknown at this stage if a  replacement would be sought by UFC official.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/04/lyman-good-out-ufc-249-injury-belal-muhammad-opponent|title=Lyman Good out of UFC 249 bout with Belal Muhammad due to injury|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Danny Segura|date=2020-04-04|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMuhammad is a devout [[Muslim]].<ref>https://mmajunkie.com/2018/06/ufc-utica-belal-muhammad-win-during-ramadan-god</ref> \n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]'''\n**[[List of UFC bonus award recipients|Performance of the Night]] (One time) {{small|vs. Takashi Sato}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/9/7/20854693/khabib-nurmagemodov-leads-quartet-of-ufc-242-performance-bonuses|title=Khabib Nurmagemodov leads quartet of UFC 242 performance bonuses|last=Lee|first=Alexander K.|date=2019-09-07|website=MMA Fighting|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref>\n**[[Bonus Awards|Fight of the Night]] (One time)\n*'''[[Titan Fighting Championship]]\n**[[Titan FC#Welterweight Championship|Titan FC Welterweight Championship]] (One time)\n\n*'''[[MMAjunkie.com]]'''\n**2019 January Fight of the Month <small>vs. Geoff Neal</small><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2019/02/fight-of-the-month-january-2019-geoff-neal-belal-muhammad-ufc-espn-plus-1|title=MMAjunkie's 'Fight of the Month' for January: A bloody barnburner|date=February 1, 2019|publisher=mmajunkie.com}}</ref>\n\n==Mixed martial arts record==\n{{MMArecordbox\n|ko-wins=4\n|sub-wins=1\n|ko-losses=1\n|sub-losses=0\n|dec-wins=11\n|dec-losses=2\n}}\n{{MM