0|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref name=\"BB200\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8482014/a-star-is-born-soundtrack-third-week-no-1-album|title='A Star Is Born' Soundtrack Earns Third Week at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart, Future & Juice WRLD Debut at No. 2|work=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=October 28, 2018|accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| 4\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardAlternative|1|artist=Disturbed|rowheader=true|accessdate=October 31, 2018}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardRock|1|artist=Disturbed|rowheader=true|accessdate=October 31, 2018}}\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2018)\n! scope=\"col\"| Position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Germany (Official German Charts)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/charts/single-jahr/for-date-2018|title=Top 100 Single-Jahrescharts|language=German|work=[[GfK Entertainment charts]]|accessdate=December 21, 2018}}</ref>\n| 84\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Disturbed}}\n\n[[Category:2018 albums]]\n[[Category:Disturbed (band) albums]]\n[[Category:Reprise Records albums]]\n", "name_user": "Urgal", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePromotion and release", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolution_(Disturbed_album)"}
{"title_page": "Text Services Framework", "text_new": "{{short description|Software framework and API for input method in Microsoft Windows}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name             = Text Services Framework\n| screenshot       = LangSwitch.gif\n| screenshot_size  = 300px\n| caption          = A standalone Language Bar in {{Nowrap|[[Windows XP]]}}, with language selection menu open \n| developer        = [[Microsoft]]\n| replaces         = Input Method Manager (IMM32)\n| operating system = [[Microsoft Windows]]\n| platform         = [[IA-32]], [[x86-64]], [[Itanium]], [[ARM64]]\n| genre            = [[Software framework]]\n| website          = {{URL|https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/tsf/text-services-framework}}\n}}\nThe '''Text Services Framework (TSF)''' is a [[Component Object Model|COM]] [[Software framework|framework]] and [[API]] in [[Windows XP]] and later [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] [[operating systems]] that supports advanced text input and text processing. The '''Language Bar''' is the core [[user interface]] for Text Services Framework.\n\n==Overview==\nThe Text Services Framework is designed to offer advanced language and [[word processing]] features to applications. It supports features such as multilingual support, keyboard drivers, [[handwriting recognition]], [[speech recognition]], as well as [[Spell checker|spell checking]] and other text and [[natural language processing]] functions. It is also downloadable for older Windows operating systems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.microsoft.com:80/en-us/download/details.aspx?id=11759|title=Download: Platform SDK Redistributable: Microsoft Windows Text Services Framework Redist files|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120713081945/http://www.microsoft.com:80/en-us/download/details.aspx?id=11759|archive-date=June 13, 2012|access-date=July 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Language Bar enables text services to add UI elements to the toolbar and enables these elements when an application has focus. From the Language Bar, users can select the input language, and control keyboard input, handwriting recognition and speech recognition.\n\nThe language bar also provides a direct means to switch between installed languages, even when a non-TSF-enabled application has focus.\n\nStarting with [[Windows XP Tablet PC Edition]] 2005 and [[Windows Vista]], the [[RichEdit]] control  supports the Text Services Framework. [[Windows Speech Recognition]] in Windows Vista is also implemented using the Text Services Framework.\n{{clear|right}}\n{{Wide image|LangBar.gif|705px|Language bar tools \u2013 From left: Language selection menu, spell checking, keyboard layout selection menu, speech recognition, tools, handwriting recognition and drawing pad|100%}}\n\n==Features==\n*TSF is extensible. [[Independent Software Vendor|ISVs]] can write their own text processing feature for TSF.\n*TSF-enabled applications can receive text input from any text service that supports TSF without having to be aware of any details of the text source.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/desktop/TSF/what-is-text-services-framework|title=What is Text Services Framework?|last=|first=|date=May 31, 2018|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 25, 2018}}</ref> Services built using TSF are globally available to any application.\n*TSF enables a text service to store [[metadata]] with a document, a piece of text, or an object within the document. For example, a speech input text service can store sound information associated with a block of text.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/desktop/TSF/why-use-text-services-framework|title=Why Use Text Services Framework?|last=|first=|date=May 31, 2018|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 25, 2018}}</ref>\n*TSF enables text services to provide accurate and complete text conversion, with continuous access to the document buffer. Text services using TSF can avoid separating their functionality into modes for input and modes for editing. This input architecture enables the buffered and accumulating text stream to change dynamically, thereby enabling more efficient keyboard input and text editing.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*TSF is [[Device Independence|device-independent]] and enables text services for multiple input devices including [[Computer keyboard|keyboard]], [[electronic pen]] or stylus, and [[microphone]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==ctfmon and CTF==\n'''ctfmon''' (ctfmon.exe) is a process used to activate the Alternative User Input Text Input Processor (TIP) and also the Microsoft '''Language Bar'''. Ctfmon is also a component of [[Windows XP Tablet PC Edition]], [[Windows Vista]] and [[Windows 7]] which enables advanced user input services in applications (pen and ink, speech etc.).<ref>[http://support.microsoft.com/kb/282599 Ctfmon.exe FAQ in Microsoft Knowledge Base]</ref>\n\n'''CTF''' is an undocumented, insecure protocol involved in TSF which security researchers have observed to be present in Windows versions back to Windows XP.<ref>{{cit web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/vulnerability-in-microsoft-ctf-protocol-goes-back-to-windows-xp/|website=ZDNet|title=Vulnerability in Microsoft CTF protocol goes back to Windows XP|accessdate=August 13, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/2019/08/down-rabbit-hole.html|title=Down the Rabbit Hole|website=Google Project Zero|accessdate=August 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://msdn2.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ms629032.aspx Text Services Framework documentation on MSDN]\n*[http://blogs.msdn.com/tsfaware/Default.aspx?p=2 Text Services Framework blog]\n*[http://support.microsoft.com/kb/306993 How to use the language bar in Windows XP]\n*[http://www.microsoft.com/resources/documentation/windows/xp/all/proddocs/en-us/langbar_overview.mspx?mfr=true The Language Bar in Windows XP]\n*[http://windowshelp.microsoft.com/Windows/en-US/Help/cc452fac-0858-4baf-bc01-005ef3c901751033.mspx Language Bar Overview: Windows Vista Help]\n\n{{Input Method}}\n{{Microsoft APIs}}\n\n[[Category:Windows components]]\n[[Category:Natural language and computing]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Software framework and API for input method in Microsoft Windows}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name             = Text Services Framework\n| screenshot       = LangSwitch.gif\n| screenshot_size  = 300px\n| caption          = A standalone Language Bar in {{Nowrap|[[Windows XP]]}}, with language selection menu open \n| developer        = [[Microsoft]]\n| replaces         = Input Method Manager (IMM32)\n| operating system = [[Microsoft Windows]]\n| platform         = [[IA-32]], [[x86-64]], [[ARM64]]\n| genre            = [[Software framework]]\n| website          = {{URL|https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/tsf/text-services-framework}}\n}}\nThe '''Text Services Framework (TSF)''' is a [[Component Object Model|COM]] [[Software framework|framework]] and [[API]] in [[Windows XP]] and later [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] [[operating systems]] that supports advanced text input and text processing. The '''Language Bar''' is the core [[user interface]] for Text Services Framework.\n\n==Overview==\nThe Text Services Framework is designed to offer advanced language and [[word processing]] features to applications. It supports features such as multilingual support, keyboard drivers, [[handwriting recognition]], [[speech recognition]], as well as [[Spell checker|spell checking]] and other text and [[natural language processing]] functions. It is also downloadable for older Windows operating systems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.microsoft.com:80/en-us/download/details.aspx?id=11759|title=Download: Platform SDK Redistributable: Microsoft Windows Text Services Framework Redist files|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120713081945/http://www.microsoft.com:80/en-us/download/details.aspx?id=11759|archive-date=June 13, 2012|access-date=July 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Language Bar enables text services to add UI elements to the toolbar and enables these elements when an application has focus. From the Language Bar, users can select the input language, and control keyboard input, handwriting recognition and speech recognition.\n\nThe language bar also provides a direct means to switch between installed languages, even when a non-TSF-enabled application has focus.\n\nStarting with [[Windows XP Tablet PC Edition]] 2005 and [[Windows Vista]], the [[RichEdit]] control  supports the Text Services Framework. [[Windows Speech Recognition]] in Windows Vista is also implemented using the Text Services Framework.\n{{clear|right}}\n{{Wide image|LangBar.gif|705px|Language bar tools \u2013 From left: Language selection menu, spell checking, keyboard layout selection menu, speech recognition, tools, handwriting recognition and drawing pad|100%}}\n\n==Features==\n*TSF is extensible. [[Independent Software Vendor|ISVs]] can write their own text processing feature for TSF.\n*TSF-enabled applications can receive text input from any text service that supports TSF without having to be aware of any details of the text source.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/desktop/TSF/what-is-text-services-framework|title=What is Text Services Framework?|last=|first=|date=May 31, 2018|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 25, 2018}}</ref> Services built using TSF are globally available to any application.\n*TSF enables a text service to store [[metadata]] with a document, a piece of text, or an object within the document. For example, a speech input text service can store sound information associated with a block of text.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/desktop/TSF/why-use-text-services-framework|title=Why Use Text Services Framework?|last=|first=|date=May 31, 2018|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 25, 2018}}</ref>\n*TSF enables text services to provide accurate and complete text conversion, with continuous access to the document buffer. Text services using TSF can avoid separating their functionality into modes for input and modes for editing. This input architecture enables the buffered and accumulating text stream to change dynamically, thereby enabling more efficient keyboard input and text editing.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*TSF is [[Device Independence|device-independent]] and enables text services for multiple input devices including [[Computer keyboard|keyboard]], [[electronic pen]] or stylus, and [[microphone]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==ctfmon and CTF==\n'''ctfmon''' (ctfmon.exe) is a process used to activate the Alternative User Input Text Input Processor (TIP) and also the Microsoft '''Language Bar'''. Ctfmon is also a component of [[Windows XP Tablet PC Edition]], [[Windows Vista]] and [[Windows 7]] which enables advanced user input services in applications (pen and ink, speech etc.).<ref>[http://support.microsoft.com/kb/282599 Ctfmon.exe FAQ in Microsoft Knowledge Base]</ref>\n\n'''CTF''' is an undocumented, insecure protocol involved in TSF which security researchers have observed to be present in Windows versions back to Windows XP.<ref>{{cit web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/vulnerability-in-microsoft-ctf-protocol-goes-back-to-windows-xp/|website=ZDNet|title=Vulnerability in Microsoft CTF protocol goes back to Windows XP|accessdate=August 13, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/2019/08/down-rabbit-hole.html|title=Down the Rabbit Hole|website=Google Project Zero|accessdate=August 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://msdn2.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ms629032.aspx Text Services Framework documentation on MSDN]\n*[http://blogs.msdn.com/tsfaware/Default.aspx?p=2 Text Services Framework blog]\n*[http://support.microsoft.com/kb/306993 How to use the language bar in Windows XP]\n*[http://www.microsoft.com/resources/documentation/windows/xp/all/proddocs/en-us/langbar_overview.mspx?mfr=true The Language Bar in Windows XP]\n*[http://windowshelp.microsoft.com/Windows/en-US/Help/cc452fac-0858-4baf-bc01-005ef3c901751033.mspx Language Bar Overview: Windows Vista Help]\n\n{{Input Method}}\n{{Microsoft APIs}}\n\n[[Category:Windows components]]\n[[Category:Natural language and computing]]\n", "name_user": "Ghettoblaster", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Text_Services_Framework"}
{"title_page": "Everett, Washington", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Everett\n|official_name            = City of Everett\n|other_name = [[Lushootseed]]: ''{{lang|lut|d\u1dbb\u0259\u026cig\u02b7\u0259d}}''<ref name=\"Lushootseed1994\">{{cite book |last1=Bates |first1=Dawn |last2=Hess |first2=Thom |last3=Hilbert |first3=Vi |year=1994 |title=d\u1dbb\u0259\u026big\u02b7\u0259d |page=90 |work=Lushootseed Dictionary |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ekq921r1kV0C |publisher=University of Washington Press |isbn=0-295-97323-4 |oclc=843308724 |via=Google Books}}</ref>\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|image_skyline            = Everett Station and Everett skyline, April 2020.jpg\n|image_caption            = [[Everett Station]] and the city skyline\n|image_seal               = Everett logo.svg\n|image_blank_emblem       = Logo of Everett, Washington (horizontal).svg\n|blank_emblem_type        = Logo\n|blank_emblem_size        = 150px\n|image_map                = Snohomish_County_Washington_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Everett_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Everett, Washington\n|pushpin_map              = USA\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location in the United States\n|subdivision_type         = Country\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Washington|County]]\n|subdivision_name         = [[United States]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish]]\n|established_title        = Established\n|established_date         = 1890\n|established_title2       = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]]\n|established_date2        = May 4, 1893\n|government_type          = [[Mayor\u2013council government|Mayor\u2013council]]\n|leader_title             = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name              = Cassie Franklin\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web |title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files |url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_53.txt |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=February 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_sq_mi         = 47.91\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 33.20\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 14.71\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 111262\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes        = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name=\"QuickFacts\"/>\n|population_total         = 103019\n|population_density_sq_mi = 3351.47\n|population_metro         = 3,939,363 (US: [[List of Metropolitan Statistical Areas|15th]])\n|population_rank          = US: [[List of United States cities by population|270th]]<br />WA: 7th\n|population_demonym       = Everettite\n|timezone                 = [[Pacific Time Zone|PST]]\n|utc_offset               = &minus;8\n|timezone_DST             = [[Pacific Daylight Time|PDT]]\n|utc_offset_DST           = &minus;7\n|coordinates              = {{coord|47|58|45|N|122|12|06|W|region:US-WA_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = Zip codes\n|postal_code = 98201, 98203, 98204, 98206, 98207, 98208, 98213<ref>{{cite web |title=Look Up a ZIP Code\u2122 |url=https://tools.usps.com/go/zip-code-lookup.htm |publisher=[[United States Postal Service]] |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n|area_code                = [[Area code 425|425]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 53-22640\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1512198<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov |accessdate=January 31, 2008 |title=US Board on Geographic Names |publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]] |date=October 25, 2007}}</ref>\n|website                  = {{URL|everettwa.gov}}\n|footnotes                = \n|area_total_km2           = 124.09\n|area_land_km2            = 85.98\n|area_water_km2           = 38.11\n|population_density_km2   = 1294.01\n}}\n\n'''Everett''' is the [[county seat]] of and the largest city in [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], United States. It is located {{convert|25|mi|km|0}} north of [[Seattle]] and is one of the main cities in the [[Seattle metropolitan area|metropolitan area]] and [[Puget Sound region]]. Everett is the [[List of cities and towns in Washington|seventh-largest]] city in Washington state by population, with a total of 103,019 residents at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]]. The city is located on a peninsula at the mouth of the [[Snohomish River]] along [[Port Gardner Bay]], an inlet of [[Possession Sound]] (itself part of [[Puget Sound]]).\n\nThe Port Gardner Peninsula was historically inhabited by the [[Snohomish people]], who had a winter village named Hibulb near the mouth of the river. American settlement in the area began with loggers and homesteaders arriving in the 1860s, but plans to build a city were not conceived until 1890. A consortium of East Coast investors seeking to build a major industrial city acquired land in the area and filed a [[plat]]ted for \"Everett\", which they named in honor of [[Everett Colby]], the son of investor [[Charles L. Colby]]. The city was [[municipal incorporation|incorporated]] in 1893, shortly after the arrival of the [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]], and prospered as a major lumber center with several large [[sawmill]]s.\n\nEverett became the county seat in 1897 after a dispute with [[Snohomish, Washington|Snohomish]] contested over several elections and a [[Washington Supreme Court|Supreme Court]] case. The city was the site of labor unrest during the 1910s, which culminated in the [[Everett massacre]] in 1916 that killed several members of the [[Industrial Workers of the World]]. The area was connected by new [[interurban]] railways and highway bridges in the 1920s, transforming it into a major commercial hub, and gained an airport at [[Paine Field]] in 1936.\n\nThe city's economy transitioned away from lumber and towards aerospace after [[World War II]], with the construction of [[Boeing]]'s [[Boeing Everett Factory|aircraft assembly plant]] at Paine Field in 1967. Boeing's presence brought additional industrial and commercial development to Everett, as well as new residential neighborhoods to the south and west of the peninsula that was [[Annexation|annexed]] by the city. Boeing remains the city's largest employer, alongside the [[U.S. Navy]], which has operated [[Naval Station Everett]] since 1992.\n\nEverett remains a major employment center for Snohomish County, but has also become a [[bedroom community]] for Seattle in recent decades. It is connected to Seattle by [[Interstate 5 in Washington|Interstate 5]] and various public transit services at [[Everett Station]], including the [[Sounder commuter rail|Sounder commuter train]], [[Amtrak]], and commuter buses. Everett stages several annual festivals and is also home to minor league sports teams, including the [[Everett Silvertips]] at [[Angel of the Winds Arena]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Early history and settlement===\n[[File:Port Gardner Bay, Everett, Washington, October 1891 (LAROCHE 278).jpeg|thumb|right|Looking south on the [[Seattle and Montana Railroad]] as it passes [[Port Gardner]] Bay in 1891]]\n\nThe [[Port Gardner]] peninsula was originally inhabited by local [[Coast Salish]] tribes who arrived in the region 10,000 years [[before present]] and settled near modern-day Everett approximately 2,000 years [[before present]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=2}} The [[Snohomish people]] lived around local waterways in the [[Possession Sound]] estuary and had a fortified winter village at Hibulb (also called Hebolb) at the mouth of the [[Snohomish River]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=2}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Whitely |first=Peyton |date=March 16, 2005 |title=Aerial photos show 2 very different cities |page=H8 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/aerial-photos-show-2-very-different-cities/ |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref> The first Europeans in the area were explorers from the 1792 [[Vancouver Expedition]], landing on a beach on the modern Everett waterfront on June 4 and claiming the land for [[England]] on the birthday of King [[George III of the United Kingdom|George III]].<ref>{{cite book |author=[[Federal Writers' Project]] |year=1941 |title=The WPA Guide to Washington: The Evergreen State |pages=186\u2013200 |series=[[American Guide Series]] |publisher=[[Works Progress Administration]] |oclc=881468746 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=07PpCAAAQBAJ |via=Google Books |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref> [[Puget Sound]] was further explored and charted ny the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] in 1824 and the [[United States Exploring Expedition]] under [[Charles Wilkes]] in 1841, ahead of a larger American presence in the area.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=4}}<ref name=\"HistoryLink\">{{cite web |last=Oakley |first=Janet |date=July 26, 2005 |title=Everett \u2014 Thumbnail History |url=https://www.historylink.org/file/7397 |work=[[HistoryLink]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Snohomish and other Coast Salish tribes signed the [[Treaty of Point Elliott]] in 1855, which relinquished their lands to the [[Washington Territory|territorial government]] and established the nearby [[Tulalip Indian Reservation]], where they would be relocated.<ref name=\"Herald-125th\">{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=May 9, 2018 |title=City of Everett to celebrate 125th birthday with big party |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/city-of-everett-celebrates-125-years-and-counting/ |work=[[The Everett Herald]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref> The first permanent American settler to arrive on the peninsula was Dennis Brigham, a carpenter from [[Worcester, Massachusetts]], who claimed a {{convert|160|acre|km2|1|adj=on}} [[Homestead Acts|homestead]] and built a cabin for himself. He was joined by several other families on their own homesteads, which included the establishment of a general store and a [[sawmill]] that quickly went out of business.<ref name=\"HistoryLink\"/> Over the next several years a handful of loggers moved to the area, but plans for a settlement were not conceived until 1890.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=7}}\n\nDuring an Alaskan cruise via the [[Inside Passage]] aboard the steamship ''[[Queen of the Pacific]]'' in July 1890, plans were drawn up for an industrial city on Port Gardner Bay by lumberman [[Henry Hewitt Jr.]] and railroad executive [[Charles L. Colby]]. Hewitt and Colby had previously met in [[Wisconsin]], where they operated lumber and maritime businesses, respectively, and in [[Tacoma, Washington]], from which the voyage began. The pair sought to build an industrial center at a site they speculated would be the first ocean port for [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]], to be constructed by [[James J. Hill]], and turn it into a \"[[Pittsburgh]] of the West\".{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=12}}<ref name=\"Times-HewittColby93\">{{cite news |last=Dilgard |first=David |date=April 22, 1993 |title=Odd couple of Hewitt and Colby hatched ambitious plan for Everett |page=F5 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19930422&slug=1697251 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> On August 22, 1890, the [[plat]] for a {{convert|50|acre|m2|adj=on}} townsite on the peninsula was filed by the [[Rucker Brothers]], who had moved north from Tacoma and had more modest plans for the area.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=12}}\n\nBy September, Colby had secured $800,000 in funding from oil magnate [[John D. Rockefeller]] and his railroad associate [[Colgate Hoyt]] to begin acquiring land while avoiding property speculators.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=12}} The Hewitt\u2013Colby syndicate decided to use a name without an identifiable location, naming their planned city after [[Everett Colby]], the fifteen-year-old son of investor Charles L. Colby, who had displayed a \"prodigious appetite\" at a group dinner.<ref name=\"Times-HewittColby93\"/> The [[Everett Land Company]] was incorporated in [[Pierce County, Washington|Pierce County]] on November 19, 1890, and acquired {{convert|434.15|acre|sqkm}} of property from the Rucker Brothers a week later.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=15}} Several businesses had already been established on the peninsula, generally dividing themselves between the Bayside facing Port Gardner and Riverside facing the Snohomish River.<ref>{{cite news |last=Humphrey |first=Robert |date=August 14, 1991 |title=Boom times coming in Everett? We've been that route before |page=F2 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> The Rucker Brothers' plat was withdrawn after an agreement to donate half of their holdings was reached with Hewitt, who promised a series of industrial developments under the \"Remarkable Document\", which was also used to acquire property from other landowners in the area.{{sfnp|Whitfield|1926|p=314}}{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=103}}\n\nEverett gained its first businesses in early 1891, as the new settlement on the Snohomish River attracted land speculators and commitments to build lumber mills and other industrial enterprises.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=16}} The first [[post office]] opened in July at a [[general store]] on the bayfront, where the [[Seattle and Montana Railroad]] was later built in October. By the end of the year, Everett had gained its first school, [[Western saloon|saloon]], church, and [[sawmill]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=17}} The Swalwell Brothers had begun selling property in Riverside along Hewitt Avenue, which was laid {{convert|100|ft|m}} wide and became the main east\u2013west thoroughfare from the riverfront when it was completed in June 1892.{{sfnp|Dorpat|McCovy|1998|p=153}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Burden |first1=Bill |last2=Dorpat |first2=Paul |date=December 20, 1988 |title=Everett: Growth of a late bloomer |page=C6 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> The Everett Land Company did not initially organize a municipal government, leaving local issues to be resolved by a \"citizen's committee\" formed by 21 residents on March 21, 1892.{{sfnp|Whitfield|1926|p=335}} The area had an estimated population of 5,000 by the end of the year, shortly before the completion of the Great Northern Railway across [[Stevens Pass]] on January 6, 1893. The railroad did not terminate in Everett as originally hoped, instead continuing along the shoreline of Puget Sound to [[Seattle]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=20\u201321}}\n\n===Incorporation and early years===\n[[File:Port Gardner Bay, Everett, ca 1905 (CURTIS 70).jpeg|thumb|right|The Everett waterfront, {{circa}} 1905]]\n\nFollowing the acquisition of tidelands on the waterfront, which had been in dispute, the Everett Land Company allowed for a municipal government to be formed.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=20\u201321}} The initial city boundaries were set by the company to avoid taxing the industrial areas and exclude the town of [[Lowell, Everett, Washington|Lowell]], which pre-dated Everett.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=20\u201321}} On April 27, 1893, the citizens of Everett voted 670\u201399 in favor of [[Municipal incorporation|incorporating]] as a city, and elected Thomas Dwyer as [[mayor]].<ref>{{cite news |date=April 29, 1893 |title=The Everett Election |page=1 |work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47971884/the-everett-election/ |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> The incorporation was certified by the [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]] government on May 4, 1893.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=20\u201321}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Riddle |first=Margaret |date=February 27, 2010 |title=Everett incorporates on May 4, 1893. |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/9324 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> The city's privately owned [[streetcar]] system launched on July 3, 1893, with lines connecting the Hewitt Avenue commercial district to mills, [[smelter]]s, and areas as far as Lowell.<ref>{{cite web |last=Labovitch |first=Lisa |date=December 11, 2019 |title=Everett's Streetcars |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/20935 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Everett Land Company ran into financial trouble within months of the city's incorporation as the impact of the national [[Panic of 1893|economic depression]] was felt in the region. The company's investment into the [[Monte Cristo, Washington|Monte Cristo]] area yielded ore of poorer quality than expected and it was unable to meet the promises in the \"Remarkable Document\", which was amended several times with the Rucker Brothers, by then junior partners in the company.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=119}} Rockefeller called his investment into question and appointed advisory Frederick Gates to begin divestment while Colby and Hoyt remained as the leaders of the company.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=119}} Several of the major businesses in Everett closed or failed during the three-year height of the economic depression, but work on [[Alexander McDougall (ship designer)|Alexander McDougall]]'s [[Whaleback]] was finished with the launch of {{SS|City of Everett}} in October 1894, the largest to be built on Puget Sound at the time.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=23}} The Everett Women's Book Club was established in 1894 and opened the city's first [[hospital]] and [[public library]], which would later expand into the [[Everett Public Library]] system.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=April 14, 2019 |title=Everett's museum salutes book club celebrating 125 years |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everetts-museum-salutes-book-club-celebrating-125-years/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDespite the economic turmoil, Everett continued to grow with the addition of new businesses as the area's lumber activities increased.{{sfnp|Whitfield|1926|pages=355\u2013356}} Other industries also expanded in Everett, including a local [[cannery]], a [[brick]] factory, and several ore [[smelter]]s.{{sfnp|Whitfield|1926|p=355}} The discovery of new mineral deposits in Monte Cristo fueled a population boom, along with the completion of the [[Everett and Monte Cristo Railway]] under the ownership of Rockefeller.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=124\u2013125}} The city also benefited from the [[Klondike Gold Rush]], building several [[steamboat]]s to transport prospectors and entrepreneurs.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=124\u2013125}}\n\nIn its early years, Everett launched a campaign to become [[county seat]] by replacing [[Snohomish, Washington|Snohomish]], which had waned in importance following the completion of several railroads serving other cities in the county. An election to determine which city would be named county seat was scheduled for November 6, 1894, beginning a heated debate by citizens and newspapers.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=121\u2013122}} The initial count by the commissioners was announced on December 19 in Everett's favor, amid accusations of fraud and bought votes from both sides. Following an appeal from Snohomish, thee [[Washington Supreme Court]] declared the result to be invalid and blocked the move, but a recount by the commissioners in October 1895 remained in Everett's favor.{{sfnp|Whitfield|1926|pages=136\u2013137}} A long legal battle was fought between the two cities and was decided in October 1895 by the Supreme Court, who ruled that Everett would become county seat per the legal and binding recount.{{sfnp|Whitfield|1926|p=139}} In January 1897, the county government's records were moved by wagons from Snohomish to Everett, where a three-story [[courthouse]] was opened on February 1, 1898.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=121\u2013122}}{{sfnp|Whitfield|1926|p=140}}\n\n===Milltown and labor unrest===\n[[File:everettwaterfront.jpg|thumb|A [[Weyerhaeuser]] lumber mill on the Everett waterfront, seen in the early 20th century]]\n\nAfter outside investors withdrew in the Everett Land Company, its holdings were transferred in 1899 to the [[Everett Improvement Company]], controlled by James J. Hill and his trusted associate John T. McChesney.{{sfnp|Whitfield|1926|pages=356\u2013357}} [[Friedrich Weyerh\u00e4user]] acquired Hill's timberland holdings in the Pacific Northwest and chose Everett for the site of his major lumber mill, which opened in 1902. By the end of the decade, Everett had 11 lumber mills, 16 [[wood shingle|shingle]] mills, and 17 combined mills\u2014surpassing every other city in the state and earning it the nicknames of \"Milltown\" and the \"City of Smokestacks\".{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=135\u2013136}} The [[Weyerhaeuser Company]] opened its larger second mill, named Mill B, on the Snohomish River in April 1915 with the ability to process 1,000,000 [[board feet]] of timber and a {{convert|203|ft|m|adj=mid}} smokestack.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=36}}\n\nThe city gained its first [[interurban]] railway in 1903 with the opening of the [[Everett\u2013Snohomish Interurban|Snohomish Interurban]]. It was then followed by the [[Seattle\u2013Everett Interurban Railway|Seattle Interurban]] on May 2, 1910, which ran hourly on an inland route via [[Alderwood Manor, Washington|Alderwood Manor]].{{sfnp|Whitfield|1926|pages=373\u2013374}} Everett became a first-class city in 1907 and had a population of nearly 25,000 residents by 1910, a quarter of whom were foreign-born. A major lumber boom began following the [[1906 San Francisco earthquake]], which created a high demand for West Coast wood products as the city was rebuilt.<ref name=\"HistoryLink\"/> Everett itself suffered from a major fire on August 2, 1909, that destroyed 12 buildings, including the county courthouse.<ref>{{cite web |last=Riddle |first=Margaret |date=August 16, 2006 |title=Fire destroys the Snohomish County Courthouse in Everett on August 2, 1909. |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/7889 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> The city's growth was not stopped by the fire and a [[Snohomish County Courthouse|new county courthouse]] opened in 1910 alongside the [[Everett High School (Washington)|Everett High School]] campus.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=156}} Everett voters approved a new city charter in 1912 that reorganized the city government into a three-commissioner council with a ceremonial [[mayor]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=34\u201335}}\n\nDuring the first decade of the 20th century, workers at mills and other factories began organizing [[labor union]]s under the Everett Central Trades Council, which had 27 member trades and six unions by 1901. The council had 25 unions by 1907 and became affiliated with the [[American Federation of Labor]], using its influence to stage strikes and work stoppages that resulted in wage increases and safer conditions at mills, where 35 workers had died in 1909.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=30\u201332}}{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=151}} Everett was also home to local [[socialist]] groups and organizers, who published the ''Labor Journal'' and ''The Commonwealth'' on a weekly basis until 1914.<ref name=\"HL-Massacre\">{{cite web |last=Riddle |first=Margaret |date=December 18, 2011 |title=Everett Massacre (1916) |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/9981 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Several survivors of the September 1907 [[Bellingham riots|anti-Indian riots]] in [[Bellingham, Washington|Bellingham]] settled in Everett for two months, but were beaten and forcefully evicted by a mob.<ref>{{cite news |date=November 30, 2019 |title=Looking back: Everett mob terrorizes immigrant mill workers |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/looking-back-everett-mob-terrorizes-immigrant-mill-workers/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city's labor unrest culminated in the 1916 [[Everett massacre]], the deadliest event in Pacific Northwest labor history. A strike of [[shingle weaver]]s began at local mills in May 1916 and continued into the summer with violent attacks from mill owners, which attracted attention from the [[Industrial Workers of the World]] (IWW), a radical socialist union who provided speakers at Everett events.<ref name=\"HL-Massacre\"/>{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=174\u2013175}} The city government passed a new ordinance to restrict street speaking as a result of tensions between the IWW and county sheriff [[Donald McRae (sheriff)|Donald McRae]], who armed a local militia and beat 41 union members who were attempting to enter the city by boat on October 30, 1916.<ref name=\"Herald-Massacre100\">{{cite news |last1=Stevick |first1=Eric |last2=Muhlstein |first2=Julie |date=November 3, 2016 |title=100 years after Everett Massacre we're still learning more |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/100-years-after-the-everett-massacre-were-still-learning-more/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> The incident drew anger from union members and other Everett citizens, prompting 300 IWW members to travel on the steamers ''[[Verona (steamship)|Verona]]'' and ''[[Calista (steamboat)|Calista]]'' from Seattle to Everett on November 5, 1916, when they were confronted at the docks by McRae and his posse of 200 citizen deputies, who feared violence and arson from the group.<ref name=\"HL-Massacre\"/><ref name=\"Herald-Massacre97\">{{cite news |date=November 4, 2013 |title=97 years since 'bloody Sunday,' the Everett Massacre |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/97-years-since-bloody-sunday-the-everett-massacre/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs the ''Verona'' attempted to dock, McRae and several IWW members engaged in a heated debate before a shot was fired by an unknown person. After several minutes of gunfire, five people on the ''Verona'' were killed and two deputies on the dock had been mortally wounded from [[friendly fire]]; an unofficial death toll of twelve IWW members was determined from the recovery of underwater bodies.<ref name=\"HL-Massacre\"/> The ''Verona'', which had nearly capsized as its passengers rushed away from the dock, returned to Seattle with the ''Calista'', which had not attempted to land in Everett.<ref name=\"Herald-Massacre100\"/> At least 50 people were injured, including McRae, and 297 were arrested in Everett and Seattle.<ref>{{cite news |date=November 6, 1916 |title=7 Killed, 50 Injured As Citizens' Posse Battles I. W. W. Mob |page=1 |work=[[San Francisco Examiner]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48042141/everett-massacre-7-killed-50-injured/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Only one IWW member, Thomas Tracy, was ultimately tried and found not guilty of first-degree murder after a two-month trial.<ref name=\"Herald-Massacre100\"/>\n\nThe shingle weavers strike ended on November 10, 1916, with no concessions from the mill owners, and local residents turned against the IWW for escalating the dispute.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=174\u2013175}} The labor tensions subsided with the entry of the U.S. into [[World War I]], despite an attempted comeback by the IWW in disrupting logging for the war effort.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=180}} As a result of the massacre, the state government outlawed citizens from advocating for [[anarchy]] or violent overthrow; the law was not repealed until 1999.<ref>{{cite news |date=May 6, 1999 |title=Anarchism is legal again in state |page=B4 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19990506&slug=2959132 |work=The Seattle Times |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> The massacre was largely unacknowledged by local residents until the late 20th century, when book accounts were published and a [[historic marker]] was installed overlooking the former docks.<ref name=\"Herald-Massacre100\"/><ref name=\"Herald-Massacre97\"/>\n\n===Inter-war years===\n[[File:Monte Cristo Hotel, Everett, Washington (4861196624).jpg|thumb|right|The [[Monte Cristo Hotel]], completed in 1925]]\n\nThe local timber industry continued its boom and bust cycle into the 1920s, suffering from price swings but benefiting from the [[1923 Great Kanto earthquake|1923 Japanese earthquake]] to supply lumber and the opening of the [[Panama Canal]]. The Clough-Hartley shingle mill claimed to be the largest in the world, producing 1.5 million wood shingles per day; the city produced approximately 4.5 million shingles and 3.5 million board feet of lumber per day in 1920.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=184\u2013185}} The [[Port of Everett]] was created on July 13, 1918, to enable public ownership of the waterfront and promote economic development in the city. By the end of the 1920s, the port had opened the county's first airport on [[Ebey Island]] and acquired the 14th Street Dock and [[Jetty Island]] from the Everett Improvement Company.<ref>{{cite news |last=Podsada |first=Janice |date=July 3, 2018 |title=A century ago, a publicly owned port was a radical notion |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/a-century-ago-a-publicly-owned-port-was-a-radical-notion/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=July 3, 2018 |title=Port of Everett history at a glance |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/port-of-everett-history-at-a-glance/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> The city also acquired the private water system in 1915 and replaced it with a new supply from the [[Sultan River]] basin that was fully activated four years later.{{sfnp|Dorpat|McCovy|1998|p=207}}\n\nEverett's central [[commercial district]] grew from a handful of businesses into a busy downtown during the 1920s, including the construction of several multi-story office and retail buildings, two [[junior high school]]s, a [[Everett City Hall|modern city hall]], and additions to the city's two hospitals.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=192}} The six-story [[Monte Cristo Hotel]] opened in 1925 with 140 guest rooms, elaborate furnishings, and a [[banquet hall]] that would host civic functions for several decades.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=192}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Bruestle |first=Sara |date=April 16, 2018 |title=History of a hotel: Everett's dreams gave rise to Monte Cristo |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/history-of-a-hotel-everetts-dreams-gave-rise-to-monte-cristo/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> The county's first radio station, KFBL (now [[KRKO]]), began broadcasting on August 25, 1922, and was among the earliest in the state.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=197}} In 1924, a third mill at the Weyerhaeuser complex, which employed 1,500 people and contributed to $28.125&nbsp;million in annual timber output by the end of the decade.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=45}}\n\nThe widespread adoption of the automobile lead to the construction of new roads out of Everett and Snohomish County to neighboring regions. The earliest iteration of the [[Stevens Pass Highway]] opened in 1925, providing the second automobile crossing of the [[Cascade Mountains]] in the state and access to new timberland and other resources.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=211}} The highway was later improved with the opening of the [[Hewitt Avenue Trestle]] in 1939, crossing the Gnomish River and Ebey Island on an elevated viaduct.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=253}} The [[Pacific Highway (United States)|Pacific Highway]] (part of [[U.S. Route 99]]) was completed in 1927 with the opening of four bridges across the Snohomish River delta to [[Marysville, Washington|Marysville]].{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=207\u2013209}} Everett was also among the first cities in the U.S. to replace its streetcars with [[transit bus|buses]], doing so in 1923,{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=211}} and the last train on the Seattle\u2013Everett Interurban ran on February 20, 1939.<ref name=\"Herald-Interurban\">{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=December 2, 2019 |title=The Interurban Railway: Everett's first rapid transit line |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/the-interurban-railway-everetts-first-rapid-transit-line/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett experienced a major rise in unemployment as demand for lumber products dropped, with an estimated 32 percent of [[property tax]]es left unpaid in 1932. Charitable organizations in the area set up relief programs and provided work for unemployed residents, including commencing work on a {{convert|185|acre|ha|adj=mid}} park and [[golf course]] in North Everett that later became [[American Legion Memorial Park]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=50\u201351}} The federal [[Works Progress Administration]] employed local workers to construct a new downtown [[public library]], develop parks, expand schools, and improve streets.<ref name=\"Herald-WPAForest\">{{cite news |date=February 15, 2020 |title=Looking back: 1930s WPA project transformed Forest Park |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/looking-back-1930s-wpa-project-transformed-forest-park/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> The works program also built a new county airport, [[Paine Field]], southwest of Everett that opened in 1936 to serve commercial uses. The airport was appropriated for military use during [[World War II]], but was later turned over to county ownership.<ref name=\"HistoryLink\"/>{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=53}} The war also brought a new [[shipyard]] operated by the [[Everett-Pacific Shipbuilding & Dry Dock Company]], which employed 6,000 workers and closed in 1949.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=266}}\n\n===Boeing and suburban development===\n[[File:Boeing 747 rollout (3).jpg|thumb|right|The rollout of the first [[Boeing 747]] from the [[Boeing Everett Factory|Everett assembly plant]] in September 1968]]\n\nDowntown Everett continued to grow as the regional commercial center following the end of the war, with four large [[department store]]s and dozens of smaller retailers and restaurants in a six-block radius of Hewitt Avenue and Colby Avenue. The population boom triggered construction of new housing areas around the peninsula and new schools, with enrollment in the [[Everett School District]] doubling to 11,600 from 1941 to 1951.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=63}} The school district also built [[Everett Memorial Stadium]] in 1947 to host high school sports and civic events.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=315}} A new [[public housing]] complex, Baker Heights, was built in 1943 to house military personnel amid a local shortage, providing a total of 1,275 apartments that later went to low-income families.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=August 25, 2019 |title=Baker Heights: Tight-knit Everett community must scatter |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/baker-heights-a-tight-knit-community-must-scatter/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe first suburban-style [[supermarket]] opened on Evergreen Way (part of U.S. Route 99) in 1950 and was followed by [[strip mall]]s and similar [[big box store]]s along the highway by the end of the decade.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=72}} The areas surrounding the highway were developed into suburban housing and made up the bulk of the city's then-largest [[annexation]], of {{convert|900|acre|ha}} near Madison Street on December 31, 1959. A second round of South Everett annexations completed in 1961 and 1972 added {{convert|10,300|acre|ha}} to the city, including the Lowell area, and boosted its population to over 50,000.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=72}}<ref name=\"Annexations\">{{cite map |date=March 2019 |title=City of Everett Annexations By Year |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/15379/ANNEXATION-HISTORY-as-of-3122019-PDF |publisher=City of Everett Department of Community, Planning & Economic Development |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Everett's second high school, [[Cascade High School (Everett, Washington)|Cascade High School]], opened in 1961 to serve the annexed areas.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=72}} The new suburban neighborhoods were linked via [[Interstate 5 in Washington|Interstate 5]], which opened from North Seattle to Everett in February 1965 and bypassed U.S. Route 99 with a six-lane freeway roughly following the former interurban railway.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=77}}{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=332}} The freeway was extended around the east side of Downtown Everett in January 1968 and Interstate 5 was completed within Washington with the opening of the section connecting the city to Marysville in May 1969.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=81}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Mansfield |first=Tom |date=May 14, 1969 |title=I-5 Opened Today |page=A1 |work=The Everett Herald}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Boeing Company]] opened its first Everett factory in 1943 as part of its wartime production for the [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress|B-17]] program. The company moved to the Everett\u2013Pacific Shipyard in 1956 and grew to be the city's largest single employer by 1965, with 1,728 employees.<ref name=\"Herald-BoeingTimeline\">{{cite news |last=Dominguez |first=Alejandro |date=March 23, 2012 |title=Boeing's history in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/boeings-history-in-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Boeing approved early development of its [[Boeing 747]] passenger jetliner in March 1966 and purchased {{convert|780|acre|ha}} near Paine Field in June to build its [[Boeing Everett Factory|assembly plant]] for the plane, which would become the world's first \"jumbo jet\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=January 22, 2016 |title=How Boeing's incredible 747 launched the Everett factory |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/how-boeings-incredible-747-launched-the-everett-factory/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Work on the first 747 plane, named the \"City of Everett\", began at the unfinished factory in January 1967.<ref name=\"Herald-Boeing50\">{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=May 22, 2017 |title=50 history-making years of building Boeing jets in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/boeing-has-built-planes-in-everett-for-50-history-making-years/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> It was unveiled in September 1968 and made its maiden flight on February 9, 1969.<ref>{{cite news |last=Podsada |first=Janice |date=September 30, 2018 |title=50 years ago, they rolled it out: the first Boeing 747 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/50-years-ago-they-rolled-it-out-the-first-boeing-747/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> The Everett factory was expanded several times to accommodate later Boeing programs, including the [[Boeing 767|767]], [[Boeing 777|777]], and [[Boeing 787|787 Dreamliner]].<ref name=\"Herald-Boeing50\"/>\n\nThe impending construction of the Boeing plant triggered a boom in residential and commercial development in Everett and surrounding communities in the late 1960s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Moody |first=Dick |date=June 5, 1966 |title=Monroe, a Residential City, Hopes to Remain That Way |page=34 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> By the end of the decade, Everett had annexed additional areas to stretch the city boundaries west to Mukilteo and south to Silver Lake.<ref name=\"Annexations\"/> A new freeway, [[Washington State Route 526|State Route 526]], was built to connect the plant to Interstate 5 at the Eastmont Interchange, where the [[Everett Mall]] was planned to be built.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=81}} The mall was built in stages, beginning with a [[Sears]] store in February 1969 and ending with a grand opening on October 9, 1974, with 14 stores.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=83}} The development of the mall was slowed by a local economic crash that began with the cancellation of Boeing's [[Boeing 2707|supersonic jetliner]] program in 1971 and financial issues for airliners that affected sales of the Boeing 747. The Everett factory reduced its number of employees from 25,000 to 4,700, causing a spike in local unemployment rates and an exodus of former employees; the Everett School District closed three of its elementary schools as enrollment dropped by 3,000 students.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=83}}{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=339\u2013340}}\n\nDuring the 1970s, several of Everett's surviving lumber and pulp mills closed as they were too costly to renovate or replace, marking the end of the \"Mill Town\". Lowell's pulp mill closed in 1972 and was followed by Weyerhaeuser's Mill B in 1979 and Mill A in 1981.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=85}} The final Weyerhaeuser mill closed in 1992, leaving the [[Scott Paper Company]] as the last remaining paper mill in Everett until its closure in 2012.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=85}}<ref name=\"Herald-KimClark\">{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Debra |date=March 30, 2012 |title=Kimberly-Clark mill is part of the Everett we've lost |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/kimberly-clark-mill-is-part-of-the-everett-weve-lost/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The city instead deepened its connections to the aerospace and high-tech industry, opening facilities in the 1980s for [[Hewlett-Packard]], [[Fluke Corporation|Fluke]], and other electronics firms.<ref name=\"Times-WH1992\">{{cite news |last=Nelson |first=Robert T. |date=March 29, 1992 |title=Funeral bells toll for Mill Town Everett |page=B1 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19920329&slug=1483696 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Downtown Everett also declined as an activity center as retailers and car dealerships moved to suburban areas, despite the opening of a large [[hotel]] and several high-rise office building.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=88\u201390}} A city landfill southeast of Downtown Everett was turned into a recycling plant for millions of rubber [[tire]]s, nicknamed \"Mount Firestone\", which caught fire in September 1984 and burned for seven months as the incident gained national media attention.<ref>{{cite web |last=Riddle |first=Margaret |date=December 8, 2009 |title=The Everett Tire Fire begins on September 24, 1984. |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/9233 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Naval base and downtown revival===\n[[File:Naval Station Everett.jpg|thumb|right|[[Naval Station Everett]], a U.S. Navy facility opened in 1994 under the [[Strategic Homeport]] program]]\n\nBoeing recovered from its sales slump and increased employment at its Everett plant to 18,000 people in 1980 as it prepared to unveil the [[Boeing 767]], the second family of jetliners to be produced in Everett. A neighboring [[industrial park]] along Seaway Boulevard was developed in the 1980s as demand for commercial space in the city grew.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=88\u201390}} The Port of Everett began developing a new shopping and retail complex on Port Gardner Bay as it looked to diversify away from industrial uses, but the project ran into financial issues as Everett-area employers failed or laid off workers amid an aerospace slump in 1981\u201382.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=88\u201390}} The [[U.S. Navy]] selected the former shipyard site on Port Gardner Bay as the site of a new military base in 1984 under the [[Strategic Homeport]] program.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cowley |first=Geoffrey |date=November 7, 1984 |title=Everett says 'yes' to Navy by a margin of more than 2-to-1 |page=B10 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> [[Naval Station Everett]] and its {{convert|1,600|ft|m|adj=mid}} pier were constructed between 1987 and 1994 alongside auxiliary facilities located to the north in [[Smokey Point, Washington|Smokey Point]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Brooks |first=Diane |date=June 5, 1992 |title=The Navy's in port: three ships greeted at Everett's new base |page=E1 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hendricks |first=Tyche |date=June 5, 1995 |title=Eagerly awaiting stores' opening\u2014Navy exchange, commissary ready |page=B1 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19950605&slug=2124724 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> The first ships arrived in September 1994, and Naval Station Everett was the long-term home of several [[aircraft carrier]]s, including the {{USS|Abraham Lincoln|CVN-72|6}}.<ref>{{cite news |last=Clutter |first=Stephen |date=January 9, 1997 |title=Bringing home the future: The Lincoln, with crew of 3,200 is first carrier permanently assigned to Everett |page=B1 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref>\n\nThe city underwent an urban revival in the 1990s, fueled by the upcoming centennial celebrations and a third expansion of the Boeing plant for the [[Boeing 777]] program. The plant expansion was completed in 1993, enlarging the world's largest building by volume to {{convert|96|acre|ha}}.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=355}}<ref name=\"NYT-1990\">{{cite news |last=King |first=Harriet |date=May 13, 1990 |title=Focus: The I-5 Corridor; A Lively New Washington Growth Area |page=A1 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/05/13/realestate/focus-the-i-5-corridor-a-lively-new-washington-growth-area.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"DJC-2001\">{{cite news |last=Stephens |first=Terry |date=August 9, 2001 |title=Energizing Everett |url=https://www.djc.com/news/re/11124627.html |work=[[Seattle Daily Journal of Commerce]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Everett's inner neighborhoods grew with new residential and commercial development, including Downtown Everett, where a beautification and restoration program had begun in the 1980s.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=349}} The downtown program included a [[road diet]] for Colby Avenue, [[Flower box|planter boxes]] on widened sidewalks, and new parks.<ref name=\"PI-Life97\">{{cite news |last=Carter |first=Don |date=July 12, 1997 |title=New life breathes in old mill town |page=D1 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Tewkesbury |first=Don |date=October 30, 1989 |title=Everett beautifies with flower planters |page=B1 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer}}</ref> Several new office buildings were completed in Downtown Everett, including the 11-story [[Key Bank Tower (Everett, Washington)|Everett Mutual Tower]], and other historic buildings were renovated or restored for new businesses and organizations.<ref name=\"PI-Life97\"/>{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=370}} The city also annexed {{convert|465|acre|ha}} near Paine Field in March 2000, bringing Everett's population to over 91,000.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brooks |first=Diane |date=March 1, 2000 |title=Everett voters approve West Casino annexation |page=A23 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> Everett was recognized as an [[All-America City]] by the [[National Civic League]] in 2002 and has been a member of the [[Tree City USA]] program since 1993.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=September 13, 2012 |title=Remembering Everett's All-America summer of 2002 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/remembering-everetts-all-america-summer-of-2002/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=March 27, 2012 |title=Garden club has left a vibrant legacy all around Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/garden-club-has-left-a-vibrant-legacy-all-around-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett was identified as a key transport hub under the regional [[Sound Transit]] system, which was approved in a ballot measure in 1996 after an earlier failed attempt. The transit agency opened a multimodal train and bus center, [[Everett Station]], in February 2003 to replace scattered downtown facilities for [[Amtrak]], [[Greyhound Lines|Greyhound]], and local transit. It would also serve as the northern terminus for [[Sounder commuter rail]] and [[Sound Transit Express]] buses, which both connect Everett to Seattle.<ref name=\"Times-Station03\">{{cite news |last=Whitley |first=Peyton |date=January 1, 2003 |title=City's new terminal has amassed transit depots in single location |page=I17 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20030101&slug=station01n |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808042501/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20030101&slug=station01n |archivedate=August 8, 2014 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> A {{convert|6|mi|km|spell=in|adj=mid}} section of Interstate 5 was rebuilt by the state government from 2005 to 2008 by adding new lanes and improving several interchanges at a cost of $263&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nohara |first=Yoshiaki |date=May 28, 2008 |title=I-5 work not done, but is helping traffic |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/i-5-work-not-done-but-is-helping-traffic/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Everett remains home to one of the most congested stretches of I-5, which is also among the worst in the United States for travel delays.<ref name=\"Times-Traffic18\">{{cite news |last=Lindblom |first=Mike |date=February 5, 2018 |title=It's worse than you think: Everett leads the nation in traffic congestion, report says |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/transportation/its-worse-than-you-think-everett-leads-the-nation-in-traffic-congestion-report-says/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDowntown Everett remained a center for new development in the 2000s and 2010s, with several projects completed by local governments and private developers. The [[Everett Events Center]] (now Angels of the Winds Arena) opened in 2003 to serve as an indoor sports venue, [[convention center]], and community [[ice rink]].<ref name=\"Times-Arena03\">{{cite news |last=Tuinstra |first=Rachel |date=September 24, 2003 |title=A $71.5 million venue represents 'a big leap of faith' for the city |page=H28 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20030924&slug=center24n |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004084051/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20030924&slug=center24n |archivedate=October 4, 2012 |accessdate=March 25, 2012}}</ref> The county government redeveloped its Everett office campus by building a new administrative center, jail, [[parking garage]], and public [[plaza]] that opened in 2005.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kelly |first=Brian |date=January 1, 2005 |title=The year ahead |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/the-year-ahead/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Whitely |first=Peyton |date=January 12, 2005 |title=New county garage \"doing well\" |page=H10 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> In the 2010s, two new downtown hotels were opened along with several apartment buildings that were encouraged by relaxed zoning policies.<ref name=\"Herald-DTHotel\">{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=October 28, 2016 |title=New downtown Everett hotel sign of changing economy |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/new-downtown-everett-hotel-sign-of-changing-economy/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Herald-DTApartments\">{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=March 22, 2015 |title=102 new apartments opening in downtown Everett this summer |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/102-new-apartments-opening-in-downtown-everett-this-summer/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> As the region's [[Homelessness in Seattle|homeless population]] grew, Everett added two [[supportive housing]] buildings in downtown to provide 150 units of low-income housing with access to social services.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=February 11, 2019 |title=150 units of supportive housing coming to Everett in 2019 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/150-units-of-supportive-housing-coming-to-everett-in-2019/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBoeing selected Everett as the main site of its [[Boeing 787|787 Dreamliner]] and [[Boeing 747-8|747-8]] programs, which did not require major building expansions.<ref name=\"Herald-BoeingTimeline\"/> The company also partnered with the county government to create the [[Future of Flight Aviation Center & Boeing Tour]], an aviation museum at Paine Field that opened in 2005.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wolcott |first=John |date=March 31, 2012 |title=Future of Flight's popularity soars |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/future-of-flights-popularity-soars/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The [[Boeing 777X]] program launched in 2013 with plans to build a wing assembly center adjacent to the Everett plant, which opened in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gates |first=Dominic |date=May 19, 2016 |title=Boeing shows off new 777X wing center |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeing-shows-off-new-777x-wing-center/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Commercial passenger service at Paine Field resumed at a new terminal on March 4, 2019, after earlier plans from the 1980s onward were blocked by nearby residents.<ref name=\"Times-Paine\">{{cite news |last=Blethen |first=Ryan |date=March 5, 2019 |title=How the first day of commercial flights from Paine Field went |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/life/travel/first-commercial-flight-to-take-off-from-everetts-paine-field-today/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=March 6, 2019 |title=Paine airport battle lasted longer than the Thirty Years War |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/paine-airport-battle-lasted-longer-than-the-thirty-years-war/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city government began planning for a major redevelopment of a former landfill on the Snohomish River waterfront in the late 1990s, but the project was stalled as private developers declined to move the project forward.<ref name=\"Herald-Riverfront\">{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=November 3, 2016 |title=Massive Riverfront development begins to rise in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/homes-being-built-in-massive-riverfront-development-in-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The original concept for the {{convert|139|acre|ha|adj=mid}} property was an entertainment center with shopping, housing, offices, and parks. The [[Everett Riverfront|riverfront project]] was ultimately divided into three sections: a southern portion for 235 [[single-family home]]s that was constructed in 2016; a center portion with commercial space, apartments, a movie theater, and a small park; and a northern portion with 190 [[townhome]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=May 3, 2019 |title=Riverfront plan approved, ushering in a new era for Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/riverfront-plan-approved-ushering-in-a-new-era-for-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> A similar redevelopment plan for the Port of Everett's {{convert|65|acre|ha}} on the bayside waterfront, known as Port Gardner Wharf, was shelved in 2007 by the developer's financial issues.<ref>{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=April 21, 2014 |title=Port of Everett prepares new waterfront redevelopment plan |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/port-of-everett-prepares-new-waterfront-redevelopment-plan-2/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> A new development, named Fisherman's Harbor, began construction in 2018 with a hotel, apartments, restaurants, and shops adjacent to the city's public [[marina]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Watanabe |first=Ben |date=April 19, 2018 |title=New Everett hotel will double waterfront rooms in the county |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/new-everett-hotel-will-double-waterfront-rooms-in-the-county/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Providence Regional Medical Center Everett|Providence Regional Medical Center]], formed from a merger of Everett's two hospitals in 1994, completed a major expansion of its North Everett campus in 2011 by opening a 12-story medical tower.<ref name=\"Herald-Providence11\">{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=May 15, 2011 |title=A $460 million gamble |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/a-460-million-gamble/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The first [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|U.S. case]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] was identified in a Snohomish County resident at Providence Regional Medical Center on January 20, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Blethen |first=Ryan |date=February 14, 2020 |title=What it was like for doctors and nurses at an Everett hospital to treat the nation's first novel coronavirus patient |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/what-it-was-like-for-doctors-and-nurses-at-an-everett-hospital-to-treat-the-nations-first-novel-coronavirus-patient/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> As the coronavirus pandemic worsened in the state, mayor Cassie Franklin declared the first shelter-in-place order for Washington state on March 21, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutman |first=David |date=March 21, 2020 |title=Everett orders residents to stay home to slow coronavirus, others call on Inslee to follow suit |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/everett-orders-residents-to-stay-home-to-slow-coronavirus-others-call-on-inslee-to-follow-suit/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Everett - Hewitt Ave.jpg|thumb|right|Hewitt Avenue in Downtown Everett]]\n\nEverett is one of the core cities comprising the [[Seattle metropolitan area]] and is located {{convert|25|mi|km}} north of [[Seattle]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Kirk |date=December 10, 2013 |title=Boeing Looks Around, and a State Worries |page=A16 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/11/us/washington-state-not-ready-to-ponder-future-without-boeing.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> It is located primarily on Port Gardner Peninsula, bordered to the west by [[Port Gardner Bay]] (part of [[Possession Sound]] in the [[Puget Sound]] estuary), and to the north and east by the [[Snohomish River]] delta.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dietrich |first=William |date=May 1, 2005 |title=Port Reform: With homes and offices, trails and tourist stops, waterfronts are finding new life |page=14 |url=http://seattletimes.com/pacificnw/2005/0501/cover.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012091251/http://seattletimes.com/pacificnw/2005/0501/cover.html |archivedate=October 12, 2012 |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The city also encompasses suburban and industrial areas to the south and southwest of the peninsula, which were annexed during the mid-to-late 20th century.<ref name=\"Annexations\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Chircop |first=David |date=May 5, 2008 |title=Everett eyes massive annexation that would boost city's population by 62,000 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-eyes-massive-annexation-that-would-boost-citys-population-by-62000/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Everett has {{convert|11|mi|km}} of freshwater shoreline and {{convert|11|mi|km}} of saltwater shoreline, including public access points at parks and [[boat launch|boat ramps]] on Port Gardner Bay and the Snohomish River.<ref name=\"CAFR2018\"/>{{rp|2}} According to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|48.49|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which {{convert|33.45|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|15.04|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web |title=US Gazetteer files 2010 |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=December 19, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112090031/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |archivedate=January 12, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe city's western boundary with [[Mukilteo, Washington|Mukilteo]] is generally defined by [[Japanese Gulch]] on the edge of the [[Boeing Everett Factory|Boeing Everett Assembly Plant]] and its auxiliary buildings.<ref name=\"BaseMap\">{{cite map |date=April 2019 |title=Everett, Washington Base Map |url=https://www.everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/19039/Basemap |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The southwestern edge of Everett borders an [[unincorporated area]] that includes [[Paine Field]] and the [[Lake Stickney, Washington|Lake Stickney/Mariner]] neighborhoods, which are part of the city's designated [[urban growth boundary|urban growth area]] that extends south towards [[Lynnwood, Washington|Lynnwood]].<ref name=\"MUGA\">{{cite map |date=September 2, 2013 |title=Snohomish County GMA Comprehensive Plan: Municipal Urban Growth Areas |url=https://snohomishcountywa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/8216/Map-3-Municipal-Urban-Growth-Areas-MUGA-11x17 |publisher=Snohomish County |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The southern boundary wraps around [[Silver Lake (Everett, Washington)|Silver Lake]] and follows [[Washington State Route 527|State Route 527]] to [[Washington State Route 96|State Route 96]] at Murphy's Corner, where it borders [[Mill Creek, Washington|Mill Creek]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Alexander |first=Brian |date=September 21, 2005 |title=Hard-fought annexation now just around corner |page=H14 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/hard-fought-annexation-now-just-around-corner/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Everett's boundaries follow various housing subdivisions in the [[Eastmont, Washington|Eastmont]] area before reaching the Snohomish River, which forms the primary eastern border. The northeastern boundary includes portions of [[Smith Island (Washington)|Smith Island]] in the river delta reaching towards [[Marysville, Washington|Marysville]];<ref name=\"BaseMap\"/> a series of highway bridges connect Everett to Marysville to the north and [[Lake Stevens, Washington|Lake Stevens]] to the east by crossing the Snohomish River delta.<ref name=\"WSDOT-Map\">{{cite map |year=2014 |title=Washington State Highways, 2014\u20132015 |url=https://www.wsdot.wa.gov/sites/default/files/2006/06/13/TouristMapFront_withoutHillshade.pdf |inset=[https://www.wsdot.wa.gov/sites/default/files/2017/08/31/highway-map-PugetSound_Full.pdf Puget Sound] |publisher=[[Washington State Department of Transportation]] |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite map |date=March 2013 |title=Snohomish County Urban Growth Areas and Incorporated Cities |url=http://www.snoco.org/docs/scd/PDF/PDS_UGA/County_11x17.pdf |publisher=Snohomish County |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The city boundaries also include {{convert|3,729|acre|ha}} of forestland surrounding [[Lake Chaplain]], a reservoir in the Cascade Mountains that provides part of the municipal water supply.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=May 10, 2015 |title=Trade-off would allow timber harvest at Lake Chaplain |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/trade-off-would-allow-timber-harvest-at-lake-chaplain/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Port Gardner Peninsula was formed during the northward retreat of [[Vashon Glaciation]] during an [[ice age]] 14,000 years before present.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=2}} The underlying soil is generally [[loam]]y and includes gravelly sand in the [[glacial outwash]].<ref name=\"Soil-Survey\">{{cite report |last1=Debose |first1=Alfonso |last2=Klungland |first2=Michael W. |date=July 1983 |title=Soil survey of Snohomish County Area, Washington |pages=4, 13 |url=https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_MANUSCRIPTS/washington/WA661/0/wa661_text.pdf |publisher=[[Natural Resources Conservation Service|U.S. Soil Conservation Service]] |oclc=9975367 |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Everett is located near the [[Puget Sound faults|Southern Whidbey Island Fault]], a shallow [[earthquake fault]] zone that runs near the western edge of the city and was discovered in 1994.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fiege |first=Gale |date=June 15, 2009 |title=South Whidbey fault has potential for major quake |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/south-whidbey-fault-has-potential-for-major-quake/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> In the 1990s, local geologists also found evidence of a [[tsunami]] and [[soil liquefaction]] in deposits under the Snohomish River delta that were not directly connected to the South Whidbey Island Fault.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dietrich |first=Bill |date=July 23, 1996 |title=Hunting for the big one |page=A6 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> The city government established its emergency management and preparedness office in 2002 and conducts regular disaster drills to simulate a potential response.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stevick |first1=Eric |last2=Sheets |first2=Bill |last3=King |first3=Rikki |date=March 11, 2011 |title=Tsunami in the Sound |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/tsunami-in-the-sound/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The southwestern neighborhoods of Everett include several [[ravine]]s formed by local creeks that drain into Port Gardner Bay. The area is also prone to [[mudslide]]s that interrupt passenger and freight service on the railroad that runs along the coastline of the bay.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sheets |first=Bill |date=March 19, 2013 |title=Mudslide trouble spots identified |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/mudslide-trouble-spots-identified/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Other areas of the city drain into the watersheds of the Snohomish River and [[Lake Washington]].<ref>{{cite map |date=January 2020 |title=Drainage Basins & Watersheds |url=https://www.everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/19690/Drain-Basins-11x17 |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Cityscape and neighborhoods===\n\nThe city of Everett maintains an Office of Neighborhoods which facilitate communication between the city and recognized neighborhood associations. The neighborhood associations are independent from the city and have elected leaders who communicate with the city government.<ref>{{cite web |title=Neighborhood Associations |url=https://everettwa.gov/334/Neighborhood-Associations |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Various neighborhoods in Everett have views of the [[Cascades Mountains|Cascade]] and [[Olympic Mountains|Olympic]] mountains, including [[Mount Baker]] and [[Mount Rainier]].<ref name=\"Herald-Hikes\">{{cite news |last=Bruestle |first=Sara |date=September 17, 2017 |title=Urban trails: 10 hiking destinations close to home |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/urban-trails-10-hiking-destinations-close-to-home/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Herald-Munk\">{{cite news |last=Munk |first=Melanie |date=July 5, 2007 |title=Top ways to spend a day |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/top-ways-to-spend-a-day/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2019}}, Everett's 19 recognized neighborhood associations are:<ref name=\"Neighborhoods\">{{cite map |date=April 2019 |title=Everett Neighborhoods |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/17789/4-16-19-Everett-Neighborhoods-Map-11x17 |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Bayside, which includes most of Downtown Everett, the Port of Everett, and [[Naval Station Everett]], and surrounding residential areas.<ref name=\"Neighborhoods\"/>\n* Boulevard Bluffs, a primarily residential area of the city bordering Mukilteo<ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Joseph |date=August 14, 2019 |title=City to Edgewater Bridge bidders: What about Boeing traffic? |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/edgewater-bridge-replacement-likely-to-slow-boeing-commuters/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n* Cascade View, a residential area in South Everett, north of Everett Mall<ref name=\"Neighborhoods\"/>\n* Delta, a primarily residential area north of downtown Everett<ref>{{cite news |last=Cornfield |first=Jerry |date=January 30, 2019 |title=Delta neighbors make their pitch to hasten smelter cleanup |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/delta-neighbors-make-their-pitch-to-hasten-smelter-cleanup/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n* Evergreen, a primarily residential area in South Everett<ref name=\"Neighborhoods\"/>\n* Glacier View, an older residential area south of downtown<ref name=\"Neighborhoods\"/>\n* Harborview\u2013Seahurst\u2013Glenhaven, consisting of older residential areas south of downtown<ref name=\"Neighborhoods\"/>\n* Holly, a mix of residential, commercial, and industrial areas on the southern edge of the city<ref name=\"Neighborhoods\"/>\n* Lowell, a primarily residential area southeast of downtown and formerly an independent town founded in 1863<ref>{{cite news |date=December 25, 2012 |title=Lowell prepares for its 150th anniversary |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/lowell-prepares-for-its-150th-anniversary/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n* Northwest Everett, which includes older residential areas northwest of downtown, a historic district, and the [[Everett Community College]] campus<ref name=\"HistoricOverlay\">{{cite web |title=Historic Overlay Zones |url=https://everettwa.gov/578/Historic-Overlay-Zones |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n* Pinehurst\u2013Beverly Park, a mix of residential and commercial areas in South Everett<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=November 3, 2016 |title=Pinehurst residents really don't want homeless housing nearby |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/pinehurst-residents-try-to-stop-homeless-housing-project/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n* Port Gardner, which includes parts of Downtown Everett and residential areas on Rucker Hill, a historic district<ref name=\"HistoricOverlay\"/>\n* Riverside, includes residential areas northeast of downtown and a historic district<ref name=\"HistoricOverlay\"/>\n* Silver Lake, includes residential and commercial areas surrounding Silver Lake in the extreme southeastern part of the city<ref>{{cite news |last=Chircop |first=David |date=November 3, 2008 |title=Everett eyes growth to southeast |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-eyes-growth-to-southeast/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n* South Forest Park, a residential neighborhood near downtown<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=May 9, 2019 |title=A new beginning for a neighborhood park in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/a-new-beginning-for-a-neighborhood-park-in-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n* Twin Creeks, which includes the area surrounding Everett Mall and a mix of residential and commercial areas.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=August 28, 2012 |title=Everett's Twin Creeks neighborhood gets its renaissance |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everetts-twin-creeks-neighborhood-gets-its-renaissance/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 10, 2019}}</ref>\n* Valley View\u2013Sylvan Crest\u2013Larimer Ridge, residential areas in southeast Everett<ref>{{cite news |last=Haglund |first=Noah |date=December 5, 2013 |title=Everett homeowners file lawsuit over landslides |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-homeowners-file-lawsuit-over-landslides/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n* View Ridge\u2013Madison, residential areas west and southwest of Forest Park<ref name=\"Neighborhoods\"/>\n* Westmont, a primarily multi-family housing area in the southwestern part of the city<ref name=\"Neighborhoods\"/>\n\n====Downtown====\n\nDowntown Everett is generally defined by the area north of Pacific Avenue, east of West Marine View Drive, south of Everett Avenue, and west of Broadway.<ref>{{cite web |date=July 2006 |title=Everett  Downtown Plan |page=4 |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/Home/View/784 |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=February 2, 2017}}</ref> It is home to city and county government offices, high-rise office buildings, hotels, and [[apartment building]]s.<ref name=\"Herald-DTHotel\"/><ref name=\"Herald-DTApartments\"/> The [[Angel of the Winds Arena]] is located on the west side of Broadway, anchoring a small [[historic district]] on Hewitt Avenue.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=December 12, 2001 |title=Everett to raze buildings |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-to-raze-buildings/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> Several downtown streets are named for the founders of the Everett Land Company and their associates, including John D. Rockefeller, the [[Rucker Brothers]], [[Charles L. Colby]], and [[Alexander McDougall (1845-1923)|Alexander McDougall]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Rathbun |first=Andy |date=September 7, 2012 |title=We have mnemonic winner for Everett's streets |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/we-have-mnemonic-winner-for-everetts-streets/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Chircop |first=David |date=November 10, 2008 |title=Everett sees a beautiful downtown |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-sees-a-beautiful-downtown/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> The city government approved plans in 2018 to allow for high-rise buildings as tall as 25 stories and with reduced parking requirements to encourage denser development in anticipation of a future [[Link light rail]] station.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=August 31, 2018 |title=A taller, denser downtown Everett gets City Council approval |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-plans-for-a-taller-denser-future-downtown/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\n\nThe climate of Everett is generally similar to most of the [[Puget Sound region|Puget Sound lowlands]], with year-round moderate temperatures influenced by marine air masses. The variation of normal weather between seasons is less extreme than inland areas, with dry summers and mild, rainy winters due to the proximity of the [[Pacific Ocean]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=253}} Under the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] system, Everett has a [[warm-summer Mediterranean climate]] (Csb), though it is also described as having an [[oceanic climate]] (Cfb).{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=253}}<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Peel |first1=M. C. |last2=Finlayson |first2=B. L. |last3=McMahon |first3=T. A. |year=2007 |title=Updated world map of the K\u00f6ppen-Geiger climate classification |journal=[[Hydrology and Earth System Sciences]] |doi=10.5194/hess-11-1633-2007 |issn=1027-5606 |volume=11 |issue=5 |pages=1633\u20131644 |publisher=[[European Geosciences Union]] |url=http://www.hydrol-earth-syst-sci.net/11/1633/2007/hess-11-1633-2007.html |accessdate=October 14, 2019|doi-access=free }}</ref> The city marks the north end of the [[Puget Sound Convergence Zone]], a local weather phenomenon caused by colliding air currents from the region's mountain ranges that produces heavier rain and stronger winds than the rest of the region.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mass |first=Cliff |year=2008 |title=The Weather of the Pacific Northwest |page=149 |publisher=[[University of Washington Press]] |isbn=978-0-295-98847-4 |oclc=416457886 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xPiACgAAQBAJ&pg=PA149 |via=Google Books |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Sistek |first=Scott |date=December 17, 2015 |title=What Is A Puget Sound Convergence Zone? |url=https://komonews.com/weather/faq/what-is-a-puget-sound-convergence-zone |publisher=[[KOMO-TV|KOMO News]] |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe warmest month for Everett is August, with average high temperatures of {{convert|72.7|F|C|lk=on}}, while January is the coolest, at an average high of {{convert|44.9|F|C}}.<ref name=\"WRCC\"/> The highest recorded temperature, {{convert|98|F|C}}, occurred on June 9, 1955, and the lowest, {{convert|0|F|C}}, occurred on November 11, 1993.<ref name=\"WRCC\"/> The city receives {{convert|35.71|in|mm}} of annual rainfall, which mostly falls from October to March and peaks in December.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=253}}<ref name=\"WRCC\"/> Everett rarely receives significant snowfall and its highest total, {{convert|26.6|in|cm}}, occurred in 1965.<ref name=\"Soil-Survey\"/><ref name=\"WRCC\"/>\n\n{{Weather box \n|location = Everett\n|single line = Y\n| Jan record high F = 72\n| Feb record high F = 74\n| Mar record high F = 82\n| Apr record high F = 85\n| May record high F = 93\n| Jun record high F = 98\n| Jul record high F = 93\n| Aug record high F = 94\n| Sep record high F = 89\n| Oct record high F = 83\n| Nov record high F = 74\n| Dec record high F = 66\n| year record high F = 98\n| Jan high F = 44.9\n| Feb high F = 48.8\n| Mar high F = 52.8\n| Apr high F = 58.1\n| May high F = 63.6\n| Jun high F = 68.3\n| Jul high F = 72.6\n| Aug high F = 72.7\n| Sep high F = 67.8\n| Oct high F = 59.5\n| Nov high F = 50.9\n| Dec high F = 45.7\n| year high F = 58.8\n| Jan low F = 33.1\n| Feb low F = 34.4\n| Mar low F = 36.8\n| Apr low F = 40.4\n| May low F = 45.3\n| Jun low F = 50.2\n| Jul low F = 52.9\n| Aug low F = 52.8\n| Sep low F = 48.3\n| Oct low F = 43\n| Nov low F = 37.6\n| Dec low F = 34.3\n| year low F = 42.4\n| Jan record low F = 1\n| Feb record low F = 2\n| Mar record low F = 10\n| Apr record low F = 23\n| May record low F = 29\n| Jun record low F = 36\n| Jul record low F = 37\n| Aug record low F = 38\n| Sep record low F = 30\n| Oct record low F = 22\n| Nov record low F = 0\n| Dec record low F = 5\n| year record low F = 0\n| precipitation colour = green\n| Jan precipitation inch = 4.51\n| Feb precipitation inch = 3.25\n| Mar precipitation inch = 3.57\n| Apr precipitation inch = 2.7\n| May precipitation inch = 2.34\n| Jun precipitation inch = 2.12\n| Jul precipitation inch = 1.04\n| Aug precipitation inch = 1.2\n| Sep precipitation inch = 1.98\n| Oct precipitation inch = 3.39\n| Nov precipitation inch = 4.65\n| Dec precipitation inch = 4.96\n| year precipitation inch = 35.71\n| Jan precipitation days = 19\n| Feb precipitation days = 16\n| Mar precipitation days = 18\n| Apr precipitation days = 15\n| May precipitation days = 12\n| Jun precipitation days = 10\n| Jul precipitation days = 6\n| Aug precipitation days = 6\n| Sep precipitation days = 9\n| Oct precipitation days = 15\n| Nov precipitation days = 18\n| Dec precipitation days = 19\n| Jan snow inch = 3.3\n| Feb snow inch = 1.2\n| Mar snow inch = 0.6\n| Apr snow inch = 0.2\n| May snow inch = 0\n| Jun snow inch = 0\n| Jul snow inch = 0\n| Aug snow inch = 0\n| Sep snow inch = 0\n| Oct snow inch = 0\n| Nov snow inch = 0.6\n| Dec snow inch = 1.4\n| year snow inch = 7.3\n\n|source 1 = [[Western Regional Climate Center]] (1894\u20132015)<ref name=\"WRCC\">{{cite web |title=Period of Record Monthly Climate Summary: Everett, Washington (452675) |url=http://www.wrcc.dri.edu/cgi-bin/cliMAIN.pl?wa2675 |publisher=[[Western Regional Climate Center]] |accessdate=November 16, 2015}}</ref>\n|date=November 2015\n}}\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Aerial Boeing Everett Factory October 2011.jpg|thumb|right|Aerial view of the [[Boeing Everett Factory]], the largest employer in Snohomish County]]\n\nEverett has a workforce population of 88,146 people with 59,599 who are employed, according to a 2018 estimate from the U.S. Census Bureau.<ref name=\"ACS\">{{cite web |year=2019 |title=Selected Economic Characteristics: Everett, Washington |url=https://data.census.gov/cedsci/table?q=DP03&g=1600000US5322640&tid=ACSDP5Y2018.DP03&hidePreview=true |work=[[American Community Survey]] |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The city also had an estimated 7,335 registered businesses in 2012 providing 94,000 jobs.<ref name=\"USCB-Profile\">{{cite web |title=Profile: Everett, Washington |url=https://data.census.gov/cedsci/profile?g=1600000US5322640&q=Everett |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Comp-Economy\">{{cite web |year=2015 |title=Chapter 7: Economic Development |pages=3\u20134 |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/4862/Chapter-07-Economic-Development-PDF |work=Everett Comprehensive Plan |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Everett's economy is centered around [[aerospace]] manufacturing, maritime activities, the technology sector, and the [[service industry]].<ref name=\"Comp-Economy\"/> The largest employer in the city is airplane manufacturer [[Boeing]], with 31 percent of all jobs.<ref name=\"CAFR2018\"/> The company's main [[Boeing Everett Factory|manufacturing plant]] near Paine Field is the world's largest building by volume.<ref>{{cite web |title=Boeing in Everett |url=http://www.boeing.com/company/about-bca/everett-production-facility.page |publisher=[[Boeing]] |accessdate=September 27, 2016}}</ref> The local economy of Everett and Snohomish County is heavily affected by Boeing's performance, with layoffs and strikes causing downturns in other industries.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dunlop |first=Michelle |date=December 30, 2006 |title=Boeing keeps Snohomish County economy humming |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/boeing-keeps-snohomish-county-economy-humming/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Nohara |first1=Yoshiaki |last2=Dunlop |first2=Michelle |date=October 18, 2008 |title=Strike has ripple effect on local economy |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/strike-has-ripple-effect-on-local-economy/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city's economy in the 19th and early 20th centuries was tied to the lumber trade and maritime industries, including fishing and boat manufacturing.<ref name=\"Herald-WaterfrontHist\">{{cite news |last=Muhlstein  |first=Julie |date=June 1, 2018 |title=Everett and its waterfront were built by the working class |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-built-by-the-working-class/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Everett's last remaining wood [[pulp mill]], owned by [[Kimberly-Clark]], shut down in April 2012 and was demolished a year later, marking the end of the lumber economy's dominance.<ref name=\"Herald-KimClark\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Haglund |first=Noah |date=August 18, 2013 |title=Kimberly-Clark says former mill site better without grass |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/kimberly-clark-says-former-mill-site-better-without-grass/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The aerospace industry in Everett began growing in the late 1960s after Boeing began constructing its assembly plant at Paine Field, bringing suppliers and subcontractors to the area.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kershner |first=Jim |date=September 8, 2015 |title=Boeing and Washington's Aerospace Industry, 1934-2015 |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/11111 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Since the 1990s, the city government has encouraged economic development in other industries to add diversity, particularly in the technology sector.<ref>{{cite news |last=Matlick |first=Justin |date=November 6, 2005 |title=Boomtown dreams: Feisty Everett chases Bremerton, Tacoma with mixed results |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/stories/2005/11/07/story3.html |work=[[Puget Sound Business Journal]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The Port of Everett has also developed its own industrial park in North Everett that is home to an aerospace supplier and distribution centers for [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] and [[FedEx]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=March 5, 2018 |title=Port of Everett's Riverside Business Park finally takes shape |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/everett-riverside-business-park-is-finally-taking-shape/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Podsada |first=Janice |date=September 9, 2019 |title=An Everett business park is getting a big new tenant: Amazon |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/an-everett-business-park-is-getting-a-big-new-tenant-amazon/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2018}}, the largest industry in Everett is manufacturing, with 18 percent of residents employed there, followed by educational services (18%), retail (12%), professional services (11%), and entertainment (11%).<ref name=\"ACS\"/> Electronics manufacturer [[Fluke Corporation]] (now part of [[Fortive]]) is based in Everett and has 1,000 employees in Washington state.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lerman |first=Rachel |date=October 28, 2016 |title=Quiet industrial giant emerges in Everett |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/technology/everetts-fortive-shapes-strategy-for-successful-companies/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> Toymaker [[Funko]] is also headquartered in Downtown Everett, where it has its own retail store that opened in 2017, and operates a distribution center in the city.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hefley |first=Diana |date=August 20, 2017 |title='Funatics' pour into downtown Everett for Funko grand opening |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/funatics-pour-into-downtown-everett-for-funko-grand-opening/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=September 9, 2016 |title=Toymaker Funko moving to downtown Everett |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/news/toymaker-funko-moving-to-downtown-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=September 27, 2016}}</ref> Other large employers in Everett include the [[Providence Regional Medical Center Everett|Providence Regional Medical Center]], with 4,900 employees, the [[U.S. Navy]] with 2,900 employees, and [[Everett Public Schools (Washington)|Everett Public Schools]] with 2,440 employees.<ref name=\"CAFR2018\"/>\n\nApproximately 28 percent of Everett workers are employed at businesses located within the city limit, while 15 percent commute to [[Seattle]].<ref name=\"OnTheMap\">{{cite web |title=Work Destination Report&nbsp;\u2014 Where Workers are Employed Who Live in the Selection Area&nbsp;\u2014 by Places (Cities, CDPs, etc.) |url=https://lehd.ces.census.gov/data/ |publisher=United States Census Bureau |via=[https://onthemap.ces.census.gov/ OnTheMap] |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The majority of the city's employed residents (70%) commute to work in [[Single-occupancy vehicle|single-occupant vehicles]], while 14 percent use [[carpool]]s and 6 percent use [[public transportation]].<ref name=\"ACS\"/> Everett workplaces have employees who live across Snohomish and King counties, with 15 percent from within the city, 7 percent from [[Marysville, Washington|Marysville]], 5 percent from Seattle, and 4 percent from [[Lake Stevens, Washington|Lake Stevens]].<ref name=\"OnTheMap\"/> The changing of [[shift work|first shift]] at the Boeing facility in Everett causes a spike in traffic congestion during the mornings and early afternoons that spills out from freeways onto local streets.<ref>{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=December 26, 2016 |title=Boeing eyes ending staggered start times to optimize production |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/boeing-eyes-ending-staggered-start-times-to-optimize-production/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city's retailers had total sales of $2&nbsp;million in 2012 and are concentrated along two major highways, Evergreen Way and Everett Mall Way, in [[strip mall]]s and standalone [[big-box store]]s.<ref name=\"USCB-Profile\"/><ref name=\"Comp-Economy\"/> The intersection of the two corridors is home to a large [[auto row]] that developed in the 1980s after dealerships relocated from Downtown Everett.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=101}} The [[Everett Mall]], located at the northeast end of Everett Mall Way ([[Washington State Route 99|State Route 99]]), opened in 1974 and has over 100 stores. The mall was expanded in 2005, adding a [[movie theater]] and a new set of stores, but has since lost two major retailers and several other tenants.<ref>{{cite news |last=Haglund |first=Noah |date=September 6, 2013 |title=New tenant seen as key to Everett Mall revival |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/new-tenant-seen-as-key-to-everett-mall-revival-2/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=January 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=February 24, 2017 |title=Everett Mall back on the block for the third time in two years |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/everett-mall-back-on-the-block-for-the-third-time-in-two-years/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Largest employers===\n\n:''Source: 2018 Comprehensive Annual Financial Report''<ref name=\"CAFR2018\">{{cite web |date=June 26, 2019 |title=City of Everett, Washington 2018 Comrpehensive Annual Financial Report For the Year Ended December 31, 2018 |page=175 |url=https://everettwa.gov/ArchiveCenter/ViewFile/Item/1156 |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Rank\n! Employer\n! Number of employees\n|-\n|1\n|[[Boeing]]\n|35,000\n|-\n|2\n|[[Providence Regional Medical Center Everett]]\n|4,906\n|-\n|3\n|[[Washington (state)|State of Washington]]\n|3,000\n|-\n|4\n|[[Naval Station Everett]]\n|2,900\n|-\n|5\n|[[The Everett Clinic]]\n|2,871\n|-\n|6\n|[[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]]\n|2,759\n|-\n|7\n|[[Everett Public Schools (Washington)|Everett Public Schools]]\n|2,443\n|-\n|8\n|[[Fluke Corporation]] ([[Fortive]])\n|1,200\n|-\n|9\n|City of Everett\n|1,198\n|-\n|10\n|[[Snohomish County Public Utility District]]\n|1,004\n|}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1900= 7838\n|1910= 24814\n|1920= 27644\n|1930= 30567\n|1940= 30224\n|1950= 33849\n|1960= 40304\n|1970= 53622\n|1980= 54413\n|1990= 69961\n|2000= 91488\n|2010= 103019\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=111262\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web |date=June 27, 2019 |title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates |url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=February 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|footnote=Sources: U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 6, 2013}}</ref><br />2018 U.S. Census Estimate<ref name=\"2018 Pop Estimate\">{{cite web |title=Population Estimates |url=https://census.gov/data/tables/2018/demo/popest/total-cities-and-towns.html |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=June 5, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\nEverett is the largest city in Snohomish County and the seventh largest in Washington state by population, ranking between [[Kent, Washington|Kent]] and [[Renton, Washington|Renton]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Taylor |first=Chuck |date=May 22, 2015 |title=Marysville among top U.S. cities for population growth |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/marysville-among-top-u-s-cities-for-population-growth/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> It had a population of 103,019 at the time of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 U.S. census]], and an estimated population of 111,800 in 2019 counts from the state government.<ref>{{cite web |author=OFM Forecasting & Research Division |date=August 2019 |title=State of Washington 2019 Population Trends |page=20 |url=https://www.ofm.wa.gov/sites/default/files/public/dataresearch/pop/april1/ofm_april1_poptrends.pdf |publisher=[[Washington State Office of Financial Management]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> The city's [[urban growth area]] has a population of 44,596 residents {{as of|2016|lc=y}} that are part of [[unincorporated area|unincorporated]] Snohomish County.<ref>{{cite web |date=March 22, 2017 |title=Snohomish County Tomorrow 2016 Growth Monitoring Report: Population Growth Trends |page=22 |url=https://snohomishcountywa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/44883/2---2016-GMR---Population-Trends |format=PDF |publisher=Snohomish County Tomorrow Steering Committee |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Everett's population grew by 47 percent from 1990 to 2000 and 13 percent from 2000 to 2010, due to annexations and increased housing development.<ref name=\"Comp-Intro\">{{cite web |date=June 2015 |title=Chapter 1: Introduction |page=13 |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/4858/Chapter-01-Introduction-PDF |work=Everett Comprehensive Plan |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> It is projected to increase by 40,000 to 60,000 residents by 2035 as part of state-mandated growth plans.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stevick |first=Eric |date=July 1, 2009 |title=Snohomish County population rising fast since 2000, led by Marysville |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/snohomish-county-population-rising-fast-since-2000-led-by-marysville/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Herald-Boom15\">{{cite news |last1=Winters |first1=Chris |last2=Catchpole |first2=Dan |date=May 15, 2015 |title=High expectations drive downtown Everett building boom |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/high-expectations-drive-downtown-everett-building-boom/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The city's population growth since 1990 has largely been driven by non-Caucasian racial groups, with the white majority decreasing from 92 percent in 1990 to 75 percent in 2010.<ref name=\"Comp-Intro\"/>\n\nThe city had 16,394 housing units in 2010, 9,181 of which were [[single-family home]]s and 7,213 of which were in [[multi-family housing]].<ref name=\"Comp-Housing\">{{cite web |year=2015 |title=Chapter 4: Housing Element |page=17 |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/4868/Chapter-04-Housing-PDF |work=Everett Comprehensive Plan |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Everett's homeownership rate is among the lowest in Washington, with 44 percent of homes occupied by their owners, and its residents have a low median income relative to the county and Seattle metropolitan area.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=December 1, 2015 |title=Low homeownership rate could make Everett ripe for renewal |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/low-homeownership-rate-could-make-everett-ripe-for-renewal/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The average monthly [[Renting|rent]] for housing units in Everett in 2013 ranged from $700 for a [[studio apartment]] to $2,723 for a five-bedroom home.<ref name=\"Comp-Housing\"/>{{rp|12}} The city also has several [[affordable housing]] complexes that provide 2,461 units to low-income households through federal and local grants.<ref name=\"Comp-Housing\"/>{{rp|13}}\n\n===2010 census===\n\nAs of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 U.S. census]], there were 103,019 people, 41,312 households, and 23,282 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|3079.8|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 44,609 housing units at an average density of {{convert|1333.6|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census|racial makeup]] of the city was 74.6% White, 4.1% African American, 1.4% Native American, 7.8% Asian, 0.7% Pacific Islander, 6.1% from other races, and 5.3% from two or more races. Hispanic or Latino of any race were 14.2% of the population.<ref name=\"QuickFacts\">{{cite web |title=QuickFacts: Everett, Washington |url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/everettcitywashington/POP060210 |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere were 41,312 households of which 30.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 38.2% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 12.5% had a female householder with no husband present, 5.7% had a male householder with no wife present, and 43.6% were non-families. 34.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 9.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.39 and the average family size was 3.09.<ref name=\"QuickFacts\"/>\n\nThe median age in the city was 34.4 years. 22.7% of residents were under the age of 18; 11.3% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 30.6% were from 25 to 44; 25% were from 45 to 64; and 10.3% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 50.9% male and 49.1% female.<ref name=\"QuickFacts\"/>\n\n===2000 census===\n\nAs of the [[2000 United States Census|2000 U.S. census]], there were 91,488 people, 36,325 households and 21,613 families residing in the city.  The population density was 2,814.6 people per square mile (1,086.9/km\u00b2).  There were 38,512 housing units at an average density of 1,184.8 per square mile (457.5/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the city was 56% White, 9% African American, 1.56% Native American, 10% Asian, 4% Pacific Islander, 3.13% from other races and 4.25% from two or more races.  Hispanic or Latino of any race were 13% of the population.<ref name=\"Census2000\">{{cite web |year=2000 |title=Profile of General Demographic Characteristics: Everett city, Washington |url=https://www.psrc.org/sites/default/files/everett.pdf |publisher=United States Census Bureau |via=[[Puget Sound Regional Council]] |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere were 36,325 households, out of which 31.9% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 42.1% were married couples living together, 12.5% had a female householder with no husband present, and 40.5% were non-families. 31.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.40 and the average family size was 3.04.<ref name=\"Census2000\"/>\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 25.1% under the age of 18, 12.3% from 18 to 24, 33.3% from 25 to 44, 18.9% from 45 to 64, and 10.3% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 32 years.  For every 100 females, there were 103.5 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 102.8 males.<ref name=\"Census2000\"/>\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $40,100 and the median income for a family was $46,743.  Males had a median income of $35,852 versus $28,841 for females.  The [[per capita income]] for the city was $20,577.  About 10.1% of families and 19.5% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 16% of those under the age of 18 and 12.1% of those ages 65 and older.<ref name=\"Census2000\"/>\n\n===Crime===\n{{Infobox UCR\n|city_name = Everett\n|year = 2015\n|homicide = 5\n|rape = 44\n|robbery = 148\n|aggravated_assault = 225\n|burglary = 974\n|larceny_theft = 4316\n|motor_vehicle_theft = 908\n|arson = 33\n|source_url = https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/seattle/news/press-releases/the-fbi-releases-2015-crime-statistics-for-washington-state\n|source_name = 2015 FBI Crime Statistics\n|notes = 2015 population: 107,219\n}}\n\nThe Everett Police Department has 201 uniformed police officers and five unfilled positions {{as of|2020|lc=y}}.<ref name=\"Herald-Crime20\">{{cite news |last=Watanabe |first=Ben |date=February 17, 2020 |title=Crime is down, but Everett hopes to hire 24 more officers |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/crime-is-down-but-everett-hopes-to-hire-24-more-officers/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> The city had 422 [[violent crime]]s and 6,198 [[property crime]]s reported to law enforcement in 2015.<ref name=\"UCR\">{{cite web |date=September 2016 |title=Table 8 \u2013 Washington: Offenses Known to Law Enforcement by City, 2015 |url=https://ucr.fbi.gov/crime-in-the-u.s/2015/crime-in-the-u.s.-2015/tables/table-8/table-8-state-pieces/table_8_offenses_known_to_law_enforcement_washington_by_city_2015.xls |work=[[Uniform Crime Reports]] |publisher=[[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> The number of reported crimes in Everett has declined since reaching their peak in 2009\u201310, with 610 violent crimes and 7,672 property crimes.<ref name=\"Herald-Crime20\"/> Everett had ranked in the top 20 percent of U.S. cities for reported crimes in reports by [[CQ Press]], which included property crimes and burglary among violent crimes.<ref>{{cite news |last=Holtz |first=Jackson |date=November 23, 2008 |title=List distorts Everett crime statistics |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/list-distorts-everett-crime-statistics/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> It was ranked 49th among cities in Washington for crimes per capita in a 2019 study by the [[National Council for Home Safety and Security]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Clarridge |first=Christine |date=January 29, 2019 |title=These are Washington's safest and least safe cities, according to crime stats |page= |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/crime/is-seattle-safe-you-might-be-better-off-in-snoqualmie-or-sunnyside/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Everett Police Department and Snohomish County Sheriff's Office began criminal investigations against operators and employees of various [[bikini barista]] coffee stands in 2009 for violating adult entertainment laws.<ref name=\"Herald-Bikini20\">{{cite news |last=Davey |first=Stephanie |date=February 4, 2020 |title=Everett bikini baristas file petition to U.S. Supreme Court |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-bikini-baristas-file-petition-to-u-s-supreme-court/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Rikki |date=October 30, 2013 |title=Everett police raid bikini coffee stand; 3 arrested |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-police-raid-bikini-coffee-stand-3-arrested/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The city government passed a [[dress code]] ordinance for food service workers in August 2017, but were met with a lawsuit from stand operators and employees over the constitutionality of the ordinance.<ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Rikki |date=September 11, 2017 |title=Bikini baristas sue Everett, say dress code unfair |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/bikini-baristas-sue-everett-over-new-dress-code-rule/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> The ordinance was suspended by a preliminary injuction from the U.S. District Court in December 2017, but the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit|Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals]] ruled in favor of the city government in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Clarridge |first=Christine |date=August 19, 2019 |title=No new bottom line in Everett's bikini barista brouhaha |page= |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/bikini-baristas-arent-giving-up-after-appeals-court-rules-everett-can-regulate-their-outfits/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> The city government does not plan to enforce the dress code ordinance until the lawsuit is resolved with the lifting of the preliminary injunction.<ref name=\"Herald-Bikini20\"/>\n\nThe city has a high rate of [[opioid abuse]], particularly [[OxyContin]] and [[heroin]], fueled by cross-state drug trafficking.<ref name=\"LAT-Oxy\">{{cite news |last=Ryan |first=Harriet |date=January 19, 2017 |title=City devastated by OxyContin use sues Purdue Pharma, claims drugmaker put profits over citizens' welfare |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-oxycontin-lawsuit-20170118-story.html |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hefley |first1=Diana |last2=North |first2=Scott |date=January 18, 2017 |title=Everett ready to sue OxyContin maker over opioid deaths, crime |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-might-sue-oxycontin-maker-over-opioid-deaths-crime/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> The widespread opioid use also contributed to a 65 percent rise in [[homelessness]] in Everett from 2015 to 2017, straining local [[homeless shelter|shelters]] and supportive housing systems.<ref>{{cite news |last=Le |first=Phuong |date=December 27, 2017 |title=Addiction, mental illness complicate help for the homeless |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/addiction-mental-illness-complicate-help-for-the-homeless/ |work=The Everett Herald |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> The city government filed a lawsuit against OxyContin manufacturer [[Purdue Pharma]] in January 2017, claiming that the company had been [[gross negligence|grossly negligent]] in distributing the drug and containing its effect on Everett residents. The lawsuit also identified a drug trafficking ring based in [[Los Angeles]], large prescriptions by doctors to procure the drug, and direct marketing by Purdue Pharma as contributing factors to the rise in opioid cases.<ref name=\"LAT-Oxy\"/> Everett's lawsuit was joined by complaints from other jurisdictions, including Snohomish County and the Tulalip Tribes, and was heard in the [[United States District Court for the Northern District of Ohio|U.S. District Court of Northern Ohio]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Giordano |first1=Lizz |last2=Haglund |first2=Noah |date=September 1, 2019 |title=Oklahoma's opioid verdict could bolster Everett\u2019s own lawsuit |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/oklahomas-opioid-verdict-could-bolster-everetts-own-lawsuit/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government and politics==\n\nEverett is a first-class city with an organized [[city charter|charter]] and a [[mayor\u2013council government|mayor\u2013council]] form of government.<ref name=\"MRSC-First\">{{cite web |date=March 10, 2020 |title=First Class Cities |url=http://mrsc.org/getdoc/490c32b2-2cd8-480a-92bc-a4ec66fbeb1c/First-Class-Cities-by-Form-of-Government.aspx |publisher=[[Municipal Research and Services Center]] |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The city's [[mayor]] and seven councilmembers are elected [[at-large]] to four-year terms in staggered elections that take place during odd-numbered years. Beginning in 2021, the Everett city council will elect five members from districts and two from at-large seats.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=November 19, 2018 |title=Significant changes coming to Everett's City Council |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/significant-changes-coming-to-everetts-city-council/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The city council meets weekly on Wednesdays and offers live television and web broadcasts via the [[Everett Channel]].<ref>{{cite web |title=City Council |url=https://everettwa.gov/409/City-Council |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The city government is based out of the Wall Street Building in Downtown Everett, a 10-story office tower adjacent to the historic [[Everett City Hall]]\u2014now home to the city police department and city council chambers.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=December 6, 2016 |title=City of Everett tightens Wall Street building security |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-hires-security-for-building-housing-mayor-city-offices/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Debra |date=February 26, 2012 |title=Plan could allow new name for old Everett city hall |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/plan-could-allow-new-name-for-old-everett-city-hall/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Cassie Franklin]], a former city councilmember, was elected as mayor in 2017 and is the second woman and first non-appointee to hold the office.<ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Rikki |date=November 16, 2017 |title=Franklin becomes first woman to be elected mayor of Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/cassie-franklin-becomes-first-woman-to-be-elected-mayor-of-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The mayor of Everett is responsible for appointing the heads of various city departments, the city clerk, the city treasurer, the [[police chief|police]] and [[fire chief|fire]] chiefs, and members of service commissions and boards.<ref name=\"MRSC-First\"/> The city government has 1,200 employees and an operating budget of $148.7&nbsp;million for 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=January 11, 2019 |title=City of Everett offers buyouts to 330 senior employees |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/city-of-everett-offers-buyouts-to-330-senior-employees/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=November 15, 2019 |title=Everett balances 2020 budget with no new fees or taxes |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-balances-2020-budget-with-no-new-fees-or-taxes/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> It provides a range of municipal services, including police, fire, [[emergency medical services]], public works, a [[housing authority]], zoning and planning, parks and recreation, and some utilities.<ref name=\"CAFR2018\"/>{{rp|2}}<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web |title=About Everett |url=https://everettwa.gov/272/About-Everett |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> Everett also has a [[municipal court]] that was established in 1987 and has two judges who are elected to four-year terms.<ref>{{cite news |last=Haglund |first=Noah |date=December 20, 2013 |title=First woman to serve on Everett Municipal Court |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/first-woman-to-serve-on-everett-municipal-court/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The city government runs its own [[Everett Transit|public transit]] and [[Everett Public Library|library]] systems, which are separate from the countywide [[Community Transit]] and [[Sno-Isle Libraries]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=November 8, 2019 |title=Everett entertains pitch for joining county-wide bus system |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-entertains-pitch-for-joining-county-wide-bus-system/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett is also the [[county seat]] of [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]] and houses several major government facilities on a campus in Downtown Everett. The campus includes the [[Snohomish County Courthouse|county courthouse]], county jail, administrative offices, and the main precinct of the [[Snohomish County Sheriff|county sheriff]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Departments-Offices-Campus Map |url=https://snohomishcountywa.gov/2902/Departments-Offices-CampusMap |publisher=Snohomish County |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kelly |first=Brian |date=June 1, 2005 |title=$175 million later... |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/175-million-later/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt the federal level, Everett is part of the [[Washington's 2nd congressional district|2nd congressional district]], represented by Democrat [[Rick Larsen]] since 2001.<ref name=\"DistrictMap\">{{cite map |date=February 7, 2012 |title=Washington State Legislative & Congressional District Map |url=http://www.redistricting.wa.gov/assets/maps/FoldedMap_State.pdf |inset=[http://www.redistricting.wa.gov/assets/maps/FoldedMap_Insets.pdf Puget Sound & Other Areas] |publisher=[[Washington State Redistricting Commission]] |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Cornfield |first=Jerry |date=January 7, 2019 |title=Now in majority, state\u2019s Democrats ready to use new clout |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/now-in-majority-states-democrats-ready-to-use-new-clout/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> At the state level, most of the city is in the [[Washington's 38th legislative district|38th legislative district]] alongside Marysville and the Tulalip Indian Reservation. The southern neighborhoods of the city, including Silver Lake, are part of the [[Washington's 21st legislative district|21st legislative district]], shared with Edmonds and Mukilteo.<ref name=\"DistrictMap\"/> Everett is also part of the [[Snohomish County Council]]'s 2nd district, which also includes Mukilteo and the Tulalip Indian Reservation.<ref>{{cite map |title=Snohomish County Council Districts |url=http://snohomishcountywa.gov/DocumentCenter/Home/View/49 |publisher=Snohomish County Elections |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Arts===\n[[File:Everett Theater 02.jpg|thumb|The Historic Everett Theatre, opened in 1901]]\n\nEverett is described as a \"largely [[blue-collar]] city\", but is home to a regional arts scene that includes galleries, community theaters, music, and artwork.<ref name=\"Herald-Music\">{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=August 27, 2014 |title=With a change of tune, Snohomish County Music Project thrives |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/with-a-change-of-tune-snohomish-county-music-project-thrives/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wood |first=Kyle R. |date=August 16, 1996 |title=Selling Snohomish County |page=B1 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19960816&slug=2344504 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The city has five major [[performing arts]] venues that host various groups and traveling events.<ref name=\"Times-Venues\">{{cite news |last=Wright |first=Diane |date=June 20, 2007 |title=Take a seat |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/take-a-seat/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 834-seat [[Historic Everett Theatre]] on Colby Avenue opened in 1901 and hosts community theater productions, musical groups, [[improv comedy]], and film screenings.<ref name=\"Herald-Theater\">{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=June 13, 2018 |title=Historic Everett Theatre holds an audition for new investors |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/historic-everett-theatre-seeking-investors/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The city once had a \"theater district\" in downtown that included the Everett, Granada, Balboa, and Roxy theaters, all opened during the early 20th century.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=222}} The Everett Theatre is the last surviving theater from the era, having been partially rebuilt following a fire in December 1923, renovated into a [[Multiplex (movie theater)|triplex]] theater in 1979, closed in 1989, and restored to its original state beginning in 2000.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brooks |first=Diane |date=February 28, 2000 |title=Theater begins to look like old self |page=B1 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=September 7, 2006 |title=Theater switches to edgier material |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/theater-switches-to-edgier-material/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The regional [[Village Theatre]] performs in [[Issaquah, Washington|Issaquah]] and at the Everett Performing Arts Center, a city-owned facility that opened in 1993 and is also home to the Everett Chorale.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fiege |first=Gale |date=January 8, 2015 |title=Five times a year, Village Theatre packs up and heads to Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/five-times-a-year-village-theatre-packs-up-and-heads-to-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Fiege |first=Gale |date=December 2, 2015 |title=Everett Chorale kicks off golden anniversary this weekend |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/everett-chorale-kicks-off-golden-anniversary-this-weekend/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The Village Theatre opened KidStage, a venue for young performers, in 2011 by converting a former [[bank branch]] building adjacent to the Everett Performing Arts Center.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=September 26, 2011 |title=Kids at center stage |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/kids-at-center-stage/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The Everett Civic Auditorium at [[Everett High School (Washington)|Everett High School]] was completed in 1939 and is home to the Everett Philharmonic Orchestra, which was formed in 2010 by musicians from the former Everett Symphony after it ran into financial issues.<ref name=\"Herald-Music\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=February 19, 2010 |title=Everett Symphony musicians form own orchestra |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-symphony-musicians-form-own-orchestra/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city's [[public art]] program is managed by the Everett Cultural Arts Commission, a citizen advisory board established in 1974 alongside a [[percent for art]] program for public projects.<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=February 17, 2019 |title=Everett couple honored for their 'deep passion for the arts' |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/everett-couple-honored-for-their-deep-passion-for-the-arts/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> In addition to public art, the commission manages 16 [[street piano]]s in Downtown Everett that are painted by local artists and available for public use every August.<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=August 8, 2019 |title=Music returns to Everett sidewalks with Street Tunes program |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/music-returns-to-everett-sidewalks-with-street-tunes-program/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Everett's main arts district is on a three-block section of Hoyt Avenue in downtown, which is home to the [[Schack Art Center]] and several sculptures installed in the late 2000s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=February 26, 2013 |title=New lights shine on Everett's art district |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/new-lights-shine-on-everetts-art-district/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The Schack Art Center opened in 2011 as a multipurpose exhibition space and artist workshop, with facilities for various mediums and housing for artists provided by [[Artspace Projects|Artspace]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=April 29, 2011 |title=Art center opens this weekend |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/schack-art-center-opening/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=December 18, 2009 |title=Idamae Schack's generosity built Everett's arts and cultural community |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/jobs-must-be-cut-for-actual-savings/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The center was originally the Arts Council of Snohomish County and named in honor of John and Idamae Schack, longtime supporters of the organization and arts in the region;<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=August 27, 2015 |title=Schacks' quiet generosity leaves huge legacy in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/schacks-quiet-generosity-leaves-huge-legacy-in-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> in its first year, the Schack Art Center had 265 artists on exhibit and 33,000 visitors, helping to revitalize downtown during the [[Great Recession]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=April 28, 2012 |title=The key to Schack Art Center's success |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/the-key-to-schack-art-centers-success/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kareiva |first=Celina |date=February 19, 2012 |title=Everett arts center revitalizes downtown, artists |page=H1 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/thearts/2017517345_schack19.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501081252/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/thearts/2017517345_schack19.html |archivedate=May 1, 2012 |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The Everett area has attracted artists and musicians from Seattle due to its relative affordability and incentives from the city government.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wilkinson |first=Eric |date=November 30, 2016 |title=New CD looks to put Everett on the musical map |url=https://www.king5.com/article/news/local/everett/new-cd-looks-to-put-everett-on-the-musical-map/359623390 |publisher=[[KING-TV|KING 5 News]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Potterf |first=Tina |date=June 15, 2005 |title=Wendy Becker: Everett's arts guru |page=H14 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=20050615&slug=becker15n |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Events and tourism===\n\nThe city hosts several annual events and festivals for local arts and celebrations, usually during the summer months. The city's waterfront hosts an annual parade and [[fireworks]] display on [[Independence Day (United States)|Independence Day]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Davey |first=Stephanie |date=July 5, 2019 |title=July 4th parade is a 'special tradition' for local families |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/july-4th-parade-is-a-special-tradition-for-local-families/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Everett has hosted a downtown [[sausage]] and street festival annually in September since 1977.<ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Evan |date=September 27, 2018 |title=Fill up on German grub at Everett Sausage Fest this weekend |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/fill-up-on-german-grub-at-everett-sausage-fest-this-weekend/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Several annual festivals were established in the 1990s, including a [[film festival]] in February,<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=February 7, 2019 |title=Everett Film Festival marks its 20th year with 10 screenings |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/see-10-short-films-and-documentaries-at-everett-film-festival/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> the Cruzin' to Colby [[classic car]] show in May,<ref>{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=March 29, 2017 |title=Cool cars converge as Cruzin' to Colby returns to Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/cool-cars-converge-as-cruzin-to-colby-returns-to-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> the Sorticulture garden festival in June,<ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Evan |date=June 1, 2019 |title=Sprinklers with style, and much more at Everett's Sorticulture |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/sprinklers-with-style-and-much-more-at-everetts-sorticulture/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> and the Fresh Paint [[art show]] in August.<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=August 16, 2018 |title=Fresh Paint to bring artists, art lovers to waterfront |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/fresh-paint-to-bring-artists-art-lovers-to-waterfront/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The city's largest annual summer festival, the Salty Sea Days, was established in 1970 and included a parade, [[hydroplane race]]s, a classic auto show, and other events. It was originally subsidized using city [[lodging tax]]es until 2003, and shut down three years later.<ref>{{cite news |last=Langston |first=Jennifer |date=August 26, 2003 |title=Puget Sound Journal: Everett's summer fest not worth its salt, some say |page=B3 |url=https://www.seattlepi.com/news/article/Puget-Sound-Journal-Everett-s-summer-fest-not-1122698.php |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Warnick |first=Jennifer |date=March 1, 2005 |title=Group scuttles Salty Sea Days |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/group-scuttles-salty-sea-days/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Everett [[farmers market]] began in 1994 and operates on Sundays from May to October with 200 vendors and about 5,000 weekly visitors.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=July 20, 2019 |title=Farmers Market is leaving Boxcar, moving to downtown Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/farmers-market-is-leaving-boxcar-moving-to-downtown-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> It was originally located at the Port of Everett but moved in 2019 to Wetmore Avenue in downtown because of parking and accessibility issues at the waterfront site.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Debra |date=June 6, 2011 |title=Future murky for Everett waterfront farmers market |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/article/20110606/NEWS01/706069912 |work=The Everett Herald |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728064906/http://www.heraldnet.com/article/20110606/NEWS01/706069912 |archivedate=July 28, 2011 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Herald-FM19\">{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=August 13, 2019 |title=Long parking lines, costs led Everett Farmers Market to move |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/parking-lines-costs-led-to-move-by-everett-farmers-market/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The farmers market also operates popup [[bazaar]]s during the off-season and a Wednesday market at [[Everett Station]] during the summer.<ref>{{cite news |last=Watanabe |first=Ben |date=February 10, 2020 |title=First popup Everett Farmers Market draws hundreds of people |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/first-popup-everett-farmers-market-draws-hundreds-of-people/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The waterfront remains home to a summer [[concert]] series that has been staged annually since 1991.<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=June 20, 2019 |title=A sure sign summer's here: 10 free concerts at Everett marina |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/a-sure-sign-summers-here-10-free-concerts-at-everett-marina/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett's government and the Everett Downtown Association have also launched tourism initiatives that have created new events and promotional branding for Everett.<ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Rikki |date=February 27, 2014 |title=One-man tourism bureau wants world to 'Experience Everett' |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/one-man-tourism-bureau-wants-world-to-experience-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The city government launched a [[logo]] design contest in 2014 that had 850 entries and 5,700 votes from local residents.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=December 4, 2014 |title=New Everett logo chosen from 850 entries |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/new-everett-logo-chosen-from-850-entries/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The winning design was later withdrawn due to its similarity to the logo of financial services company [[Envestnet]] and was replaced by a new brand design in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=October 25, 2015 |title=Everett's new website successful, but logo is no more |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everetts-new-website-successful-but-logo-is-no-more/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=March 2019 |title=Everett Logo |url=https://everettwa.gov/2314/Everett-Logo |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> A [[craft beer]] festival was established in 2012 by the [[Washington Beer Commission]] and was later renamed to the Upper Left Beerfest in 2017 after the city government took over operations.<ref>{{cite news |last=Swaney |first=Aaron |date=September 15, 2017 |title=Upper Left Beerfest raises a glass to the area's good taste |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/upper-left-beerfest-new-festival-to-enter-everetts-beer-scene/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The Fisherman's Village Music Festival, established in 2014, takes place annually over a three-day weekend in May at four stages in Downtown Everett. The music festival includes performances from 50 local and national artists as well as art exhibitions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rietmulder |first=Michael |date=March 29, 2018 |title=With Fisherman's Village Music Festival, Everett out-rocks Seattle one weekend a year |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/with-fishermans-village-music-festival-everett-out-rocks-seattle-one-weekend-a-year/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Evan |date=May 9, 2019 |title=Fisherman's Village Music Festival expands to Everett Station |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/fishermans-village-music-festival-expands-to-everett-station/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Everett area has several major tourist attractions, particularly those themed around aviation. The [[Future of Flight Aviation Center & Boeing Tour|Future of Flight Aviation Center]] at Paine Field, owned by the county government and operated by Boeing, has several aviation exhibits and includes a tour of the Boeing assembly plant. It is the most popular tourist attraction in Snohomish County, with 495,000 total visitors in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gates |first=Dominic |date=February 28, 2018 |title=Boeing, Snohomish County hold key to Future of Flight as aviation center faces turbulent times |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeing-snohomish-county-hold-key-to-future-of-flight-aviation-centers-future/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> The [[Flying Heritage & Combat Armor Museum]] opened in 2008 at a renovated Paine Field hangar and houses a collection of restored 20th century military planes and vehicles.<ref>{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=April 11, 2017 |title=Growing Flying Heritage Collection now has a new name |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/growing-flying-heritage-collection-now-has-a-new-name/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> The [[Imagine Children's Museum]] opened in 2004 at a renovated bank building in Downtown Everett after relocating from Marysville. It has interactive exhibits designed to teach children about local history, science, and the arts.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dunnewind |first=Stephanie |date=October 16, 2004 |title=Exploring children's museums: They educate and stimulate; they're expanding, and more are opening |page=C1 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=20041016&slug=childmuseum16 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=October 7, 2012 |title=Imagine Children's Museum adds new exhibits |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/life/imagine-children%C2%92s-museum-adds-new-exhibits/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Media===\n\nThe ''[[Everett Herald]]'' is the city's daily newspaper, providing local and national news for 40,000 subscribers in Snohomish County. It began publication on February 11, 1901, emerging as the city's lone daily newspaper from a field of three competitors established in the early 1890s, including the ''Everett News'', ''Everett Times'', and ''Everett Tribune''.<ref name=\"Editions\">{{cite book |last1=Bagwell |first1=Steve |last2=Stapilus |first2=Randy |year=2013 |title=New Editions: The Northwest's newspapers as they were, are, and will be |pages=212\u2013213 |publisher=Ridenbaugh Press |location=Carlton, Oregon |isbn=978-0-945648-10-9 |oclc=861618089}}</ref> The newspaper remained under local ownership until it was purchased by [[The Washington Post Company]] in 1978 and it was sold to [[Sound Publishing]] in 2013.<ref name=\"Editions\"/><ref>{{cite news |date=March 4, 2013 |title=Herald sale to Sound Publishing completed |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/herald-sale-to-sound-publishing-completed/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The ''Herald'' launched its online website on January 5, 1997, the monthly ''Herald Business Journal'' in 1998,<ref>{{cite web |title=The Herald Business Journal |url=http://www.soundpublishing.com/titles/the-herald-business-journal/ |publisher=[[Sound Publishing]] |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> and began publishing a weekly Spanish-language newspaper, ''La Raza del Noroeste'', in April 2006.<ref>{{cite web |title=About the Daily Herald and Heraldnet |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/article/99999999/EXTRAS02/676034648 |publisher=The Everett Herald |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716223513/http://www.heraldnet.com/article/99999999/EXTRAS02/676034648 |archivedate=July 16, 2010 |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Arriola |first=Cindy |date=February 14, 2013 |title=El futuro de \"La Raza\" |language=Spanish |trans-title=The future of \"La Raza\" |url=https://www.larazanw.com/noticias/el-futuro-de-la-raza/ |work=La Raza del Noroeste |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> My Everett News is an independent online news outlet for Everett that was established in 2011 and is affiliated with ''[[The Seattle Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news |date=July 13, 2011 |title=Seattle Times announces more local news partners |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/seattle-times-announces-more-local-news-partners-1/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city is part of the [[Media in Seattle|Seattle\u2013Tacoma media market]], ranked 13th among U.S. metro areas, which includes several major television and radio stations.<ref>{{cite web |date=September 28, 2019 |title=Local Television Market Universe Estimates |page=1 |url=https://www.nielsen.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/09/2019-20-dma-ranker.pdf |publisher=[[Nielsen Media Research]] |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> [[KONG-TV]], a Seattle-based broadcast channel that is affiliated with [[KING-TV]], has been licensed to Everett sine 1984 and debuted in 1997.<ref>{{cite news |last=Levesque |first=John |date=July 2, 1997 |title=KING grooms KONG for a Monday debut and a spot on cable |page=D10 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer}}</ref> The City of Everett also runs The Everett Channel (formerly Everett TV), a [[government-access television]] station that broadcasts local events, city meetings, and special programming.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Everett Channel |url=https://everettwa.gov/408/Everett-Channel |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wright |first=Diane |date=July 18, 2007 |title=Everett's little TV station that could |page= |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/everetts-little-tv-station-that-could/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Everett itself has four radio stations.<ref>{{cite news |last=Guiney |first=Kelley |date=January 2, 2010 |title=Neighborhood of the week: North Everett |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/realestate/2010652800_realneighborhood03.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107053938/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/realestate/2010652800_realneighborhood03.html |archivedate=January 7, 2010 |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> The Skotdal family owns two stations in Everett that share facilities with the Everett Post: [[KRKO|KRKO-AM]], which began broadcasting in 1922 and primary plays [[Classic hits]] along with local sports;<ref>{{cite web |last=Blecha |first=Peter |date=December 6, 2010 |title=KRKO: Everett's Historic Radio Station |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/9620 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> and [[KKXA|KKXA-AM]], a country music station launched in 2011.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=October 7, 2016 |title=Two Everett AM radio stations approved to broadcast on FM |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/two-everett-am-radio-stations-approved-to-broadcast-on-fm/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Brown |first=Andrea |date=April 10, 2018 |title=An Everett 'potcast' explains what all the buzz is about |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/what-all-the-buzz-is-about/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> [[KSER|KSER-FM]] is an independent [[public radio]] station founded in 1991 to serve Snohomish County, carrying local news, music programming, and nationally syndicated news.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=March 12, 2016 |title=At 25, Everett's KSER still entertains, informs community |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/at-25-everetts-kser-still-entertains-informs-community/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Everett is also the home to [[KWYZ|KWYZ-AM]] (Radio Hankook), a [[Korean language]] news and entertainment station that launched in 1997 and is broadcast from [[Federal Way, Washington|Federal Way]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Virgin |first=Bill |date=June 10, 1999 |title=Korean-language stations a resource for immigrants |page=C6 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kugiya |first=Hugo |date=July 8, 2014 |title=Radio Hankook: The heart of Korea on Washington radio |url=https://crosscut.com/2014/07/korean-radio-hankook-federal-way-seattle |work=[[Crosscut.com]] |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Libraries===\n[[File:Everett Library 01.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Everett Public Library]] in Downtown Everett, built in 1934 and renovated in 1991]]\n\nThe [[Everett Public Library]] system has two locations with 258,133 total items and serves 45,205 registered members in the city and surrounding communities {{as of|2018|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite web |date=September 2019 |title=2018 Washington Public Library Statistical Report |pages=50\u201356 |url=https://www.sos.wa.gov/_assets/library/libraries/libdev/2018stats.pdf |publisher=[[Washington State Library]] |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> The library was founded in 1894 and moved into a [[Everett Carnegie Library|permanent building]] in 1905. The current downtown library opened in 1934 and was expanded in 1991;<ref>{{cite web |last=Van Wingen |first=Melinda |date=December 3, 2019 |title=Everett Public Library |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/20926 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> a branch library in South Everett opened in 1985 and was renovated in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=December 11, 2019 |title=It's a launch for Everett library's renovated Evergreen Branch |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/its-a-launch-for-everett-librarys-renovated-evergreen-branch/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> In 2017, [[Sno-Isle Libraries]], the countywide library system, opened a demonstration branch at a [[strip mall]] in South Everett to serve the Mariner area.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bray |first=Kari |date=February 9, 2017 |title=Everett community finally gets long-awaited library |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-community-finally-gets-long-awaited-library/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Historic preservation===\n[[File:Henry M. Jackson's Home-1.jpg|thumb|Senator [[Henry M. Jackson]]'s home in North Everett]]\n\nEverett is home to 14 properties listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"LandmarkMap\">{{cite map |date=April 23, 2019 |title=Historic Register Properties & Areas |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/19452/Historic-Register-Properties-and-Areas |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref> The city also maintains its own register of historic places that began in 1987 and has 35 listed properties.<ref name=\"Herald-History17\">{{cite news |date=April 7, 2017 |title=Groups work to preserve Everett's rich history |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/advertising/groups-work-to-preserve-everetts-rich-history/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref> A non-profit preservation group, Historic Everett, was founded in 2002 and hosts educational events and tours of the city.<ref name=\"Herald-History17\"/>\n\nIn addition to historic properties, the city has several designated [[Historic districts in the United States|historic districts]]: [[Hewitt Avenue Historic District]] in Downtown Everett; the [[Rucker Hill Historic District]]; and the [[Swalwell Block]]. Several historic overlay districts are designated by the city government, including the Riverside Overlay, the Norton\u2013Grand Overlay, and the Rucker\u2013Grand Overlay, which includes the home of the former U.S. Senator [[Henry M. Jackson]].<ref name=\"LandmarkMap\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=October 21, 2018 |title=Jackson home stays in family, but many treasures to be sold |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/jackson-home-stays-in-family-but-many-treasures-to-be-sold/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Several properties within the historic districts have undergone renovation and restoration work in the 21st century to preserve their historic value, partially in response to the demolition of other buildings for new construction.<ref>{{cite news |last=Chircop |first=David |date=November 2, 2007 |title=How Everett can keep old buildings amid new |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/how-everett-can-keep-old-buildings-amid-new/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Everett Museum of History was established in 1953 as a countywide historical association and maintained its own museum until 2007. The organization's collections moved between several historic buildings, including the former [[Everett Carnegie Library]] and part of the [[Everett Mall]], while a new location was sought.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=August 28, 2016 |title=Everett Museum of History seeks a forever home |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-museum-of-history-seeks-a-forever-home/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref> A permanent museum at the former downtown offices of the ''Everett Herald'' is planned to open in 2021.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=December 21, 2017 |title=A Christmas present for the keepers of Everett's past |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/a-present-for-the-past/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=https://everett-museum.org/everett-museum-of-history/ |publisher=Everett Museum of History |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:Everett Events Center.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Angel of the Winds Arena]], opened in 2003 for the [[Everett Silvertips]] and other teams]]\n\nEverett is home to two sports venues that are used by professional [[minor league]] teams and for other events.<ref name=\"Times-Sports05\">{{cite news |last=Alexander |first=Brian |date=October 19, 2005 |title=Snohomish County minor league teams are a major success |page=H16 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=20051019&slug=minorleagues19n |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The [[Angel of the Winds Arena]], an indoor arena in downtown which seats 8,149, is home to [[Everett Silvertips]] of the [[Western Hockey League]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Watanabe |first=Ben |date=May 4, 2018 |title=Silvertips fans: Meet the enemy stronghold of Swift Current |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/silvertips-fans-meet-the-enemy-stronghold-of-swift-current/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> It opened in 2003 at a cost of $83&nbsp;million and includes a community [[ice rink]] and a [[convention center]] for use by other events.<ref name=\"Times-Arena03\"/> The arena has also hosted basketball games for the [[Seattle Storm]] of the [[WNBA]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Patterson |first=Nick |date=January 16, 2020 |title=Storm returning to Everett for 8 games in 2020 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/storm-returning-to-everett-for-8-games-in-2020/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> indoor tennis events including the [[2020 Fed Cup]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Patterson |first=Nick |date=February 17, 2020 |title=USTA: Everett aces first time hosting Fed Cup qualifier |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/usta-everett-aces-first-time-hosting-fed-cup-qualifier/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> and two editions of the [[Skate America]] figure skating championships in 2008 and 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last=Patterson |first=Nick |date=October 30, 2018 |title=Can Everett become a regular on the figure-skating circuit? |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/skate-americas-encore-in-everett-deemed-a-success/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The [[Everett AquaSox]] of the [[Northwest League]] play at Funko Field, a 3,682-seat baseball stadium that is part of the [[Everett Memorial Stadium]] complex.<ref>{{cite news |last=Calkins |first=Matt |date=August 2, 2019 |title=As he tries to revive MLB career, Felix Hernandez remains King in Everett |page=C1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/mariners/felix-hernandez-after-rehab-start-in-everett-it-feels-good-to-be-back-on-the-mound/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The Memorial Stadium complex was built in 1947 and also includes a 12,000-seat football and track stadium that is used by the city's various high school teams.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=157}}<ref>{{cite news |date=September 6, 2001 |title=Ticket prices and more for region's football stadiums |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=20010906&slug=stadiumweb06 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city formerly had additional indoor sports teams who played in minor leagues: the [[Snohomish County Explosion]], which played from 2008 to 2010 in the defunct [[International Basketball League]];<ref>{{cite news |last=Lommers |first=Aaron |date=April 8, 2011 |title=New owners bring Explosion back to Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/new-owners-bring-explosion-back-to-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> the [[Everett Hawks]] of the [[National Indoor Football League]] and [[AF2]], who folded in 2007; the [[Everett Raptors]] of the [[Indoor Football League]], who played for one season in 2012;<ref>{{cite news |last=Boyle |first=John |date=February 24, 2012 |title=Everett Raptors make their debut Saturday night |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/everett-raptors-make-their-debut-saturday-night/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> and the [[Washington Stealth]] of the [[National Lacrosse League]], who moved to British Columbia in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |date=June 27, 2013 |title=Stealth moving to Langley, B.C. |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/stealth-moving-to-langley-b-c/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nEverett also hosted several minor league soccer teams, including the [[Seattle BigFoot|Everett BigFoot]] of the third-division [[USISL Pro League]], who began play in 1995 and moved to [[West Seattle]] in 1997.<ref>{{cite news |last=Peoples |first=John |date=February 2, 1995 |title=Bigfoot hoping to leave mark on Everett, soccer landscape |page=C9 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19950202&slug=2102732 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=March 17, 1997 |title=Around the Northwest |page=D8 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> The [[North Sound SeaWolves]] of the [[USL Premier Development League]] began play at [[Mariner High School (Everett, Washington)|Mariner High School]] in 2011 and moved to [[Edmonds, Washington|Edmonds]] the following season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Allende |first=Mike |date=October 13, 2011 |title=SeaWolves fans pick team's new logo |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/seawolves-fans-pick-teams-new-logo/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> Everett Jets FC, an ameatur team based at Memorial Stadium, are set to begin their inaugural 2020 season in the [[Evergreen Premier League]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Patterson |first=Nick |date=January 27, 2020 |title=Community sports roundup: Everett Jets FC to join men's league |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/community-sports-roundup-everett-jets-fc-to-join-mens-league/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Club\n! Sport\n! League\n! Founded\n! Venue\n! Championships\n|-\n| [[Everett AquaSox]]\n| align=center | [[Baseball]]\n| [[Northwest League]]\n| align=center | 1984\n| [[Everett Memorial Stadium|Funko Field]]\n| 1985, 2010\n|-\n| [[Everett Jets FC]]\n| align=center | [[Association football|Soccer]]\n| [[Evergreen Premier League]]\n| align=center | 2020\n| [[Everett Memorial Stadium]]\n| \n|-\n| [[Everett Silvertips]]\n| align=center | [[Ice hockey|Hockey]]\n| [[Western Hockey League]]\n| align=center | 2003\n| [[Angel of the Winds Arena]]\n|\n|}\n\n==Parks and recreation==\n[[File:Everett - Grand Ave Park.jpg|thumb|Grand Ave. Park]]\n\nEverett has more than 40 [[city park|parks]], [[hiking trail|trails]], [[golf course]]s, and [[playground]]s maintained by the city government's Parks and Recreation Department.<ref name=\"Herald-Clark\">{{cite news |last=Chircop |first=David |date=September 20, 2006 |title=Everett's first park comes to life |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everetts-first-park-comes-to-life/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The department manages a total of {{convert|693|acre|ha}} of land, with most areas set aside for nature [[wildlife conservation|conservation]] and others developed for use by residents and visitors.<ref name=\"POPS\">{{cite web |year=2015 |title=Everett, Washington Parks, Recreation and Open Space (PROS) Plan |page=28 |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/6455/PROS-PDF |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The department also organizes recreational activities at city parks and throughout the city, including sports leagues, [[swimming]] lessons, hiking trips, and classes on [[cooking]] and [[gardening]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Jackson |first=Sarah |date=May 2, 2008 |title=Get outdoors: Registration begins May 12 for Everett Parks and Rec programs |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/get-outdoors-registration-begins-may-12-for-everett-parks-and-rec-programs/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=January 26, 2009 |title=Everett parks department class makes learning cross-country skiing fun, easy |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/everett-parks-department-class-makes-learning-cross-country-skiing-fun-easy/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city's first park, now known as Clark Park, was established in 1894 and functioned as a [[town square]] with regular concerts and protests until its [[bandstand]] was demolished in 1979.{{sfnp|May|Preboski|1989|pages=12\u201313}} The largest park in Everett, Forest Park, was acquired in late 1894 and was left largely undeveloped until the 1930s.{{sfnp|May|Preboski|1989|p=16}} The parks system includes several facilities with [[Pitch (sports field)|sports fields]] and courts, including Garfield Park, Kasch Park, Henry M. Jackson Park, and Phil Johnson Ballfields.<ref name=\"POPS\"/> The city also operates two public golf courses at American Legion Memorial Park (opened in 1934) and Walter E. Hall Park (opened in 1972).<ref name=\"Herald-Golf\">{{cite news |last=Myhre |first=Rich |date=June 22, 2013 |title=Everett's love affair with golf |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/everetts-love-affair-with-golf/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> A private golf course, the Everett Golf & Country Club, was established in 1910 on {{convert|66|acre|ha}} south of downtown.<ref>{{cite news |last=Myhre |first=Rich |date=May 12, 2010 |title=Everett Golf & Country Club celebrates 100 years of pride and joy |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/everett-golf-country-club-celebrates-100-years-of-pride-and-joy/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe municipal parks system includes several miles of public shoreline access at Howarth Park on Port Gardner Bay, Rotary Park and Langus Riverfront Park on the Snohomish River, and Thornton A. Sullivan Park on Silver Lake.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=June 6, 2015 |title=Days at Snohomish County beaches, parks may take some planning this summer |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/days-at-snohomish-county-beaches-parks-may-take-some-planning-this-summer/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The shoreline parks also include public [[beach]]es and [[boat launch]]es for recreational boating.<ref name=\"POPS\"/> The Port of Everett also has a large public [[marina]] and its own boat launch at 10th Street that also serves a ferry to [[Jetty Island]].<ref>{{cite news |date=July 3, 2018 |title=Everett's economic anchor: Big ships, big marina, big impact |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/everetts-economic-anchor-big-ships-big-marina-big-impact/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Benbow |first=Mike |date=January 12, 2010 |title=$3 parking fee to be added at Everett boat launch |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/3-parking-fee-to-be-added-at-everett-boat-launch/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The state and county governments also maintain their own parks in the Everett area, including the jointly maintained [[Spencer Island Regional Park]].<ref name=\"POPS\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Kelley |first=Tina |date=March 13, 1998 |title=Spencer Island birds rule over factories and freeway |page= |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19980313&slug=2739333 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The city government is also responsible for maintaining a section of the [[Interurban Trail (Snohomish County)|Interurban Trail]], which connects Everett to Lynnwood, [[Mountlake Terrace, Washington|Mountlake Terrace]], [[Shoreline, Washington|Shoreline]], and Seattle.<ref name=\"Herald-Interurban\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Debra |date=October 9, 2011 |title=Danger on trails |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/danger-on-trails/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> North Everett is ringed by the [[Mill Town Trail]], a {{convert|6|mi|km|adj=mid|spell=in}} multi-use pathway with interpretive signs to commemorate the city's industrial history.<ref name=\"Herald-WaterfrontHist\"/>\n\n===Major parks===\n\nForest Park, located southwest of Downtown Everett is the largest park in the city system, at {{convert|197|acre|ha}}.<ref name=\"POPS\"/>{{rp|52}} The park is situated along Pigeon Creek, with recreational facilities on a plateau overlooking the ravine and several miles of hiking trails. It was acquired by the city in 1894 and named Forest Park in 1913. A public [[zoo]] was established at Forest Park in 1914 by parks director Oden Hall, who collected animals through trades and gifts from other zoos and traveling circuses. The zookeeper position was eliminated in 1958 and the zoo was demolished in 1962 after three [[bond issue]]s to upgrade the facilities failed.{{sfnp|May|Preboski|1989|p=16}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=June 4, 2015 |title=Nostalgia tinged with sadness: The story of Forest Park Zoo |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/nostalgia-tinged-with-sadness-the-story-of-forest-park-zoo/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Forest Park's main facilities were built during the 1930s by the [[Works Progress Administration]], including the Floral Hall, playgrounds, terrace hillsides, and picnic shelters.<ref name=\"Herald-WPAForest\"/> A public [[swimming pool]] was opened at Forest Park in 1975 and replaced by a permanent structure in 1984.{{sfnp|May|Preboski|1989|p=19}} Major renovations of the facilities in the park were completed in 1997 and 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Watanabe |first=Ben |date=January 4, 2020 |title=Popular Forest Park playground to close 4 months for upgrade |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/forest-park-playground-to-close-for-major-renovation/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe largest park in North Everett is [[American Legion Memorial Park]], a {{convert|140|acre|ha|adj=mid}} open space located on the peninsula's northwest bluff at the site of a former [[Snohomish people|Snohomish]] village and [[smelter]].{{sfnp|May|Preboski|1989|pages=76\u201378}} The majority of the park is occupied by a golf course that was built by the [[American Legion]] and transferred to the city government alongside the rest of the park in 1935.<ref name=\"Herald-Golf\"/> The [[Evergreen Arboretum and Gardens|Evergreen Arboretum]] was built in 1963 at the northwest edge of the golf course, alongside a [[picnic shelter]] and the county's history museum.{{sfnp|May|Preboski|1989|pages=76\u201378}} A [[scenic viewpoint]] on the park grounds with views of the [[Olympic Mountains]] was named Hibulb Lookout in 2014, commemorating the historic Snohomish village at the site.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=December 12, 2014 |title=Everett bluff and trail get new names |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-bluff-and-trail-get-new-names/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Jetty Island]] is an [[artificial island]] located in Port Gardner that is {{convert|2|mi|km}} long and is home to sandy beaches and wildlife habitats. The island was formed from dredging of the [[Snohomish River]] in the early 20th century and acquired by the [[Port of Everett]] in 1929.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brown |first=Andrea |date=July 5, 2017 |title=The ferry is running! How to enjoy Everett's Jetty Island |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/the-riviera-of-everett-jetty-island-season-opens-july-5/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The city began operating a seasonal ferry between the island and a waterfront parking area in 1985; the ferry now runs from July to September, serving 50,000 visitors annually.<ref name=\"Herald-Jetty18\">{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Joseph |date=July 11, 2018 |title=Jetty Island opens for family-friendly fun |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/jetty-island-opens-for-the-season/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=McQuaide |first=Mike |date=July 28, 2010 |title=Everett's Jetty Island is an oasis of sand, sunshine and sweet memories |page= |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/outdoors/2012469134_nwwjettyisland29.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903115111/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/outdoors/2012469134_nwwjettyisland29.html |archivedate=September 3, 2011 |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Jetty Island is home to more than 115 identified bird species, salmon habitats, and mollusks.<ref name=\"Herald-Jetty18\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Stevick |first=Eric |date=August 17, 2007 |title=Digging into Jetty Island |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/digging-into-jetty-island/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Everett High School-1.jpg|thumb|[[Everett High School (Washington)|Everett High School]] (part of Everett Public Schools)]]\n\nThe city's public education system is managed by [[Everett Public Schools (Washington)|Everett Public Schools]] (officially the Everett School District), which has 26 schools, 2,000 staff members, and an enrollment of 20,000 students.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cornfield |first=Jerry |date=October 29, 2019 |title=In Everett school races, they agree more than they don't |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/in-everett-school-races-they-agree-more-than-they-dont/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Times-Cohn\">{{cite news |date=November 18, 2016 |title=Everett schools chief honored as state Superintendent of Year |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/education/everett-schools-chief-named-state-supe-of-2017/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=November 21, 2016}}</ref> The school district covers {{convert|52|sqmi|sqkm}}, including most of Everett, the city of [[Mill Creek, Washington|Mill Creek]], and the unincorporated area of [[Silver Firs, Washington|Silver Firs]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Census 2010: Everett School District |url=http://data.spokesman.com/census/2010/washington/school-districts/everett-school-district-wa/ |work=[[The Spokesman-Review]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110304004210/http://data.spokesman.com/census/2010/washington/school-districts/everett-school-district-wa/ |archivedate=March 4, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The southern and western neighborhoods of Everett are served by the [[Mukilteo School District]], which also has its own high school ([[Mariner High School (Everett, Washington)|Mariner]]) in the area.<ref>{{cite map |date=December 21, 2017 |title=Snohomish County School Districts Map |url=http://www.snoco.org/docs/scd/PDF/PDS_CFP/Snohomish%20County%20School%20District.pdf |publisher=Snohomish County |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett Public Schools has three high school campuses: [[Everett High School (Washington)|Everett High School]] near downtown, [[Cascade High School (Everett, Washington)|Cascade High School]] near Casino Corner, and [[Henry M. Jackson High School]] in Mill Creek.<ref name=\"Herald-HighSchool19\">{{cite news |last=Bryan |first=Zachariah |date=May 22, 2019 |title=After year of debate, Everett has new high school boundaries |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/after-year-of-debate-everett-has-new-high-school-boundaries/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The school district was recognized in 2016 for its high [[graduation]] rates of 90 percent for four-year students and 94.5 percent for five-year students.<ref name=\"Times-Cohn\"/> A fourth high school campus, planned to cost $220&nbsp;million to build, was part of a [[bond measure]] in February 2018 that was rejected by voters, resulting in boundary changes for the existing schools.<ref name=\"Herald-HighSchool19\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Cornfield |first=Jerry |date=September 22, 2019 |title=Trying again. Everett schools eye a $317M bond in 2020 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/trying-again-everett-schools-eye-a-317m-bond-in-2020/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The school district also has five [[middle school]]s and 18 [[elementary school]]s in Everett and Mill Creek.<ref>{{cite web |title=2019-20 Boundary Map |url=https://www.everettsd.org/Page/29519 |publisher=[[Everett Public Schools (Washington)|Everett Public Schools]] |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Stevick |first=Eric |date=December 8, 2018 |title=Meet Tambark Creek. Everett has a new kid on the block |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/meet-tambark-creek-everett-has-a-new-kid-on-the-block/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The city is also home to two [[alternative school]]s: Sequoia High School, operated by Everett Public Schools;<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mulligan |first1=Mark |last2=Mulligan |first2=Annie |date=June 28, 2013 |title=If students have the will, Sequoia High has the way |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/if-students-have-the-will-sequoia-high-has-the-way/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> and ACES High School, operated by the Mukilteo School District.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hutton |first=Caleb |date=December 6, 2018 |title=Teen guilty of plotting a massive school shooting in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-teen-with-gun-guilty-of-plotting-school-shooting/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Everett area is also home to several [[private school]] systems operated by religious organizations and independent educators, including those that cater to commuters from around the county. The largest private high school in the county is [[Archbishop Murphy High School]], a Catholic school located in southeastern Everett, with an enrollment of 500 students.<ref>{{cite news |last=Slager |first=Melissa |date=December 9, 2006 |title=Private school enrollment rises |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/stories/06/12/09/100loc_b1schools001.cfm |work=The Everett Herald |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061214170329/http://www.heraldnet.com/stories/06/12/09/100loc_b1schools001.cfm |archivedate=December 14, 2006 |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Other major private religious schools include the [[Everett Christian School]], Cedar Park Christian School, and Northshore Christian Academy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Koenig |first=Sarah |date=January 10, 2008 |title=Cedar Park takes over North Sound Christian Schools |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/uncategorized/cedar-park-takes-over-north-sound-christian-schools/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Higher education===\n\n[[Everett Community College]] (EvCC) is a two-year public [[community college]] that has enrolled 19,000 students from around Snohomish County and 463 total faculty.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=October 14, 2015 |title=Developer to build dormitory near Everett Community College |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/developer-to-build-dormitory-near-everett-community-college/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=College Navigator: Everett Community College |url=https://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?id=235149 |work=[[National Center for Education Statistics]] |publisher=[[Institute of Education Sciences]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The college's main campus is located <!--spans {{convert||acre|ha}}--> in North Everett on the south side of Legion Memorial Golf Course.<ref name=\"Times-WSU11\">{{cite news |last=Long |first=Katherine |date=May 23, 2011 |title=Steps taken toward creating WSU branch campus in Everett |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2015129940_wsu24m.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202073035/http://old.seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2015129940_wsu24m.html |archivedate=February 2, 2017 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> It was established in 1941 at a former downtown elementary school and moved to its North Everett location in 1958, where it has since expanded several times.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=210\u2013211}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Slager |first1=Melissa |last2=Warnick |first2=Jennifer |date=August 13, 2005 |title=EvCC carving a place to grow |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/evcc-carving-a-place-to-grow/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCivic and business leaders from the Everett area began lobbying the state legislature for a four-year college in the 1990s, proposing a branch of an existing state college to serve Snohomish, Island, and Skagit counties.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brooks |first=Diane |date=December 2, 1994 |title=Bid for college alive in Everett |page=B1 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> A site in [[Bothell, Washington|Bothell]] was instead chosen for a [[University of Washington Bothell|northern branch campus]] for the [[University of Washington]] (UW), but only 27 percent of its students were from Snohomish County.<ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Lynn |date=August 17, 2005 |title=Push for 4-year college revs up |page=H18 |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/education/2002442337_4year17n.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306202952/http://old.seattletimes.com/html/education/2002442337_4year17n.html |archivedate=March 6, 2018 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Stevick |first=Eric |date=August 22, 2005 |title=Ideas floated for new university |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/ideas-floated-for-new-university/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> In 2007, the state legislature authorized planning funds for a UW branch campus in Snohomish County and a site near [[Everett Station]] was named as a finalist alongside candidates in Lake Stevens and Marysville.<ref name=\"Times-WSU11\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Perry |first=Nick |date=January 6, 2008 |title=UW Everett: ambitious, but dogged by doubts |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/uw-everett-ambitious-but-dogged-by-doubts/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The [[University of Washington North Sound|branch campus project]] was shelved by the state legislature in 2008 amid a funding shortfall for the education system.<ref name=\"Herald-Degrees08\">{{cite news |last=Stevick |first=Eric |date=November 23, 2008 |title=College degrees available in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/college-degrees-available-in-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Washington State University Everett]] opened in 2017 as a branch campus of WSU and is located adjacent to the EvCC campus in North Everett.<ref name=\"Times-WSU17\">{{cite news |last=Long |first=Katherine |date=August 11, 2017 |title=WSU's new building: 'the biggest thing Everett has ever done in terms of its future' |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/education/wsus-new-building-the-biggest-thing-everett-has-ever-done-in-terms-of-its-future/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The branch campus was conceived as a replacement for the UW proposal and included a WSU takeover of the [[University Center of North Puget Sound]], an alternative degrees program at EvCC, in 2014.<ref name=\"Times-WSU11\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Harper |first=Christina |date=June 30, 2014 |title=WSU taking over University Center at EvCC |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/wsu-taking-over-university-center-at-evcc/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The EvCC campus also houses a branch of [[Western Washington University]], which it established in 1986.<ref>{{cite web |title=Everett |url=https://www.wwu.edu/everett |publisher=[[Western Washington University]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Haglund |first1=Noah |last2=Stevick |first2=Eric |date=August 16, 2017 |title=At long last, WSU Everett's new building is open for business |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/at-long-last-wsu-everetts-new-building-open-for-business/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett is also home to several private and specialized colleges, including [[City University of Seattle|City University]] and [[Everest College]] near the Everett Mall.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 27, 2011 |title=Snohomish County colleges |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/snohomish-county-colleges/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=November 13, 2017 |title=Altierus to close Everett college, layoff 29 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/altierus-to-close-everett-college-layoff-29/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The city also has branch campuses for [[Embry\u2013Riddle Aeronautical University]] near the Boeing assembly plant and [[Columbia College (Missouri)|Columbia College]] at Naval Station Everett.<ref>{{cite web |title=Locations: Everett, WA |url=https://worldwide.erau.edu/locations/everett |publisher=[[Embry\u2013Riddle Aeronautical University]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=August 26, 2015 |title=Columbia College celebrates 20 years in Snohomish County |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/columbia-college-celebrates-20-years-in-snohomish-county/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Everett's two major [[Lutheran]] churches operated a pair of short-lived private colleges in the early 20th century, Bethania College and Columbia College.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=210\u2013211}} [[Henry Cogswell College]], a private institution, moved from Kirkland to Everett in 1996 and closed in 2006.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brooks |first=Diane |date=March 21, 1996 |title=4-year school to locate in Everett |page=B3 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19960321&slug=2320138 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stevick |first1=Eric |last2=Chircop |first2=David |date=June 29, 2006 |title=Cogswell College will close |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/cogswell-college-will-close/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> In the 2010s, [[Bryman College]] and [[Trinity Lutheran College (Washington)|Trinity Lutheran College]] both closed their Everett campuses.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=January 12, 2016 |title=Trinity Lutheran College in downtown Everett to close |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/trinity-lutheran-college-in-downtown-everett-to-close/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Infrastructure==\n\n===Transportation===\n[[File:Everett Station building.jpg|thumb|[[Everett Station]], the city's [[Amtrak]] and [[Sounder commuter rail]] station that also serves local and express buses]]\n\nThe city is located along [[Interstate 5 in Washington|Interstate 5]] (I-5), a major north\u2013south freeway that connects Everett to [[Seattle]] and [[Vancouver]], British Columbia. The Everett\u2013Seattle section of I-5 is rated as one of the most congested in the United States during commuting hours, with an average of 94 minutes to travel {{convert|24|mi|km}} and 182,000 daily vehicles in South Everett.<ref name=\"Times-Traffic18\"/> The city also has several major highways with intercity connections, including [[U.S. Route 2 in Washington|U.S. Route 2]] to [[Wenatchee, Washington|Wenatchee]] via [[Stevens Pass]]; [[Washington State Route 99|State Route 99]] from the Everett Mall to Seattle; [[Washington State Route 526|State Route 526]] to Mukilteo; [[Washington State Route 527|State Route 527]] from the Everett Mall to Mill Creek; and [[Washington State Route 529|State Route 529]] from the waterfront to Marysville.<ref name=\"WSDOT-Map\"/>\n\nEverett has several public transit and intercity transport services that intersect at [[Everett Station]], a multimodal train and bus station that opened in 2002.<ref name=\"Times-Station03\"/> The station is served by two [[Amtrak]] routes: [[Amtrak Cascades|''Cascades'']], which connects Vancouver to Seattle and [[Portland, Oregon]]; and the ''[[Empire Builder]]'', which travels from Seattle to [[Chicago]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Cantwell |first=Brian J. |date=December 10, 2015 |title=Amtrak restores train service through Washington state |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/life/travel/amtrak-restores-service-through-washington-state/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Everett is also the northern terminus of the [[Sounder commuter rail]] system, which is operated by [[Sound Transit]] and travels south to Seattle during [[peak hour]]s with stops in Mukilteo and Edmonds.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lindblom |first=Mike |date=October 16, 2012 |title=Too many empty seats on Sounder north line |page=A1 |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2019441910_sounder16m.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514123023/http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2019441910_sounder16m.html |archivedate=May 14, 2013 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The station is served by intercity buses from [[Greyhound Lines]], [[BoltBus]], and [[Northwestern Trailways]], which connect Everett to cities in the Pacific Northwest.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sheets |first=Bill |date=February 6, 2012 |title=Everett Station celebrates 10 years and 17 million visits |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-station-celebrates-10-years-and-17-million-visits/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Podsada |first=Janice |date=March 8, 2019 |title=BoltBus links Everett to Seattle and other big I-5 cities |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/discount-bus-service-launches-from-everett-station/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The passenger trains operate on tracks owned by [[BNSF Railway]], which operates freight service and maintains a major railyard in Northeast Everett.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=January 18, 2015 |title=Railroad loop proposed on Everett's Smith Island |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/railroad-loop-proposed-on-everetts-smith-island/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city-run [[Everett Transit]] system was established in 1969, replacing a private operator that had opened the first [[streetcar]] lines in the city in 1893.<ref>{{cite news |date=November 30, 2008 |title=Everett Transit rolls back fares for 115th birthday |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/around-the-county-346/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The countywide [[Community Transit]] system, based in Everett, connects to surrounding cities and operates a commuter bus network.<ref>{{cite map |date=September 2019 |title=Community Transit System Map |url=https://www.communitytransit.org/docs/default-source/mappdfs/19septmaps/systemmappdfs/mapsystemsept2019.pdf |publisher=[[Community Transit]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Its [[bus rapid transit]] system, [[Swift Bus Rapid Transit|Swift]] has two lines that travel through the city: the [[Swift Blue Line|Blue Line]] from Downtown Everett to [[Shoreline, Washington|Shoreline]] via State Route 99; and the [[Swift Green Line|Green Line]], which connects the Boeing plant to Mill Creek and northern Bothell.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=March 21, 2019 |title=From Bothell to Boeing: Green Line bus route begins Sunday |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/major-changes-coming-to-community-transit-in-march/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Sound Transit also provides [[Sound Transit Express|express bus service]] to [[Bellevue, Washington|Bellevue]] during peak hours and Downtown Seattle at all hours.<ref>{{cite web |date=December 2017 |title=2017 Service Implementation Plan |pages=116\u2013117, 140\u2013141 |url=https://www.soundtransit.org/sites/default/files/2018-service-implementation-plan.pdf |publisher=[[Sound Transit]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The agency plans to extend its [[Link light rail]] service to Downtown Everett in 2036, as part of the [[Sound Transit 3]] plan passed by voters in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haglund |first1=Noah |last2=Giordano |first2=Lizz |date=June 25, 2018 |title=It's getting real: Light rail is coming to the 'burbs |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/its-getting-real-light-rail-is-coming-to-the-burbs/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> From 1910 to 1939, Everett was connected with Seattle by an [[interurban]] railway, which was later replaced by the [[Interurban Trail (Snohomish County)|Interurban Trail]].<ref name=\"Herald-Interurban\"/>\n\nEverett's airport, [[Paine Field]], is operated by Snohomish County primarily for aerospace businesses and general aviation. The airport was opened in 1936 and was used as a military base and commercial airport until 1966, when Boeing selected it for the site of a major assembly plant.<ref>{{cite news |date=August 7, 2004 |title=Paine Field's journey to flight |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/paine-fields-journey-to-flight/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Commercial passenger service to Paine Field resumed on March 4, 2019, after the construction of a new terminal operated by a private company.<ref name=\"Times-Paine\"/> The nearest major airports are [[Boeing Field]] in Seattle and [[Seattle-Tacoma International Airport]] in southern King County.<ref name=\"Times-Paine\"/> A private passenger ferry from the Port of Everett provides access to [[Gedney Island|Hat Island]] in Possession Sound.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=July 31, 2018 |title=Hat Island: The somewhat secret, other-worldy Northwest gem |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/close-yet-another-world-its-quite-a-voyage-to-hat-island/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Utilities===\n\n[[Electric power]] for Everett buildings is provided by the [[Snohomish County Public Utility District]] (PUD), a consumer-owned [[public utility]] that serves all of Snohomish County.<ref>{{cite web |date=October 2018 |title=Quick Facts for Snohomish County PUD |url=https://www.snopud.com/Site/Content/Documents/custpubs/MiniQF_1018.pdf |publisher=[[Snohomish County Public Utility District]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129142056/https://www.snopud.com/Site/Content/Documents/custpubs/MiniQF_1018.pdf |archivedate=November 29, 2018 |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The privately run [[Puget Sound Energy]] provides [[natural gas]] service to the city's residents and businesses.<ref>{{cite web |year=2013 |title=Puget Sound Energy service area |url=http://pse.com/aboutpse/PseNewsroom/MediaKit/1213_ServiceAreaMap_web.pdf |publisher=[[Puget Sound Energy]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170128213047/https://pse.com/aboutpse/PseNewsroom/MediaKit/1213_ServiceAreaMap_web.pdf |archivedate=January 28, 2017 |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The city government contracts with Rubatino Refuse Removal and [[Waste Management (corporation)|Waste Management]] for curbside [[municipal solid waste|garbage]], [[single-stream recycling|recycling]], and [[yard waste]] collection and disposal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Garbage, Recycling & Compost |url=https://everettwa.gov/637/Garbage-Recycling-Compost |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Everett's municipal [[wastewater]] and [[sewage]] system, which is combined with [[stormwater]] treatment, includes {{convert|145|mi|km}} of pipes that primarily feed into the [[Everett Water Pollution Control Facility]] on Smith Island and empties in the Snohomish River delta.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=December 4, 2014 |title=$320M fix prescribed for Everett's aging sewers |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/320m-fix-prescribed-for-everett%C2%92s-aging-sewers/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Sanders |first=Julia-Grace |date=September 12, 2019 |title=Stench wrinkles noses in some north Everett neighborhoods |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/odor-overwhelms-some-north-everett-neighborhoods/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe City of Everett maintains a [[tap water]] system that supplies 80 percent of Snohomish County through interlocal agreements with other municipalities and [[water district]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sheets |first=Bill |date=October 13, 2011 |title=Environmental plan earns Sultan River dam a new 45-year license |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/environmental-plan-earns-sultan-river-dam-a-new-45-year-license/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=November 2004 |title=Where Does Your Water Come From? |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/824/Where-Does-Your-Water-Come-From-PDF |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The system primarily sources its water from [[Spada Lake]], an artificial reservoir on the [[Sultan River]] created by the [[Culmback Dam]] located {{convert|25|mi|km}} east of Everett in the Cascade Mountains. The water is treated at a [[water purification|filtration plant]] at Lake Chaplain, the system's secondary water source, which has a capacity of {{convert|134|e6USgal|kl}} per day and typically handles {{convert|50|e6gal|kl|abbr=unit}} per day.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=September 8, 2016 |title=Anticipating growth, Everett looks to boost water flow |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-to-test-increasing-water-flow-to-customers/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The Sultan River basin has been used as the main source of the city's water since 1917 and uses a {{convert|25|mi|km|adj=mid}} network of pipes to reach Everett; the modern Spada Lake reservoir was formed in 1965 by the construction of the Culmback Dam, co-owned by Everett and the Snohomish County PUD.{{sfnp|Dorpat|McCovy|1998|p=207}}{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=187}}\n\nThe city is covered by several telecommunications companies that provide [[telephone]], [[broadband internet]], and other services. [[Frontier Communications Northwest|Frontier Communications]] is the largest telecommunications provider in the city and inherited its legacy system from [[GTE|GTE Northwest]] and [[Verizon]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Podsada |first=Janice |date=June 3, 2019 |title=A new-wave broadband firm dials up Frontier Communications |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/a-new-wave-broadband-firm-dials-up-frontier-communications/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Other major providers in the Everett area include [[Xfinity|Comcast Xfinity]], [[CenturyLink]], and [[Wave Broadband]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Everett Comprehensive Plan Capital Facilities and Utilities Element |page=36 |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/4861/Chapter-06-Capital-Facilities-and-Utilities-PDF |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Healthcare===\n\nEverett is home to [[Providence Regional Medical Center Everett]], a system of two general hospitals operated by [[Providence Health & Services]]. The hospital system was formed in 1994 by the merger of two existing hospitals in Everett: the Everett General Hospital, opened in January 1894 as the city's first hospital;{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=211}} and Providence Hospital, established in 1905 near Downtown Everett.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Providence Story |url=https://washington.providence.org/locations-directory/r/regional-medical-center/about/history |publisher=[[Providence Health & Services]] |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=August 27, 2014 |title=Spirit of giving is a cornerstone of Snohomish County history |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/spirit-of-giving-is-a-cornerstone-of-snohomish-county-history/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The existing Providence Hospital was renamed the Providence Pacific Campus, while the former General Hospital became the Colby Campus, which was expanded in 2011 with a 12-story medical tower.<ref name=\"Herald-Providence11\"/> The Providence campuses have a combined capacity of 571 beds and 3,300 employees.<ref name=\"Herald-Providence11\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=January 16, 2017 |title=Everett Providence hospital seeks state OK for 70 more beds |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-providence-hospital-seeks-state-ok-for-70-more-beds/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city also has several medical services with [[clinic]]s and specialized facilities operated by Providence and other providers. [[Kaiser Permanente]] has a five-story medical tower in Downtown Everett with a walk-in clinic, specialty services, and an [[urgent care]] clinic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Everett Medical Center |url=https://wa.kaiserpermanente.org/html/public/locations/everett |publisher=[[Kaiser Permanente]] |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The building originally opened for [[Group Health Cooperative|Group Health]] in 1994 to consolidate its three clinics in Everett and is planned to be expanded in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Alexander |first=Karen |date=April 30, 1993 |title=Group Health sets Everett groundbreaker |page=D8 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=October 2, 2019 |title=Kaiser Permanente plans big growth spurt in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/kaiser-permanente-plans-big-growth-spurt-in-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> [[The Everett Clinic]] is based in the city and operates medical facilities across Snohomish County, serving 320,000 patients.<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=February 29, 2016 |title=DaVita HealthCare Partners completes Everett Clinic purchase |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/davita-healthcare-partners-completes-everett-clinic-purchase/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The system was founded in 1924 and acquired in 2016 by [[DaVita Inc.]]; it was then sold to [[UnitedHealth Group]]'s [[Optum]] a year later.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=December 6, 2017 |title=DaVita to sell off medical groups including The Everett Clinic |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/davita-to-sell-off-medical-groups-including-the-everett-clinic/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The non-profit Community Health Center of Snohomish County operates four medical clinics in Everett, providing services to primarily low-income and uninsured patients.<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=January 16, 2018 |title=New Everett clinic to ease long wait times for appointments |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/community-health-center-opening-its-seventh-clinic/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n{{main|List of people from Everett, Washington}}\n\nEverett was the hometown of U.S. Senator [[Henry M. Jackson]], Washington governors [[Roland H. Hartley]] and [[Monrad Wallgren]], and several members of the U.S. Congress and Washington state legislature.<ref>{{cite news |date=April 23, 2008 |title=Seems Like Yesterday |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/seems-like-yesterday-1298/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The city has also produced several [[American football]] coaches under tutelage of Everett High School coach [[Jim Ennis (American football)|Jim Ennis]], including [[Jim Lambright]], [[Mike Price]], and [[Dennis Erickson]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Boyle |first=John |date=August 30, 2011 |title=Coaching close to home |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/coaching-close-to-home/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Christilaw |first=Steve |date=August 10, 1990 |title=Legendary Everett coach dies\u2014Ennis inspired many, friends say |page= |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19900810&slug=1087044 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Sister cities==\n\nEverett has the following [[Town twinning|sister city]] relationships:<ref>{{cite web |title=Washington's Sister Cities Relationships |url=https://www.ltgov.wa.gov/washington-sister-cities |publisher=[[Lieutenant Governor of Washington]] |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* {{flagdeco|JPN}} [[Iwakuni]], [[Yamaguchi Prefecture|Yamaguchi]], Japan (since 1962)<ref>{{cite news |last=Fiege |first=Gale |date=July 23, 2012 |title=Everett celebrates 50 years with Japanese sister city |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-celebrates-50-years-with-japanese-sister-city/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n* {{flagdeco|IRL}} [[Sligo]], [[County Sligo]], Ireland\n* {{flagdeco|RUS}} [[Sovetskaya Gavan]], [[Khabarovsk Krai]], Russia (since 1991)<ref>{{cite news |last=Shaw |first=Linda |date=August 21, 1991 |title=Soviet radio operator reports quiet in Everett's sister city |page=B1 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19910821&slug=1301058 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last1=Cameron |first1=David A. |last2=LeWarne |first2=Charles P. |last3=May |first3=M. Allan |last4=O'Donnell |first4=Jack C. |last5=O'Donnell |first5=Lawrence E. |year=2005 |title=Snohomish County: An Illustrated History |publisher=Kelcema Books LLC |location=Index, Washington |isbn=978-0-9766700-0-1 |oclc=62728798}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last1=Dorpat |first1=Paul |authorlink1=Paul Dorpat |last2=McCovy |first2=Genevieve |year=1998 |title=Building Washington: A History of Washington State Public Works |publisher=Tartu Publications |location=Seattle |isbn=0-9614357-9-8 |oclc=40406154}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last1=May |first1=Allan |last2=Preboski |first2=Dale |year=1989 |title=The History of Everett Parks: A Century of Service and Vision |publisher=[[The Donning Company]] |location=Norfolk, Virginia |isbn=0-89865-794-6 |oclc=20453314}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=O'Donnell |first=Lawrence E. |year=1993 |title=Everett Past and Present: A Centennial History of Everett |publisher=K&H Printers |location=Everett |isbn=978-0-89716-275-3 |oclc=436832753}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Prosser |first=William Farrand |authorlink=William Farrand Prosser |year=1903 |title=A History of the Puget Sound Country |publisher=[[Lewis Publishing Company]] |location=New York |oclc=14570355 |url=https://archive.org/details/ahistorypugetso00prosgoog/ |via=[[The Internet Archive]] |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Whitfield |first=William M. |year=1926 |title=History of Snohomish County, Washington |publisher=Pioneer Historical Publishing Company |location=Chicago |oclc=8437390 |url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/102122401 |via=[[HathiTrust]] |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}\n{{refend}}\n\n===Further reading===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Clark |first=Norman H. |year=1970 |title=Mill Town: A Social History of Everett, Washington, From Its Earliest Beginnings on the Shores of Puget Sound to the Tragic and Infamous Event Known as the Everett Massacre |publisher=[[University of Washington Press]] |location=Seattle |isbn=978-0-295-95241-3 |oclc=28005191}}\n{{refend}}\n\n===Archives===\n{{refbegin}}\n* [http://digital.lib.washington.edu/findingaids/view?docId=EverettEducationAssociation3849.xml Everett Education Association Records.] 1937\u20132002. 28.06 cubic feet. At the [http://www.lib.washington.edu/specialcoll/laws Labor Archives of Washington], [[University of Washington Libraries]] Special Collections.\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{EB1911 Poster|Everett, Washington}}\n* {{wikivoyage-inline|Everett (Washington)|Everett, Washington}}\n* {{official website|https://www.everettwa.gov/}}\n* {{dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Washington/Localities/E/Everett}}\n\n{{Everett, Washington}}\n{{Snohomish County, Washington}}\n{{Washington}}\n{{Seattle Metro}}\n{{Geographic Location (8-way)\n|Northwest = [[Port Gardner Bay]]\n|North     = [[Tulalip Indian Reservation]]/[[Marysville, Washington|Marysville]]\n|Northeast = [[Marysville, Washington|Marysville]]/[[Lake Stevens, Washington|Lake Stevens]]\n|West      = [[Gedney Island (Washington)|Hat Island]]/[[Possession Sound]]\n|Center    = Everett\n|South     = [[Mill Creek, Washington|Mill Creek]]/[[Lynnwood, Washington|Lynnwood]]\n|Southwest = [[Mukilteo, Washington|Mukilteo]]\n|Southeast = [[Snohomish, Washington|Snohomish]]\n|East      = [[Lake Stevens, Washington|Lake Stevens]]\n}}\n{{Washington cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Everett, Washington| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Cities in Snohomish County, Washington]]\n[[Category:Cities in the Seattle metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:County seats in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1890]]\n[[Category:Populated places on Puget Sound]]\n[[Category:Port settlements in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:1890 establishments in Washington (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Everett\n|official_name            = City of Everett\n|other_name = [[Lushootseed]]: ''{{lang|lut|d\u1dbb\u0259\u026cig\u02b7\u0259d}}''<ref name=\"Lushootseed1994\">{{cite book |last1=Bates |first1=Dawn |last2=Hess |first2=Thom |last3=Hilbert |first3=Vi |year=1994 |title=d\u1dbb\u0259\u026big\u02b7\u0259d |page=90 |work=Lushootseed Dictionary |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ekq921r1kV0C |publisher=University of Washington Press |isbn=0-295-97323-4 |oclc=843308724 |via=Google Books}}</ref>\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|image_skyline            = Everett Station and Everett skyline, April 2020.jpg\n|image_caption            = [[Everett Station]] and the city skyline\n|image_seal               = Everett logo.svg\n|image_blank_emblem       = Logo of Everett, Washington (horizontal).svg\n|blank_emblem_type        = Logo\n|blank_emblem_size        = 150px\n|image_map                = Snohomish_County_Washington_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Everett_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Everett, Washington\n|pushpin_map              = USA\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location in the United States\n|subdivision_type         = Country\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Washington|County]]\n|subdivision_name         = [[United States]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish]]\n|established_title        = Established\n|established_date         = 1890\n|established_title2       = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]]\n|established_date2        = May 4, 1893\n|government_type          = [[Mayor\u2013council government|Mayor\u2013council]]\n|leader_title             = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name              = Cassie Franklin\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web |title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files |url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_53.txt |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=February 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_sq_mi         = 47.91\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 33.20\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 14.71\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 111262\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes        = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name=\"QuickFacts\"/>\n|population_total         = 103019\n|population_density_sq_mi = 3351.47\n|population_metro         = 3,939,363 (US: [[List of Metropolitan Statistical Areas|15th]])\n|population_rank          = US: [[List of United States cities by population|270th]]<br />WA: 7th\n|population_demonym       = Everettite\n|timezone                 = [[Pacific Time Zone|PST]]\n|utc_offset               = &minus;8\n|timezone_DST             = [[Pacific Daylight Time|PDT]]\n|utc_offset_DST           = &minus;7\n|coordinates              = {{coord|47|58|45|N|122|12|06|W|region:US-WA_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = Zip codes\n|postal_code = 98201, 98203, 98204, 98206, 98207, 98208, 98213<ref>{{cite web |title=Look Up a ZIP Code\u2122 |url=https://tools.usps.com/go/zip-code-lookup.htm |publisher=[[United States Postal Service]] |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n|area_code                = [[Area code 425|425]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 53-22640\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1512198<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov |accessdate=January 31, 2008 |title=US Board on Geographic Names |publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]] |date=October 25, 2007}}</ref>\n|website                  = {{URL|everettwa.gov}}\n|footnotes                = \n|area_total_km2           = 124.09\n|area_land_km2            = 85.98\n|area_water_km2           = 38.11\n|population_density_km2   = 1294.01\n}}\n\n'''Everett''' is the [[county seat]] of and the largest city in [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], United States. It is located {{convert|25|mi|km|0}} north of [[Seattle]] and is one of the main cities in the [[Seattle metropolitan area|metropolitan area]] and [[Puget Sound region]]. Everett is the [[List of cities and towns in Washington|seventh-largest]] city in Washington state by population, with a total of 103,019 residents at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]]. The city is located on a peninsula at the mouth of the [[Snohomish River]] along [[Port Gardner Bay]], an inlet of [[Possession Sound]] (itself part of [[Puget Sound]]).\n\nThe Port Gardner Peninsula was historically inhabited by the [[Snohomish people]], who had a winter village named Hibulb near the mouth of the river. American settlement in the area began with loggers and homesteaders arriving in the 1860s, but plans to build a city were not conceived until 1890. A consortium of East Coast investors seeking to build a major industrial city acquired land in the area and filed a [[plat]]ted for \"Everett\", which they named in honor of [[Everett Colby]], the son of investor [[Charles L. Colby]]. The city was [[municipal incorporation|incorporated]] in 1893, shortly after the arrival of the [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]], and prospered as a major lumber center with several large [[sawmill]]s.\n\nEverett became the county seat in 1897 after a dispute with [[Snohomish, Washington|Snohomish]] contested over several elections and a [[Washington Supreme Court|Supreme Court]] case. The city was the site of labor unrest during the 1910s, which culminated in the [[Everett massacre]] in 1916 that killed several members of the [[Industrial Workers of the World]]. The area was connected by new [[interurban]] railways and highway bridges in the 1920s, transforming it into a major commercial hub, and gained an airport at [[Paine Field]] in 1936.\n\nThe city's economy transitioned away from lumber and towards aerospace after [[World War II]], with the construction of [[Boeing]]'s [[Boeing Everett Factory|aircraft assembly plant]] at Paine Field in 1967. Boeing's presence brought additional industrial and commercial development to Everett, as well as new residential neighborhoods to the south and west of the peninsula that was [[Annexation|annexed]] by the city. Boeing remains the city's largest employer, alongside the [[U.S. Navy]], which has operated [[Naval Station Everett]] since 1992.\n\nEverett remains a major employment center for Snohomish County, but has also become a [[bedroom community]] for Seattle in recent decades. It is connected to Seattle by [[Interstate 5 in Washington|Interstate 5]] and various public transit services at [[Everett Station]], including the [[Sounder commuter rail|Sounder commuter train]], [[Amtrak]], and commuter buses. Everett stages several annual festivals and is also home to minor league sports teams, including the [[Everett Silvertips]] at [[Angel of the Winds Arena]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Early history and settlement===\n[[File:Port Gardner Bay, Everett, Washington, October 1891 (LAROCHE 278).jpeg|thumb|right|Looking south on the [[Seattle and Montana Railroad]] as it passes [[Port Gardner]] Bay in 1891]]\n\nThe [[Port Gardner]] peninsula was originally inhabited by local [[Coast Salish]] tribes who arrived in the region 10,000 years [[before present]] and settled near modern-day Everett approximately 2,000 years [[before present]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=2}} The [[Snohomish people]] lived around local waterways in the [[Possession Sound]] estuary and had a fortified winter village at Hibulb (also called Hebolb) at the mouth of the [[Snohomish River]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=2}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Whitely |first=Peyton |date=March 16, 2005 |title=Aerial photos show 2 very different cities |page=H8 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/aerial-photos-show-2-very-different-cities/ |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref> The first Europeans in the area were explorers from the 1792 [[Vancouver Expedition]], landing on a beach on the modern Everett waterfront on June 4 and claiming the land for [[England]] on the birthday of King [[George III of the United Kingdom|George III]].<ref>{{cite book |author=[[Federal Writers' Project]] |year=1941 |title=The WPA Guide to Washington: The Evergreen State |pages=186\u2013200 |series=[[American Guide Series]] |publisher=[[Works Progress Administration]] |oclc=881468746 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=07PpCAAAQBAJ |via=Google Books |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref> [[Puget Sound]] was further explored and charted ny the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] in 1824 and the [[United States Exploring Expedition]] under [[Charles Wilkes]] in 1841, ahead of a larger American presence in the area.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=4}}<ref name=\"HistoryLink\">{{cite web |last=Oakley |first=Janet |date=July 26, 2005 |title=Everett \u2014 Thumbnail History |url=https://www.historylink.org/file/7397 |work=[[HistoryLink]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Snohomish and other Coast Salish tribes signed the [[Treaty of Point Elliott]] in 1855, which relinquished their lands to the [[Washington Territory|territorial government]] and established the nearby [[Tulalip Indian Reservation]], where they would be relocated.<ref name=\"Herald-125th\">{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=May 9, 2018 |title=City of Everett to celebrate 125th birthday with big party |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/city-of-everett-celebrates-125-years-and-counting/ |work=[[The Everett Herald]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref> The first permanent American settler to arrive on the peninsula was Dennis Brigham, a carpenter from [[Worcester, Massachusetts]], who claimed a {{convert|160|acre|km2|1|adj=on}} [[Homestead Acts|homestead]] and built a cabin for himself. He was joined by several other families on their own homesteads, which included the establishment of a general store and a [[sawmill]] that quickly went out of business.<ref name=\"HistoryLink\"/> Over the next several years a handful of loggers moved to the area, but plans for a settlement were not conceived until 1890.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=7}}\n\nDuring an Alaskan cruise via the [[Inside Passage]] aboard the steamship ''[[Queen of the Pacific]]'' in July 1890, plans were drawn up for an industrial city on Port Gardner Bay by lumberman [[Henry Hewitt Jr.]] and railroad executive [[Charles L. Colby]]. Hewitt and Colby had previously met in [[Wisconsin]], where they operated lumber and maritime businesses, respectively, and in [[Tacoma, Washington]], from which the voyage began. The pair sought to build an industrial center at a site they speculated would be the first ocean port for [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]], to be constructed by [[James J. Hill]], and turn it into a \"[[Pittsburgh]] of the West\".{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=12}}<ref name=\"Times-HewittColby93\">{{cite news |last=Dilgard |first=David |date=April 22, 1993 |title=Odd couple of Hewitt and Colby hatched ambitious plan for Everett |page=F5 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19930422&slug=1697251 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> On August 22, 1890, the [[plat]] for a {{convert|50|acre|m2|adj=on}} townsite on the peninsula was filed by the [[Rucker Brothers]], who had moved north from Tacoma and had more modest plans for the area.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=12}}\n\nBy September, Colby had secured $800,000 in funding from oil magnate [[John D. Rockefeller]] and his railroad associate [[Colgate Hoyt]] to begin acquiring land while avoiding property speculators.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=12}} The Hewitt\u2013Colby syndicate decided to use a name without an identifiable location, naming their planned city after [[Everett Colby]], the fifteen-year-old son of investor Charles L. Colby, who had displayed a \"prodigious appetite\" at a group dinner.<ref name=\"Times-HewittColby93\"/> The [[Everett Land Company]] was incorporated in [[Pierce County, Washington|Pierce County]] on November 19, 1890, and acquired {{convert|434.15|acre|sqkm}} of property from the Rucker Brothers a week later.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=15}} Several businesses had already been established on the peninsula, generally dividing themselves between the Bayside facing Port Gardner and Riverside facing the Snohomish River.<ref>{{cite news |last=Humphrey |first=Robert |date=August 14, 1991 |title=Boom times coming in Everett? We've been that route before |page=F2 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> The Rucker Brothers' plat was withdrawn after an agreement to donate half of their holdings was reached with Hewitt, who promised a series of industrial developments under the \"Remarkable Document\", which was also used to acquire property from other landowners in the area.{{sfnp|Whitfield|1926|p=314}}{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=103}}\n\nEverett gained its first businesses in early 1891, as the new settlement on the Snohomish River attracted land speculators and commitments to build lumber mills and other industrial enterprises.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=16}} The first [[post office]] opened in July at a [[general store]] on the bayfront, where the [[Seattle and Montana Railroad]] was later built in October. By the end of the year, Everett had gained its first school, [[Western saloon|saloon]], church, and [[sawmill]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=17}} The Swalwell Brothers had begun selling property in Riverside along Hewitt Avenue, which was laid {{convert|100|ft|m}} wide and became the main east\u2013west thoroughfare from the riverfront when it was completed in June 1892.{{sfnp|Dorpat|McCovy|1998|p=153}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Burden |first1=Bill |last2=Dorpat |first2=Paul |date=December 20, 1988 |title=Everett: Growth of a late bloomer |page=C6 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> The Everett Land Company did not initially organize a municipal government, leaving local issues to be resolved by a \"citizen's committee\" formed by 21 residents on March 21, 1892.{{sfnp|Whitfield|1926|p=335}} The area had an estimated population of 5,000 by the end of the year, shortly before the completion of the Great Northern Railway across [[Stevens Pass]] on January 6, 1893. The railroad did not terminate in Everett as originally hoped, instead continuing along the shoreline of Puget Sound to [[Seattle]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=20\u201321}}\n\n===Incorporation and early years===\n[[File:Port Gardner Bay, Everett, ca 1905 (CURTIS 70).jpeg|thumb|right|The Everett waterfront, {{circa}} 1905]]\n\nFollowing the acquisition of tidelands on the waterfront, which had been in dispute, the Everett Land Company allowed for a municipal government to be formed.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=20\u201321}} The initial city boundaries were set by the company to avoid taxing the industrial areas and exclude the town of [[Lowell, Everett, Washington|Lowell]], which pre-dated Everett.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=20\u201321}} On April 27, 1893, the citizens of Everett voted 670\u201399 in favor of [[Municipal incorporation|incorporating]] as a city, and elected Thomas Dwyer as [[mayor]].<ref>{{cite news |date=April 29, 1893 |title=The Everett Election |page=1 |work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47971884/the-everett-election/ |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> The incorporation was certified by the [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]] government on May 4, 1893.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=20\u201321}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Riddle |first=Margaret |date=February 27, 2010 |title=Everett incorporates on May 4, 1893. |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/9324 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> The city's privately owned [[streetcar]] system launched on July 3, 1893, with lines connecting the Hewitt Avenue commercial district to mills, [[smelter]]s, and areas as far as Lowell.<ref>{{cite web |last=Labovitch |first=Lisa |date=December 11, 2019 |title=Everett's Streetcars |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/20935 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Everett Land Company ran into financial trouble within months of the city's incorporation as the impact of the national [[Panic of 1893|economic depression]] was felt in the region. The company's investment into the [[Monte Cristo, Washington|Monte Cristo]] area yielded ore of poorer quality than expected and it was unable to meet the promises in the \"Remarkable Document\", which was amended several times with the Rucker Brothers, by then junior partners in the company.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=119}} Rockefeller called his investment into question and appointed advisory Frederick Gates to begin divestment while Colby and Hoyt remained as the leaders of the company.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=119}} Several of the major businesses in Everett closed or failed during the three-year height of the economic depression, but work on [[Alexander McDougall (ship designer)|Alexander McDougall]]'s [[Whaleback]] was finished with the launch of {{SS|City of Everett}} in October 1894, the largest to be built on Puget Sound at the time.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=23}} The Everett Women's Book Club was established in 1894 and opened the city's first [[hospital]] and [[public library]], which would later expand into the [[Everett Public Library]] system.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=April 14, 2019 |title=Everett's museum salutes book club celebrating 125 years |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everetts-museum-salutes-book-club-celebrating-125-years/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDespite the economic turmoil, Everett continued to grow with the addition of new businesses as the area's lumber activities increased.{{sfnp|Whitfield|1926|pages=355\u2013356}} Other industries also expanded in Everett, including a local [[cannery]], a [[brick]] factory, and several ore [[smelter]]s.{{sfnp|Whitfield|1926|p=355}} The discovery of new mineral deposits in Monte Cristo fueled a population boom, along with the completion of the [[Everett and Monte Cristo Railway]] under the ownership of Rockefeller.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=124\u2013125}} The city also benefited from the [[Klondike Gold Rush]], building several [[steamboat]]s to transport prospectors and entrepreneurs.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=124\u2013125}}\n\nIn its early years, Everett launched a campaign to become [[county seat]] by replacing [[Snohomish, Washington|Snohomish]], which had waned in importance following the completion of several railroads serving other cities in the county. An election to determine which city would be named county seat was scheduled for November 6, 1894, beginning a heated debate by citizens and newspapers.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=121\u2013122}} The initial count by the commissioners was announced on December 19 in Everett's favor, amid accusations of fraud and bought votes from both sides. Following an appeal from Snohomish, thee [[Washington Supreme Court]] declared the result to be invalid and blocked the move, but a recount by the commissioners in October 1895 remained in Everett's favor.{{sfnp|Whitfield|1926|pages=136\u2013137}} A long legal battle was fought between the two cities and was decided in October 1895 by the Supreme Court, who ruled that Everett would become county seat per the legal and binding recount.{{sfnp|Whitfield|1926|p=139}} In January 1897, the county government's records were moved by wagons from Snohomish to Everett, where a three-story [[courthouse]] was opened on February 1, 1898.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=121\u2013122}}{{sfnp|Whitfield|1926|p=140}}\n\n===Milltown and labor unrest===\n[[File:everettwaterfront.jpg|thumb|A [[Weyerhaeuser]] lumber mill on the Everett waterfront, seen in the early 20th century]]\n\nAfter outside investors withdrew in the Everett Land Company, its holdings were transferred in 1899 to the [[Everett Improvement Company]], controlled by James J. Hill and his trusted associate John T. McChesney.{{sfnp|Whitfield|1926|pages=356\u2013357}} [[Friedrich Weyerh\u00e4user]] acquired Hill's timberland holdings in the Pacific Northwest and chose Everett for the site of his major lumber mill, which opened in 1902. By the end of the decade, Everett had 11 lumber mills, 16 [[wood shingle|shingle]] mills, and 17 combined mills\u2014surpassing every other city in the state and earning it the nicknames of \"Milltown\" and the \"City of Smokestacks\".{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=135\u2013136}} The [[Weyerhaeuser Company]] opened its larger second mill, named Mill B, on the Snohomish River in April 1915 with the ability to process 1,000,000 [[board feet]] of timber and a {{convert|203|ft|m|adj=mid}} smokestack.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=36}}\n\nThe city gained its first [[interurban]] railway in 1903 with the opening of the [[Everett\u2013Snohomish Interurban|Snohomish Interurban]]. It was then followed by the [[Seattle\u2013Everett Interurban Railway|Seattle Interurban]] on May 2, 1910, which ran hourly on an inland route via [[Alderwood Manor, Washington|Alderwood Manor]].{{sfnp|Whitfield|1926|pages=373\u2013374}} Everett became a first-class city in 1907 and had a population of nearly 25,000 residents by 1910, a quarter of whom were foreign-born. A major lumber boom began following the [[1906 San Francisco earthquake]], which created a high demand for West Coast wood products as the city was rebuilt.<ref name=\"HistoryLink\"/> Everett itself suffered from a major fire on August 2, 1909, that destroyed 12 buildings, including the county courthouse.<ref>{{cite web |last=Riddle |first=Margaret |date=August 16, 2006 |title=Fire destroys the Snohomish County Courthouse in Everett on August 2, 1909. |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/7889 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> The city's growth was not stopped by the fire and a [[Snohomish County Courthouse|new county courthouse]] opened in 1910 alongside the [[Everett High School (Washington)|Everett High School]] campus.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=156}} Everett voters approved a new city charter in 1912 that reorganized the city government into a three-commissioner council with a ceremonial [[mayor]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=34\u201335}}\n\nDuring the first decade of the 20th century, workers at mills and other factories began organizing [[labor union]]s under the Everett Central Trades Council, which had 27 member trades and six unions by 1901. The council had 25 unions by 1907 and became affiliated with the [[American Federation of Labor]], using its influence to stage strikes and work stoppages that resulted in wage increases and safer conditions at mills, where 35 workers had died in 1909.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=30\u201332}}{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=151}} Everett was also home to local [[socialist]] groups and organizers, who published the ''Labor Journal'' and ''The Commonwealth'' on a weekly basis until 1914.<ref name=\"HL-Massacre\">{{cite web |last=Riddle |first=Margaret |date=December 18, 2011 |title=Everett Massacre (1916) |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/9981 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Several survivors of the September 1907 [[Bellingham riots|anti-Indian riots]] in [[Bellingham, Washington|Bellingham]] settled in Everett for two months, but were beaten and forcefully evicted by a mob.<ref>{{cite news |date=November 30, 2019 |title=Looking back: Everett mob terrorizes immigrant mill workers |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/looking-back-everett-mob-terrorizes-immigrant-mill-workers/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city's labor unrest culminated in the 1916 [[Everett massacre]], the deadliest event in Pacific Northwest labor history. A strike of [[shingle weaver]]s began at local mills in May 1916 and continued into the summer with violent attacks from mill owners, which attracted attention from the [[Industrial Workers of the World]] (IWW), a radical socialist union who provided speakers at Everett events.<ref name=\"HL-Massacre\"/>{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=174\u2013175}} The city government passed a new ordinance to restrict street speaking as a result of tensions between the IWW and county sheriff [[Donald McRae (sheriff)|Donald McRae]], who armed a local militia and beat 41 union members who were attempting to enter the city by boat on October 30, 1916.<ref name=\"Herald-Massacre100\">{{cite news |last1=Stevick |first1=Eric |last2=Muhlstein |first2=Julie |date=November 3, 2016 |title=100 years after Everett Massacre we're still learning more |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/100-years-after-the-everett-massacre-were-still-learning-more/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> The incident drew anger from union members and other Everett citizens, prompting 300 IWW members to travel on the steamers ''[[Verona (steamship)|Verona]]'' and ''[[Calista (steamboat)|Calista]]'' from Seattle to Everett on November 5, 1916, when they were confronted at the docks by McRae and his posse of 200 citizen deputies, who feared violence and arson from the group.<ref name=\"HL-Massacre\"/><ref name=\"Herald-Massacre97\">{{cite news |date=November 4, 2013 |title=97 years since 'bloody Sunday,' the Everett Massacre |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/97-years-since-bloody-sunday-the-everett-massacre/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs the ''Verona'' attempted to dock, McRae and several IWW members engaged in a heated debate before a shot was fired by an unknown person. After several minutes of gunfire, five people on the ''Verona'' were killed and two deputies on the dock had been mortally wounded from [[friendly fire]]; an unofficial death toll of twelve IWW members was determined from the recovery of underwater bodies.<ref name=\"HL-Massacre\"/> The ''Verona'', which had nearly capsized as its passengers rushed away from the dock, returned to Seattle with the ''Calista'', which had not attempted to land in Everett.<ref name=\"Herald-Massacre100\"/> At least 50 people were injured, including McRae, and 297 were arrested in Everett and Seattle.<ref>{{cite news |date=November 6, 1916 |title=7 Killed, 50 Injured As Citizens' Posse Battles I. W. W. Mob |page=1 |work=[[San Francisco Examiner]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48042141/everett-massacre-7-killed-50-injured/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Only one IWW member, Thomas Tracy, was ultimately tried and found not guilty of first-degree murder after a two-month trial.<ref name=\"Herald-Massacre100\"/>\n\nThe shingle weavers strike ended on November 10, 1916, with no concessions from the mill owners, and local residents turned against the IWW for escalating the dispute.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=174\u2013175}} The labor tensions subsided with the entry of the U.S. into [[World War I]], despite an attempted comeback by the IWW in disrupting logging for the war effort.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=180}} As a result of the massacre, the state government outlawed citizens from advocating for [[anarchy]] or violent overthrow; the law was not repealed until 1999.<ref>{{cite news |date=May 6, 1999 |title=Anarchism is legal again in state |page=B4 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19990506&slug=2959132 |work=The Seattle Times |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> The massacre was largely unacknowledged by local residents until the late 20th century, when book accounts were published and a [[historic marker]] was installed overlooking the former docks.<ref name=\"Herald-Massacre100\"/><ref name=\"Herald-Massacre97\"/>\n\n===Inter-war years===\n[[File:Monte Cristo Hotel, Everett, Washington (4861196624).jpg|thumb|right|The [[Monte Cristo Hotel]], completed in 1925]]\n\nThe local timber industry continued its boom and bust cycle into the 1920s, suffering from price swings but benefiting from the [[1923 Great Kanto earthquake|1923 Japanese earthquake]] to supply lumber and the opening of the [[Panama Canal]]. The Clough-Hartley shingle mill claimed to be the largest in the world, producing 1.5 million wood shingles per day; the city produced approximately 4.5 million shingles and 3.5 million board feet of lumber per day in 1920.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=184\u2013185}} The [[Port of Everett]] was created on July 13, 1918, to enable public ownership of the waterfront and promote economic development in the city. By the end of the 1920s, the port had opened the county's first airport on [[Ebey Island]] and acquired the 14th Street Dock and [[Jetty Island]] from the Everett Improvement Company.<ref>{{cite news |last=Podsada |first=Janice |date=July 3, 2018 |title=A century ago, a publicly owned port was a radical notion |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/a-century-ago-a-publicly-owned-port-was-a-radical-notion/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=July 3, 2018 |title=Port of Everett history at a glance |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/port-of-everett-history-at-a-glance/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> The city also acquired the private water system in 1915 and replaced it with a new supply from the [[Sultan River]] basin that was fully activated four years later.{{sfnp|Dorpat|McCovy|1998|p=207}}\n\nEverett's central [[commercial district]] grew from a handful of businesses into a busy downtown during the 1920s, including the construction of several multi-story office and retail buildings, two [[junior high school]]s, a [[Everett City Hall|modern city hall]], and additions to the city's two hospitals.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=192}} The six-story [[Monte Cristo Hotel]] opened in 1925 with 140 guest rooms, elaborate furnishings, and a [[banquet hall]] that would host civic functions for several decades.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=192}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Bruestle |first=Sara |date=April 16, 2018 |title=History of a hotel: Everett's dreams gave rise to Monte Cristo |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/history-of-a-hotel-everetts-dreams-gave-rise-to-monte-cristo/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> The county's first radio station, KFBL (now [[KRKO]]), began broadcasting on August 25, 1922, and was among the earliest in the state.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=197}} In 1924, a third mill at the Weyerhaeuser complex, which employed 1,500 people and contributed to $28.125&nbsp;million in annual timber output by the end of the decade.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=45}}\n\nThe widespread adoption of the automobile lead to the construction of new roads out of Everett and Snohomish County to neighboring regions. The earliest iteration of the [[Stevens Pass Highway]] opened in 1925, providing the second automobile crossing of the [[Cascade Mountains]] in the state and access to new timberland and other resources.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=211}} The highway was later improved with the opening of the [[Hewitt Avenue Trestle]] in 1939, crossing the Gnomish River and Ebey Island on an elevated viaduct.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=253}} The [[Pacific Highway (United States)|Pacific Highway]] (part of [[U.S. Route 99]]) was completed in 1927 with the opening of four bridges across the Snohomish River delta to [[Marysville, Washington|Marysville]].{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=207\u2013209}} Everett was also among the first cities in the U.S. to replace its streetcars with [[transit bus|buses]], doing so in 1923,{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=211}} and the last train on the Seattle\u2013Everett Interurban ran on February 20, 1939.<ref name=\"Herald-Interurban\">{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=December 2, 2019 |title=The Interurban Railway: Everett's first rapid transit line |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/the-interurban-railway-everetts-first-rapid-transit-line/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett experienced a major rise in unemployment as demand for lumber products dropped, with an estimated 32 percent of [[property tax]]es left unpaid in 1932. Charitable organizations in the area set up relief programs and provided work for unemployed residents, including commencing work on a {{convert|185|acre|ha|adj=mid}} park and [[golf course]] in North Everett that later became [[American Legion Memorial Park]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=50\u201351}} The federal [[Works Progress Administration]] employed local workers to construct a new downtown [[public library]], develop parks, expand schools, and improve streets.<ref name=\"Herald-WPAForest\">{{cite news |date=February 15, 2020 |title=Looking back: 1930s WPA project transformed Forest Park |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/looking-back-1930s-wpa-project-transformed-forest-park/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> The works program also built a new county airport, [[Paine Field]], southwest of Everett that opened in 1936 to serve commercial uses. The airport was appropriated for military use during [[World War II]], but was later turned over to county ownership.<ref name=\"HistoryLink\"/>{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=53}} The war also brought a new [[shipyard]] operated by the [[Everett-Pacific Shipbuilding & Dry Dock Company]], which employed 6,000 workers and closed in 1949.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=266}}\n\n===Boeing and suburban development===\n[[File:Boeing 747 rollout (3).jpg|thumb|right|The rollout of the first [[Boeing 747]] from the [[Boeing Everett Factory|Everett assembly plant]] in September 1968]]\n\nDowntown Everett continued to grow as the regional commercial center following the end of the war, with four large [[department store]]s and dozens of smaller retailers and restaurants in a six-block radius of Hewitt Avenue and Colby Avenue. The population boom triggered construction of new housing areas around the peninsula and new schools, with enrollment in the [[Everett School District]] doubling to 11,600 from 1941 to 1951.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=63}} The school district also built [[Everett Memorial Stadium]] in 1947 to host high school sports and civic events.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=315}} A new [[public housing]] complex, Baker Heights, was built in 1943 to house military personnel amid a local shortage, providing a total of 1,275 apartments that later went to low-income families.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=August 25, 2019 |title=Baker Heights: Tight-knit Everett community must scatter |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/baker-heights-a-tight-knit-community-must-scatter/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe first suburban-style [[supermarket]] opened on Evergreen Way (part of U.S. Route 99) in 1950 and was followed by [[strip mall]]s and similar [[big box store]]s along the highway by the end of the decade.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=72}} The areas surrounding the highway were developed into suburban housing and made up the bulk of the city's then-largest [[annexation]], of {{convert|900|acre|ha}} near Madison Street on December 31, 1959. A second round of South Everett annexations completed in 1961 and 1972 added {{convert|10,300|acre|ha}} to the city, including the Lowell area, and boosted its population to over 50,000.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=72}}<ref name=\"Annexations\">{{cite map |date=March 2019 |title=City of Everett Annexations By Year |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/15379/ANNEXATION-HISTORY-as-of-3122019-PDF |publisher=City of Everett Department of Community, Planning & Economic Development |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Everett's second high school, [[Cascade High School (Everett, Washington)|Cascade High School]], opened in 1961 to serve the annexed areas.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=72}} The new suburban neighborhoods were linked via [[Interstate 5 in Washington|Interstate 5]], which opened from North Seattle to Everett in February 1965 and bypassed U.S. Route 99 with a six-lane freeway roughly following the former interurban railway.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=77}}{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=332}} The freeway was extended around the east side of Downtown Everett in January 1968 and Interstate 5 was completed within Washington with the opening of the section connecting the city to Marysville in May 1969.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=81}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Mansfield |first=Tom |date=May 14, 1969 |title=I-5 Opened Today |page=A1 |work=The Everett Herald}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Boeing Company]] opened its first Everett factory in 1943 as part of its wartime production for the [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress|B-17]] program. The company moved to the Everett\u2013Pacific Shipyard in 1956 and grew to be the city's largest single employer by 1965, with 1,728 employees.<ref name=\"Herald-BoeingTimeline\">{{cite news |last=Dominguez |first=Alejandro |date=March 23, 2012 |title=Boeing's history in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/boeings-history-in-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Boeing approved early development of its [[Boeing 747]] passenger jetliner in March 1966 and purchased {{convert|780|acre|ha}} near Paine Field in June to build its [[Boeing Everett Factory|assembly plant]] for the plane, which would become the world's first \"jumbo jet\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=January 22, 2016 |title=How Boeing's incredible 747 launched the Everett factory |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/how-boeings-incredible-747-launched-the-everett-factory/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Work on the first 747 plane, named the \"City of Everett\", began at the unfinished factory in January 1967.<ref name=\"Herald-Boeing50\">{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=May 22, 2017 |title=50 history-making years of building Boeing jets in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/boeing-has-built-planes-in-everett-for-50-history-making-years/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> It was unveiled in September 1968 and made its maiden flight on February 9, 1969.<ref>{{cite news |last=Podsada |first=Janice |date=September 30, 2018 |title=50 years ago, they rolled it out: the first Boeing 747 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/50-years-ago-they-rolled-it-out-the-first-boeing-747/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> The Everett factory was expanded several times to accommodate later Boeing programs, including the [[Boeing 767|767]], [[Boeing 777|777]], and [[Boeing 787|787 Dreamliner]].<ref name=\"Herald-Boeing50\"/>\n\nThe impending construction of the Boeing plant triggered a boom in residential and commercial development in Everett and surrounding communities in the late 1960s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Moody |first=Dick |date=June 5, 1966 |title=Monroe, a Residential City, Hopes to Remain That Way |page=34 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> By the end of the decade, Everett had annexed additional areas to stretch the city boundaries west to Mukilteo and south to Silver Lake.<ref name=\"Annexations\"/> A new freeway, [[Washington State Route 526|State Route 526]], was built to connect the plant to Interstate 5 at the Eastmont Interchange, where the [[Everett Mall]] was planned to be built.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=81}} The mall was built in stages, beginning with a [[Sears]] store in February 1969 and ending with a grand opening on October 9, 1974, with 14 stores.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=83}} The development of the mall was slowed by a local economic crash that began with the cancellation of Boeing's [[Boeing 2707|supersonic jetliner]] program in 1971 and financial issues for airliners that affected sales of the Boeing 747. The Everett factory reduced its number of employees from 25,000 to 4,700, causing a spike in local unemployment rates and an exodus of former employees; the Everett School District closed three of its elementary schools as enrollment dropped by 3,000 students.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=83}}{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|pages=339\u2013340}}\n\nDuring the 1970s, several of Everett's surviving lumber and pulp mills closed as they were too costly to renovate or replace, marking the end of the \"Mill Town\". Lowell's pulp mill closed in 1972 and was followed by Weyerhaeuser's Mill B in 1979 and Mill A in 1981.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=85}} The final Weyerhaeuser mill closed in 1992, leaving the [[Scott Paper Company]] as the last remaining paper mill in Everett until its closure in 2012.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=85}}<ref name=\"Herald-KimClark\">{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Debra |date=March 30, 2012 |title=Kimberly-Clark mill is part of the Everett we've lost |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/kimberly-clark-mill-is-part-of-the-everett-weve-lost/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The city instead deepened its connections to the aerospace and high-tech industry, opening facilities in the 1980s for [[Hewlett-Packard]], [[Fluke Corporation|Fluke]], and other electronics firms.<ref name=\"Times-WH1992\">{{cite news |last=Nelson |first=Robert T. |date=March 29, 1992 |title=Funeral bells toll for Mill Town Everett |page=B1 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19920329&slug=1483696 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Downtown Everett also declined as an activity center as retailers and car dealerships moved to suburban areas, despite the opening of a large [[hotel]] and several high-rise office building.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=88\u201390}} A city landfill southeast of Downtown Everett was turned into a recycling plant for millions of rubber [[tire]]s, nicknamed \"Mount Firestone\", which caught fire in September 1984 and burned for seven months as the incident gained national media attention.<ref>{{cite web |last=Riddle |first=Margaret |date=December 8, 2009 |title=The Everett Tire Fire begins on September 24, 1984. |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/9233 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Naval base and downtown revival===\n[[File:Naval Station Everett.jpg|thumb|right|[[Naval Station Everett]], a U.S. Navy facility opened in 1994 under the [[Strategic Homeport]] program]]\n\nBoeing recovered from its sales slump and increased employment at its Everett plant to 18,000 people in 1980 as it prepared to unveil the [[Boeing 767]], the second family of jetliners to be produced in Everett. A neighboring [[industrial park]] along Seaway Boulevard was developed in the 1980s as demand for commercial space in the city grew.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=88\u201390}} The Port of Everett began developing a new shopping and retail complex on Port Gardner Bay as it looked to diversify away from industrial uses, but the project ran into financial issues as Everett-area employers failed or laid off workers amid an aerospace slump in 1981\u201382.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=88\u201390}} The [[U.S. Navy]] selected the former shipyard site on Port Gardner Bay as the site of a new military base in 1984 under the [[Strategic Homeport]] program.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cowley |first=Geoffrey |date=November 7, 1984 |title=Everett says 'yes' to Navy by a margin of more than 2-to-1 |page=B10 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> [[Naval Station Everett]] and its {{convert|1,600|ft|m|adj=mid}} pier were constructed between 1987 and 1994 alongside auxiliary facilities located to the north in [[Smokey Point, Washington|Smokey Point]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Brooks |first=Diane |date=June 5, 1992 |title=The Navy's in port: three ships greeted at Everett's new base |page=E1 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hendricks |first=Tyche |date=June 5, 1995 |title=Eagerly awaiting stores' opening\u2014Navy exchange, commissary ready |page=B1 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19950605&slug=2124724 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> The first ships arrived in September 1994, and Naval Station Everett was the long-term home of several [[aircraft carrier]]s, including the {{USS|Abraham Lincoln|CVN-72|6}}.<ref>{{cite news |last=Clutter |first=Stephen |date=January 9, 1997 |title=Bringing home the future: The Lincoln, with crew of 3,200 is first carrier permanently assigned to Everett |page=B1 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref>\n\nThe city underwent an urban revival in the 1990s, fueled by the upcoming centennial celebrations and a third expansion of the Boeing plant for the [[Boeing 777]] program. The plant expansion was completed in 1993, enlarging the world's largest building by volume to {{convert|96|acre|ha}}.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=355}}<ref name=\"NYT-1990\">{{cite news |last=King |first=Harriet |date=May 13, 1990 |title=Focus: The I-5 Corridor; A Lively New Washington Growth Area |page=A1 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/05/13/realestate/focus-the-i-5-corridor-a-lively-new-washington-growth-area.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"DJC-2001\">{{cite news |last=Stephens |first=Terry |date=August 9, 2001 |title=Energizing Everett |url=https://www.djc.com/news/re/11124627.html |work=[[Seattle Daily Journal of Commerce]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Everett's inner neighborhoods grew with new residential and commercial development, including Downtown Everett, where a beautification and restoration program had begun in the 1980s.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=349}} The downtown program included a [[road diet]] for Colby Avenue, [[Flower box|planter boxes]] on widened sidewalks, and new parks.<ref name=\"PI-Life97\">{{cite news |last=Carter |first=Don |date=July 12, 1997 |title=New life breathes in old mill town |page=D1 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Tewkesbury |first=Don |date=October 30, 1989 |title=Everett beautifies with flower planters |page=B1 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer}}</ref> Several new office buildings were completed in Downtown Everett, including the 11-story [[Key Bank Tower (Everett, Washington)|Everett Mutual Tower]], and other historic buildings were renovated or restored for new businesses and organizations.<ref name=\"PI-Life97\"/>{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=370}} The city also annexed {{convert|465|acre|ha}} near Paine Field in March 2000, bringing Everett's population to over 91,000.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brooks |first=Diane |date=March 1, 2000 |title=Everett voters approve West Casino annexation |page=A23 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> Everett was recognized as an [[All-America City]] by the [[National Civic League]] in 2002 and has been a member of the [[Tree City USA]] program since 1993.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=September 13, 2012 |title=Remembering Everett's All-America summer of 2002 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/remembering-everetts-all-america-summer-of-2002/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=March 27, 2012 |title=Garden club has left a vibrant legacy all around Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/garden-club-has-left-a-vibrant-legacy-all-around-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett was identified as a key transport hub under the regional [[Sound Transit]] system, which was approved in a ballot measure in 1996 after an earlier failed attempt. The transit agency opened a multimodal train and bus center, [[Everett Station]], in February 2003 to replace scattered downtown facilities for [[Amtrak]], [[Greyhound Lines|Greyhound]], and local transit. It would also serve as the northern terminus for [[Sounder commuter rail]] and [[Sound Transit Express]] buses, which both connect Everett to Seattle.<ref name=\"Times-Station03\">{{cite news |last=Whitley |first=Peyton |date=January 1, 2003 |title=City's new terminal has amassed transit depots in single location |page=I17 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20030101&slug=station01n |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808042501/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20030101&slug=station01n |archivedate=August 8, 2014 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> A {{convert|6|mi|km|spell=in|adj=mid}} section of Interstate 5 was rebuilt by the state government from 2005 to 2008 by adding new lanes and improving several interchanges at a cost of $263&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nohara |first=Yoshiaki |date=May 28, 2008 |title=I-5 work not done, but is helping traffic |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/i-5-work-not-done-but-is-helping-traffic/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Everett remains home to one of the most congested stretches of I-5, which is also among the worst in the United States for travel delays.<ref name=\"Times-Traffic18\">{{cite news |last=Lindblom |first=Mike |date=February 5, 2018 |title=It's worse than you think: Everett leads the nation in traffic congestion, report says |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/transportation/its-worse-than-you-think-everett-leads-the-nation-in-traffic-congestion-report-says/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDowntown Everett remained a center for new development in the 2000s and 2010s, with several projects completed by local governments and private developers. The [[Everett Events Center]] (now Angels of the Winds Arena) opened in 2003 to serve as an indoor sports venue, [[convention center]], and community [[ice rink]].<ref name=\"Times-Arena03\">{{cite news |last=Tuinstra |first=Rachel |date=September 24, 2003 |title=A $71.5 million venue represents 'a big leap of faith' for the city |page=H28 |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20030924&slug=center24n |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004084051/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20030924&slug=center24n |archivedate=October 4, 2012 |accessdate=March 25, 2012}}</ref> The county government redeveloped its Everett office campus by building a new administrative center, jail, [[parking garage]], and public [[plaza]] that opened in 2005.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kelly |first=Brian |date=January 1, 2005 |title=The year ahead |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/the-year-ahead/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Whitely |first=Peyton |date=January 12, 2005 |title=New county garage \"doing well\" |page=H10 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> In the 2010s, two new downtown hotels were opened along with several apartment buildings that were encouraged by relaxed zoning policies.<ref name=\"Herald-DTHotel\">{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=October 28, 2016 |title=New downtown Everett hotel sign of changing economy |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/new-downtown-everett-hotel-sign-of-changing-economy/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Herald-DTApartments\">{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=March 22, 2015 |title=102 new apartments opening in downtown Everett this summer |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/102-new-apartments-opening-in-downtown-everett-this-summer/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> As the region's [[Homelessness in Seattle|homeless population]] grew, Everett added two [[supportive housing]] buildings in downtown to provide 150 units of low-income housing with access to social services.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=February 11, 2019 |title=150 units of supportive housing coming to Everett in 2019 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/150-units-of-supportive-housing-coming-to-everett-in-2019/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBoeing selected Everett as the main site of its [[Boeing 787|787 Dreamliner]] and [[Boeing 747-8|747-8]] programs, which did not require major building expansions.<ref name=\"Herald-BoeingTimeline\"/> The company also partnered with the county government to create the [[Future of Flight Aviation Center & Boeing Tour]], an aviation museum at Paine Field that opened in 2005.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wolcott |first=John |date=March 31, 2012 |title=Future of Flight's popularity soars |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/future-of-flights-popularity-soars/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The [[Boeing 777X]] program launched in 2013 with plans to build a wing assembly center adjacent to the Everett plant, which opened in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gates |first=Dominic |date=May 19, 2016 |title=Boeing shows off new 777X wing center |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeing-shows-off-new-777x-wing-center/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Commercial passenger service at Paine Field resumed at a new terminal on March 4, 2019, after earlier plans from the 1980s onward were blocked by nearby residents.<ref name=\"Times-Paine\">{{cite news |last=Blethen |first=Ryan |date=March 5, 2019 |title=How the first day of commercial flights from Paine Field went |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/life/travel/first-commercial-flight-to-take-off-from-everetts-paine-field-today/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=March 6, 2019 |title=Paine airport battle lasted longer than the Thirty Years War |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/paine-airport-battle-lasted-longer-than-the-thirty-years-war/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city government began planning for a major redevelopment of a former landfill on the Snohomish River waterfront in the late 1990s, but the project was stalled as private developers declined to move the project forward.<ref name=\"Herald-Riverfront\">{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=November 3, 2016 |title=Massive Riverfront development begins to rise in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/homes-being-built-in-massive-riverfront-development-in-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The original concept for the {{convert|139|acre|ha|adj=mid}} property was an entertainment center with shopping, housing, offices, and parks. The [[Everett Riverfront|riverfront project]] was ultimately divided into three sections: a southern portion for 235 [[single-family home]]s that was constructed in 2016; a center portion with commercial space, apartments, a movie theater, and a small park; and a northern portion with 190 [[townhome]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=May 3, 2019 |title=Riverfront plan approved, ushering in a new era for Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/riverfront-plan-approved-ushering-in-a-new-era-for-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> A similar redevelopment plan for the Port of Everett's {{convert|65|acre|ha}} on the bayside waterfront, known as Port Gardner Wharf, was shelved in 2007 by the developer's financial issues.<ref>{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=April 21, 2014 |title=Port of Everett prepares new waterfront redevelopment plan |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/port-of-everett-prepares-new-waterfront-redevelopment-plan-2/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> A new development, named Fisherman's Harbor, began construction in 2018 with a hotel, apartments, restaurants, and shops adjacent to the city's public [[marina]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Watanabe |first=Ben |date=April 19, 2018 |title=New Everett hotel will double waterfront rooms in the county |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/new-everett-hotel-will-double-waterfront-rooms-in-the-county/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Providence Regional Medical Center Everett|Providence Regional Medical Center]], formed from a merger of Everett's two hospitals in 1994, completed a major expansion of its North Everett campus in 2011 by opening a 12-story medical tower.<ref name=\"Herald-Providence11\">{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=May 15, 2011 |title=A $460 million gamble |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/a-460-million-gamble/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The first [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|U.S. case]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] was identified in a Snohomish County resident at Providence Regional Medical Center on January 20, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Blethen |first=Ryan |date=February 14, 2020 |title=What it was like for doctors and nurses at an Everett hospital to treat the nation's first novel coronavirus patient |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/what-it-was-like-for-doctors-and-nurses-at-an-everett-hospital-to-treat-the-nations-first-novel-coronavirus-patient/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> As the coronavirus pandemic worsened in the state, mayor Cassie Franklin declared the first shelter-in-place order for Washington state on March 21, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutman |first=David |date=March 21, 2020 |title=Everett orders residents to stay home to slow coronavirus, others call on Inslee to follow suit |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/everett-orders-residents-to-stay-home-to-slow-coronavirus-others-call-on-inslee-to-follow-suit/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Everett - Hewitt Ave.jpg|thumb|right|Hewitt Avenue in Downtown Everett]]\n\nEverett is one of the core cities comprising the [[Seattle metropolitan area]] and is located {{convert|25|mi|km}} north of [[Seattle]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Kirk |date=December 10, 2013 |title=Boeing Looks Around, and a State Worries |page=A16 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/11/us/washington-state-not-ready-to-ponder-future-without-boeing.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> It is located primarily on Port Gardner Peninsula, bordered to the west by [[Port Gardner Bay]] (part of [[Possession Sound]] in the [[Puget Sound]] estuary), and to the north and east by the [[Snohomish River]] delta.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dietrich |first=William |date=May 1, 2005 |title=Port Reform: With homes and offices, trails and tourist stops, waterfronts are finding new life |page=14 |url=http://seattletimes.com/pacificnw/2005/0501/cover.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012091251/http://seattletimes.com/pacificnw/2005/0501/cover.html |archivedate=October 12, 2012 |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The city also encompasses suburban and industrial areas to the south and southwest of the peninsula, which were annexed during the mid-to-late 20th century.<ref name=\"Annexations\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Chircop |first=David |date=May 5, 2008 |title=Everett eyes massive annexation that would boost city's population by 62,000 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-eyes-massive-annexation-that-would-boost-citys-population-by-62000/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Everett has {{convert|11|mi|km}} of freshwater shoreline and {{convert|11|mi|km}} of saltwater shoreline, including public access points at parks and [[boat launch|boat ramps]] on Port Gardner Bay and the Snohomish River.<ref name=\"CAFR2018\"/>{{rp|2}} According to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|48.49|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which {{convert|33.45|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|15.04|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web |title=US Gazetteer files 2010 |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=December 19, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112090031/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |archivedate=January 12, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe city's western boundary with [[Mukilteo, Washington|Mukilteo]] is generally defined by [[Japanese Gulch]] on the edge of the [[Boeing Everett Factory|Boeing Everett Assembly Plant]] and its auxiliary buildings.<ref name=\"BaseMap\">{{cite map |date=April 2019 |title=Everett, Washington Base Map |url=https://www.everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/19039/Basemap |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The southwestern edge of Everett borders an [[unincorporated area]] that includes [[Paine Field]] and the [[Lake Stickney, Washington|Lake Stickney/Mariner]] neighborhoods, which are part of the city's designated [[urban growth boundary|urban growth area]] that extends south towards [[Lynnwood, Washington|Lynnwood]].<ref name=\"MUGA\">{{cite map |date=September 2, 2013 |title=Snohomish County GMA Comprehensive Plan: Municipal Urban Growth Areas |url=https://snohomishcountywa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/8216/Map-3-Municipal-Urban-Growth-Areas-MUGA-11x17 |publisher=Snohomish County |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The southern boundary wraps around [[Silver Lake (Everett, Washington)|Silver Lake]] and follows [[Washington State Route 527|State Route 527]] to [[Washington State Route 96|State Route 96]] at Murphy's Corner, where it borders [[Mill Creek, Washington|Mill Creek]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Alexander |first=Brian |date=September 21, 2005 |title=Hard-fought annexation now just around corner |page=H14 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/hard-fought-annexation-now-just-around-corner/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Everett's boundaries follow various housing subdivisions in the [[Eastmont, Washington|Eastmont]] area before reaching the Snohomish River, which forms the primary eastern border. The northeastern boundary includes portions of [[Smith Island (Washington)|Smith Island]] in the river delta reaching towards [[Marysville, Washington|Marysville]];<ref name=\"BaseMap\"/> a series of highway bridges connect Everett to Marysville to the north and [[Lake Stevens, Washington|Lake Stevens]] to the east by crossing the Snohomish River delta.<ref name=\"WSDOT-Map\">{{cite map |year=2014 |title=Washington State Highways, 2014\u20132015 |url=https://www.wsdot.wa.gov/sites/default/files/2006/06/13/TouristMapFront_withoutHillshade.pdf |inset=[https://www.wsdot.wa.gov/sites/default/files/2017/08/31/highway-map-PugetSound_Full.pdf Puget Sound] |publisher=[[Washington State Department of Transportation]] |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite map |date=March 2013 |title=Snohomish County Urban Growth Areas and Incorporated Cities |url=http://www.snoco.org/docs/scd/PDF/PDS_UGA/County_11x17.pdf |publisher=Snohomish County |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The city boundaries also include {{convert|3,729|acre|ha}} of forestland surrounding [[Lake Chaplain]], a reservoir in the Cascade Mountains that provides part of the municipal water supply.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=May 10, 2015 |title=Trade-off would allow timber harvest at Lake Chaplain |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/trade-off-would-allow-timber-harvest-at-lake-chaplain/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Port Gardner Peninsula was formed during the northward retreat of [[Vashon Glaciation]] during an [[ice age]] 14,000 years before present.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=2}} The underlying soil is generally [[loam]]y and includes gravelly sand in the [[glacial outwash]].<ref name=\"Soil-Survey\">{{cite report |last1=Debose |first1=Alfonso |last2=Klungland |first2=Michael W. |date=July 1983 |title=Soil survey of Snohomish County Area, Washington |pages=4, 13 |url=https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_MANUSCRIPTS/washington/WA661/0/wa661_text.pdf |publisher=[[Natural Resources Conservation Service|U.S. Soil Conservation Service]] |oclc=9975367 |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Everett is located near the [[Puget Sound faults|Southern Whidbey Island Fault]], a shallow [[earthquake fault]] zone that runs near the western edge of the city and was discovered in 1994.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fiege |first=Gale |date=June 15, 2009 |title=South Whidbey fault has potential for major quake |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/south-whidbey-fault-has-potential-for-major-quake/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> In the 1990s, local geologists also found evidence of a [[tsunami]] and [[soil liquefaction]] in deposits under the Snohomish River delta that were not directly connected to the South Whidbey Island Fault.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dietrich |first=Bill |date=July 23, 1996 |title=Hunting for the big one |page=A6 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> The city government established its emergency management and preparedness office in 2002 and conducts regular disaster drills to simulate a potential response.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stevick |first1=Eric |last2=Sheets |first2=Bill |last3=King |first3=Rikki |date=March 11, 2011 |title=Tsunami in the Sound |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/tsunami-in-the-sound/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The southwestern neighborhoods of Everett include several [[ravine]]s formed by local creeks that drain into Port Gardner Bay. The area is also prone to [[mudslide]]s that interrupt passenger and freight service on the railroad that runs along the coastline of the bay.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sheets |first=Bill |date=March 19, 2013 |title=Mudslide trouble spots identified |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/mudslide-trouble-spots-identified/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Other areas of the city drain into the watersheds of the Snohomish River and [[Lake Washington]].<ref>{{cite map |date=January 2020 |title=Drainage Basins & Watersheds |url=https://www.everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/19690/Drain-Basins-11x17 |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Cityscape and neighborhoods===\n\nThe city of Everett maintains an Office of Neighborhoods which facilitate communication between the city and recognized neighborhood associations. The neighborhood associations are independent from the city and have elected leaders who communicate with the city government.<ref>{{cite web |title=Neighborhood Associations |url=https://everettwa.gov/334/Neighborhood-Associations |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Various neighborhoods in Everett have views of the [[Cascades Mountains|Cascade]] and [[Olympic Mountains|Olympic]] mountains, including [[Mount Baker]] and [[Mount Rainier]].<ref name=\"Herald-Hikes\">{{cite news |last=Bruestle |first=Sara |date=September 17, 2017 |title=Urban trails: 10 hiking destinations close to home |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/urban-trails-10-hiking-destinations-close-to-home/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Herald-Munk\">{{cite news |last=Munk |first=Melanie |date=July 5, 2007 |title=Top ways to spend a day |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/top-ways-to-spend-a-day/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2019}}, Everett's 19 recognized neighborhood associations are:<ref name=\"Neighborhoods\">{{cite map |date=April 2019 |title=Everett Neighborhoods |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/17789/4-16-19-Everett-Neighborhoods-Map-11x17 |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Bayside, which includes most of Downtown Everett, the Port of Everett, and [[Naval Station Everett]], and surrounding residential areas.<ref name=\"Neighborhoods\"/>\n* Boulevard Bluffs, a primarily residential area of the city bordering Mukilteo<ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Joseph |date=August 14, 2019 |title=City to Edgewater Bridge bidders: What about Boeing traffic? |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/edgewater-bridge-replacement-likely-to-slow-boeing-commuters/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n* Cascade View, a residential area in South Everett, north of Everett Mall<ref name=\"Neighborhoods\"/>\n* Delta, a primarily residential area north of downtown Everett<ref>{{cite news |last=Cornfield |first=Jerry |date=January 30, 2019 |title=Delta neighbors make their pitch to hasten smelter cleanup |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/delta-neighbors-make-their-pitch-to-hasten-smelter-cleanup/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n* Evergreen, a primarily residential area in South Everett<ref name=\"Neighborhoods\"/>\n* Glacier View, an older residential area south of downtown<ref name=\"Neighborhoods\"/>\n* Harborview\u2013Seahurst\u2013Glenhaven, consisting of older residential areas south of downtown<ref name=\"Neighborhoods\"/>\n* Holly, a mix of residential, commercial, and industrial areas on the southern edge of the city<ref name=\"Neighborhoods\"/>\n* Lowell, a primarily residential area southeast of downtown and formerly an independent town founded in 1863<ref>{{cite news |date=December 25, 2012 |title=Lowell prepares for its 150th anniversary |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/lowell-prepares-for-its-150th-anniversary/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n* Northwest Everett, which includes older residential areas northwest of downtown, a historic district, and the [[Everett Community College]] campus<ref name=\"HistoricOverlay\">{{cite web |title=Historic Overlay Zones |url=https://everettwa.gov/578/Historic-Overlay-Zones |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n* Pinehurst\u2013Beverly Park, a mix of residential and commercial areas in South Everett<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=November 3, 2016 |title=Pinehurst residents really don't want homeless housing nearby |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/pinehurst-residents-try-to-stop-homeless-housing-project/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n* Port Gardner, which includes parts of Downtown Everett and residential areas on Rucker Hill, a historic district<ref name=\"HistoricOverlay\"/>\n* Riverside, includes residential areas northeast of downtown and a historic district<ref name=\"HistoricOverlay\"/>\n* Silver Lake, includes residential and commercial areas surrounding Silver Lake in the extreme southeastern part of the city<ref>{{cite news |last=Chircop |first=David |date=November 3, 2008 |title=Everett eyes growth to southeast |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-eyes-growth-to-southeast/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n* South Forest Park, a residential neighborhood near downtown<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=May 9, 2019 |title=A new beginning for a neighborhood park in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/a-new-beginning-for-a-neighborhood-park-in-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n* Twin Creeks, which includes the area surrounding Everett Mall and a mix of residential and commercial areas.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=August 28, 2012 |title=Everett's Twin Creeks neighborhood gets its renaissance |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everetts-twin-creeks-neighborhood-gets-its-renaissance/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 10, 2019}}</ref>\n* Valley View\u2013Sylvan Crest\u2013Larimer Ridge, residential areas in southeast Everett<ref>{{cite news |last=Haglund |first=Noah |date=December 5, 2013 |title=Everett homeowners file lawsuit over landslides |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-homeowners-file-lawsuit-over-landslides/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n* View Ridge\u2013Madison, residential areas west and southwest of Forest Park<ref name=\"Neighborhoods\"/>\n* Westmont, a primarily multi-family housing area in the southwestern part of the city<ref name=\"Neighborhoods\"/>\n\n====Downtown====\n\nDowntown Everett is generally defined by the area north of Pacific Avenue, east of West Marine View Drive, south of Everett Avenue, and west of Broadway.<ref>{{cite web |date=July 2006 |title=Everett  Downtown Plan |page=4 |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/Home/View/784 |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=February 2, 2017}}</ref> It is home to city and county government offices, high-rise office buildings, hotels, and [[apartment building]]s.<ref name=\"Herald-DTHotel\"/><ref name=\"Herald-DTApartments\"/> The [[Angel of the Winds Arena]] is located on the west side of Broadway, anchoring a small [[historic district]] on Hewitt Avenue.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=December 12, 2001 |title=Everett to raze buildings |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-to-raze-buildings/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> Several downtown streets are named for the founders of the Everett Land Company and their associates, including John D. Rockefeller, the [[Rucker Brothers]], [[Charles L. Colby]], and [[Alexander McDougall (1845-1923)|Alexander McDougall]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Rathbun |first=Andy |date=September 7, 2012 |title=We have mnemonic winner for Everett's streets |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/we-have-mnemonic-winner-for-everetts-streets/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Chircop |first=David |date=November 10, 2008 |title=Everett sees a beautiful downtown |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-sees-a-beautiful-downtown/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> The city government approved plans in 2018 to allow for high-rise buildings as tall as 25 stories and with reduced parking requirements to encourage denser development in anticipation of a future [[Link light rail]] station.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=August 31, 2018 |title=A taller, denser downtown Everett gets City Council approval |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-plans-for-a-taller-denser-future-downtown/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\n\nThe climate of Everett is generally similar to most of the [[Puget Sound region|Puget Sound lowlands]], with year-round moderate temperatures influenced by marine air masses. The variation of normal weather between seasons is less extreme than inland areas, with dry summers and mild, rainy winters due to the proximity of the [[Pacific Ocean]].{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=253}} Under the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] system, Everett has a [[warm-summer Mediterranean climate]] (Csb), though it is also described as having an [[oceanic climate]] (Cfb).{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=253}}<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Peel |first1=M. C. |last2=Finlayson |first2=B. L. |last3=McMahon |first3=T. A. |year=2007 |title=Updated world map of the K\u00f6ppen-Geiger climate classification |journal=[[Hydrology and Earth System Sciences]] |doi=10.5194/hess-11-1633-2007 |issn=1027-5606 |volume=11 |issue=5 |pages=1633\u20131644 |publisher=[[European Geosciences Union]] |url=http://www.hydrol-earth-syst-sci.net/11/1633/2007/hess-11-1633-2007.html |accessdate=October 14, 2019|doi-access=free }}</ref> The city marks the north end of the [[Puget Sound Convergence Zone]], a local weather phenomenon caused by colliding air currents from the region's mountain ranges that produces heavier rain and stronger winds than the rest of the region.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mass |first=Cliff |year=2008 |title=The Weather of the Pacific Northwest |page=149 |publisher=[[University of Washington Press]] |isbn=978-0-295-98847-4 |oclc=416457886 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xPiACgAAQBAJ&pg=PA149 |via=Google Books |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Sistek |first=Scott |date=December 17, 2015 |title=What Is A Puget Sound Convergence Zone? |url=https://komonews.com/weather/faq/what-is-a-puget-sound-convergence-zone |publisher=[[KOMO-TV|KOMO News]] |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe warmest month for Everett is August, with average high temperatures of {{convert|72.7|F|C|lk=on}}, while January is the coolest, at an average high of {{convert|44.9|F|C}}.<ref name=\"WRCC\"/> The highest recorded temperature, {{convert|98|F|C}}, occurred on June 9, 1955, and the lowest, {{convert|0|F|C}}, occurred on November 11, 1993.<ref name=\"WRCC\"/> The city receives {{convert|35.71|in|mm}} of annual rainfall, which mostly falls from October to March and peaks in December.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=253}}<ref name=\"WRCC\"/> Everett rarely receives significant snowfall and its highest total, {{convert|26.6|in|cm}}, occurred in 1965.<ref name=\"Soil-Survey\"/><ref name=\"WRCC\"/>\n\n{{Weather box \n|location = Everett\n|single line = Y\n| Jan record high F = 72\n| Feb record high F = 74\n| Mar record high F = 82\n| Apr record high F = 85\n| May record high F = 93\n| Jun record high F = 98\n| Jul record high F = 93\n| Aug record high F = 94\n| Sep record high F = 89\n| Oct record high F = 83\n| Nov record high F = 74\n| Dec record high F = 66\n| year record high F = 98\n| Jan high F = 44.9\n| Feb high F = 48.8\n| Mar high F = 52.8\n| Apr high F = 58.1\n| May high F = 63.6\n| Jun high F = 68.3\n| Jul high F = 72.6\n| Aug high F = 72.7\n| Sep high F = 67.8\n| Oct high F = 59.5\n| Nov high F = 50.9\n| Dec high F = 45.7\n| year high F = 58.8\n| Jan low F = 33.1\n| Feb low F = 34.4\n| Mar low F = 36.8\n| Apr low F = 40.4\n| May low F = 45.3\n| Jun low F = 50.2\n| Jul low F = 52.9\n| Aug low F = 52.8\n| Sep low F = 48.3\n| Oct low F = 43\n| Nov low F = 37.6\n| Dec low F = 34.3\n| year low F = 42.4\n| Jan record low F = 1\n| Feb record low F = 2\n| Mar record low F = 10\n| Apr record low F = 23\n| May record low F = 29\n| Jun record low F = 36\n| Jul record low F = 37\n| Aug record low F = 38\n| Sep record low F = 30\n| Oct record low F = 22\n| Nov record low F = 0\n| Dec record low F = 5\n| year record low F = 0\n| precipitation colour = green\n| Jan precipitation inch = 4.51\n| Feb precipitation inch = 3.25\n| Mar precipitation inch = 3.57\n| Apr precipitation inch = 2.7\n| May precipitation inch = 2.34\n| Jun precipitation inch = 2.12\n| Jul precipitation inch = 1.04\n| Aug precipitation inch = 1.2\n| Sep precipitation inch = 1.98\n| Oct precipitation inch = 3.39\n| Nov precipitation inch = 4.65\n| Dec precipitation inch = 4.96\n| year precipitation inch = 35.71\n| Jan precipitation days = 19\n| Feb precipitation days = 16\n| Mar precipitation days = 18\n| Apr precipitation days = 15\n| May precipitation days = 12\n| Jun precipitation days = 10\n| Jul precipitation days = 6\n| Aug precipitation days = 6\n| Sep precipitation days = 9\n| Oct precipitation days = 15\n| Nov precipitation days = 18\n| Dec precipitation days = 19\n| Jan snow inch = 3.3\n| Feb snow inch = 1.2\n| Mar snow inch = 0.6\n| Apr snow inch = 0.2\n| May snow inch = 0\n| Jun snow inch = 0\n| Jul snow inch = 0\n| Aug snow inch = 0\n| Sep snow inch = 0\n| Oct snow inch = 0\n| Nov snow inch = 0.6\n| Dec snow inch = 1.4\n| year snow inch = 7.3\n\n|source 1 = [[Western Regional Climate Center]] (1894\u20132015)<ref name=\"WRCC\">{{cite web |title=Period of Record Monthly Climate Summary: Everett, Washington (452675) |url=http://www.wrcc.dri.edu/cgi-bin/cliMAIN.pl?wa2675 |publisher=[[Western Regional Climate Center]] |accessdate=November 16, 2015}}</ref>\n|date=November 2015\n}}\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Aerial Boeing Everett Factory October 2011.jpg|thumb|right|Aerial view of the [[Boeing Everett Factory]], the largest employer in Snohomish County]]\n\nEverett has a workforce population of 88,146 people with 59,599 who are employed, according to a 2018 estimate from the U.S. Census Bureau.<ref name=\"ACS\">{{cite web |year=2019 |title=Selected Economic Characteristics: Everett, Washington |url=https://data.census.gov/cedsci/table?q=DP03&g=1600000US5322640&tid=ACSDP5Y2018.DP03&hidePreview=true |work=[[American Community Survey]] |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The city also had an estimated 7,335 registered businesses in 2012 providing 94,000 jobs.<ref name=\"USCB-Profile\">{{cite web |title=Profile: Everett, Washington |url=https://data.census.gov/cedsci/profile?g=1600000US5322640&q=Everett |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Comp-Economy\">{{cite web |year=2015 |title=Chapter 7: Economic Development |pages=3\u20134 |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/4862/Chapter-07-Economic-Development-PDF |work=Everett Comprehensive Plan |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Everett's economy is centered around [[aerospace]] manufacturing, maritime activities, the technology sector, and the [[service industry]].<ref name=\"Comp-Economy\"/> The largest employer in the city is airplane manufacturer [[Boeing]], with 31 percent of all jobs.<ref name=\"CAFR2018\"/> The company's main [[Boeing Everett Factory|manufacturing plant]] near Paine Field is the world's largest building by volume.<ref>{{cite web |title=Boeing in Everett |url=http://www.boeing.com/company/about-bca/everett-production-facility.page |publisher=[[Boeing]] |accessdate=September 27, 2016}}</ref> The local economy of Everett and Snohomish County is heavily affected by Boeing's performance, with layoffs and strikes causing downturns in other industries.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dunlop |first=Michelle |date=December 30, 2006 |title=Boeing keeps Snohomish County economy humming |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/boeing-keeps-snohomish-county-economy-humming/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Nohara |first1=Yoshiaki |last2=Dunlop |first2=Michelle |date=October 18, 2008 |title=Strike has ripple effect on local economy |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/strike-has-ripple-effect-on-local-economy/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city's economy in the 19th and early 20th centuries was tied to the lumber trade and maritime industries, including fishing and boat manufacturing.<ref name=\"Herald-WaterfrontHist\">{{cite news |last=Muhlstein  |first=Julie |date=June 1, 2018 |title=Everett and its waterfront were built by the working class |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-built-by-the-working-class/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Everett's last remaining wood [[pulp mill]], owned by [[Kimberly-Clark]], shut down in April 2012 and was demolished a year later, marking the end of the lumber economy's dominance.<ref name=\"Herald-KimClark\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Haglund |first=Noah |date=August 18, 2013 |title=Kimberly-Clark says former mill site better without grass |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/kimberly-clark-says-former-mill-site-better-without-grass/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The aerospace industry in Everett began growing in the late 1960s after Boeing began constructing its assembly plant at Paine Field, bringing suppliers and subcontractors to the area.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kershner |first=Jim |date=September 8, 2015 |title=Boeing and Washington's Aerospace Industry, 1934-2015 |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/11111 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Since the 1990s, the city government has encouraged economic development in other industries to add diversity, particularly in the technology sector.<ref>{{cite news |last=Matlick |first=Justin |date=November 6, 2005 |title=Boomtown dreams: Feisty Everett chases Bremerton, Tacoma with mixed results |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/stories/2005/11/07/story3.html |work=[[Puget Sound Business Journal]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The Port of Everett has also developed its own industrial park in North Everett that is home to an aerospace supplier and distribution centers for [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] and [[FedEx]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=March 5, 2018 |title=Port of Everett's Riverside Business Park finally takes shape |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/everett-riverside-business-park-is-finally-taking-shape/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Podsada |first=Janice |date=September 9, 2019 |title=An Everett business park is getting a big new tenant: Amazon |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/an-everett-business-park-is-getting-a-big-new-tenant-amazon/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2018}}, the largest industry in Everett is manufacturing, with 18 percent of residents employed there, followed by educational services (18%), retail (12%), professional services (11%), and entertainment (11%).<ref name=\"ACS\"/> Electronics manufacturer [[Fluke Corporation]] (now part of [[Fortive]]) is based in Everett and has 1,000 employees in Washington state.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lerman |first=Rachel |date=October 28, 2016 |title=Quiet industrial giant emerges in Everett |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/technology/everetts-fortive-shapes-strategy-for-successful-companies/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> Toymaker [[Funko]] is also headquartered in Downtown Everett, where it has its own retail store that opened in 2017, and operates a distribution center in the city.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hefley |first=Diana |date=August 20, 2017 |title='Funatics' pour into downtown Everett for Funko grand opening |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/funatics-pour-into-downtown-everett-for-funko-grand-opening/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=September 9, 2016 |title=Toymaker Funko moving to downtown Everett |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/news/toymaker-funko-moving-to-downtown-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=September 27, 2016}}</ref> Other large employers in Everett include the [[Providence Regional Medical Center Everett|Providence Regional Medical Center]], with 4,900 employees, the [[U.S. Navy]] with 2,900 employees, and [[Everett Public Schools (Washington)|Everett Public Schools]] with 2,440 employees.<ref name=\"CAFR2018\"/>\n\nApproximately 28 percent of Everett workers are employed at businesses located within the city limit, while 15 percent commute to [[Seattle]].<ref name=\"OnTheMap\">{{cite web |title=Work Destination Report&nbsp;\u2014 Where Workers are Employed Who Live in the Selection Area&nbsp;\u2014 by Places (Cities, CDPs, etc.) |url=https://lehd.ces.census.gov/data/ |publisher=United States Census Bureau |via=[https://onthemap.ces.census.gov/ OnTheMap] |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The majority of the city's employed residents (70%) commute to work in [[Single-occupancy vehicle|single-occupant vehicles]], while 14 percent use [[carpool]]s and 6 percent use [[public transportation]].<ref name=\"ACS\"/> Everett workplaces have employees who live across Snohomish and King counties, with 15 percent from within the city, 7 percent from [[Marysville, Washington|Marysville]], 5 percent from Seattle, and 4 percent from [[Lake Stevens, Washington|Lake Stevens]].<ref name=\"OnTheMap\"/> The changing of [[shift work|first shift]] at the Boeing facility in Everett causes a spike in traffic congestion during the mornings and early afternoons that spills out from freeways onto local streets.<ref>{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=December 26, 2016 |title=Boeing eyes ending staggered start times to optimize production |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/boeing-eyes-ending-staggered-start-times-to-optimize-production/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city's retailers had total sales of $2&nbsp;million in 2012 and are concentrated along two major highways, Evergreen Way and Everett Mall Way, in [[strip mall]]s and standalone [[big-box store]]s.<ref name=\"USCB-Profile\"/><ref name=\"Comp-Economy\"/> The intersection of the two corridors is home to a large [[auto row]] that developed in the 1980s after dealerships relocated from Downtown Everett.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=101}} The [[Everett Mall]], located at the northeast end of Everett Mall Way ([[Washington State Route 99|State Route 99]]), opened in 1974 and has over 100 stores. The mall was expanded in 2005, adding a [[movie theater]] and a new set of stores, but has since lost two major retailers and several other tenants.<ref>{{cite news |last=Haglund |first=Noah |date=September 6, 2013 |title=New tenant seen as key to Everett Mall revival |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/new-tenant-seen-as-key-to-everett-mall-revival-2/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=January 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=February 24, 2017 |title=Everett Mall back on the block for the third time in two years |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/everett-mall-back-on-the-block-for-the-third-time-in-two-years/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Largest employers===\n\n:''Source: 2018 Comprehensive Annual Financial Report''<ref name=\"CAFR2018\">{{cite web |date=June 26, 2019 |title=City of Everett, Washington 2018 Comrpehensive Annual Financial Report For the Year Ended December 31, 2018 |page=175 |url=https://everettwa.gov/ArchiveCenter/ViewFile/Item/1156 |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Rank\n! Employer\n! Number of employees\n|-\n|1\n|[[Boeing]]\n|35,000\n|-\n|2\n|[[Providence Regional Medical Center Everett]]\n|4,906\n|-\n|3\n|[[Washington (state)|State of Washington]]\n|3,000\n|-\n|4\n|[[Naval Station Everett]]\n|2,900\n|-\n|5\n|[[The Everett Clinic]]\n|2,871\n|-\n|6\n|[[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]]\n|2,759\n|-\n|7\n|[[Everett Public Schools (Washington)|Everett Public Schools]]\n|2,443\n|-\n|8\n|[[Fluke Corporation]] ([[Fortive]])\n|1,200\n|-\n|9\n|City of Everett\n|1,198\n|-\n|10\n|[[Snohomish County Public Utility District]]\n|1,004\n|}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1900= 7838\n|1910= 24814\n|1920= 27644\n|1930= 30567\n|1940= 30224\n|1950= 33849\n|1960= 40304\n|1970= 53622\n|1980= 54413\n|1990= 69961\n|2000= 91488\n|2010= 103019\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=111262\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web |date=June 27, 2019 |title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates |url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=February 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|footnote=Sources: U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 6, 2013}}</ref><br />2018 U.S. Census Estimate<ref name=\"2018 Pop Estimate\">{{cite web |title=Population Estimates |url=https://census.gov/data/tables/2018/demo/popest/total-cities-and-towns.html |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=June 5, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\nEverett is the largest city in Snohomish County and the seventh largest in Washington state by population, ranking between [[Kent, Washington|Kent]] and [[Renton, Washington|Renton]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Taylor |first=Chuck |date=May 22, 2015 |title=Marysville among top U.S. cities for population growth |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/marysville-among-top-u-s-cities-for-population-growth/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> It had a population of 103,019 at the time of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 U.S. census]], and an estimated population of 111,800 in 2019 counts from the state government.<ref>{{cite web |author=OFM Forecasting & Research Division |date=August 2019 |title=State of Washington 2019 Population Trends |page=20 |url=https://www.ofm.wa.gov/sites/default/files/public/dataresearch/pop/april1/ofm_april1_poptrends.pdf |publisher=[[Washington State Office of Financial Management]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> The city's [[urban growth area]] has a population of 44,596 residents {{as of|2016|lc=y}} that are part of [[unincorporated area|unincorporated]] Snohomish County.<ref>{{cite web |date=March 22, 2017 |title=Snohomish County Tomorrow 2016 Growth Monitoring Report: Population Growth Trends |page=22 |url=https://snohomishcountywa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/44883/2---2016-GMR---Population-Trends |format=PDF |publisher=Snohomish County Tomorrow Steering Committee |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Everett's population grew by 47 percent from 1990 to 2000 and 13 percent from 2000 to 2010, due to annexations and increased housing development.<ref name=\"Comp-Intro\">{{cite web |date=June 2015 |title=Chapter 1: Introduction |page=13 |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/4858/Chapter-01-Introduction-PDF |work=Everett Comprehensive Plan |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> It is projected to increase by 40,000 to 60,000 residents by 2035 as part of state-mandated growth plans.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stevick |first=Eric |date=July 1, 2009 |title=Snohomish County population rising fast since 2000, led by Marysville |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/snohomish-county-population-rising-fast-since-2000-led-by-marysville/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Herald-Boom15\">{{cite news |last1=Winters |first1=Chris |last2=Catchpole |first2=Dan |date=May 15, 2015 |title=High expectations drive downtown Everett building boom |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/high-expectations-drive-downtown-everett-building-boom/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The city's population growth since 1990 has largely been driven by non-Caucasian racial groups, with the white majority decreasing from 92 percent in 1990 to 75 percent in 2010.<ref name=\"Comp-Intro\"/>\n\nThe city had 16,394 housing units in 2010, 9,181 of which were [[single-family home]]s and 7,213 of which were in [[multi-family housing]].<ref name=\"Comp-Housing\">{{cite web |year=2015 |title=Chapter 4: Housing Element |page=17 |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/4868/Chapter-04-Housing-PDF |work=Everett Comprehensive Plan |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Everett's homeownership rate is among the lowest in Washington, with 44 percent of homes occupied by their owners, and its residents have a low median income relative to the county and Seattle metropolitan area.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=December 1, 2015 |title=Low homeownership rate could make Everett ripe for renewal |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/low-homeownership-rate-could-make-everett-ripe-for-renewal/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The average monthly [[Renting|rent]] for housing units in Everett in 2013 ranged from $700 for a [[studio apartment]] to $2,723 for a five-bedroom home.<ref name=\"Comp-Housing\"/>{{rp|12}} The city also has several [[affordable housing]] complexes that provide 2,461 units to low-income households through federal and local grants.<ref name=\"Comp-Housing\"/>{{rp|13}}\n\n===2010 census===\n\nAs of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 U.S. census]], there were 103,019 people, 41,312 households, and 23,282 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|3079.8|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 44,609 housing units at an average density of {{convert|1333.6|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census|racial makeup]] of the city was 74.6% White, 4.1% African American, 1.4% Native American, 7.8% Asian, 0.7% Pacific Islander, 6.1% from other races, and 5.3% from two or more races. Hispanic or Latino of any race were 14.2% of the population.<ref name=\"QuickFacts\">{{cite web |title=QuickFacts: Everett, Washington |url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/everettcitywashington/POP060210 |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere were 41,312 households of which 30.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 38.2% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 12.5% had a female householder with no husband present, 5.7% had a male householder with no wife present, and 43.6% were non-families. 34.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 9.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.39 and the average family size was 3.09.<ref name=\"QuickFacts\"/>\n\nThe median age in the city was 34.4 years. 22.7% of residents were under the age of 18; 11.3% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 30.6% were from 25 to 44; 25% were from 45 to 64; and 10.3% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 50.9% male and 49.1% female.<ref name=\"QuickFacts\"/>\n\n===2000 census===\n\nAs of the [[2000 United States Census|2000 U.S. census]], there were 91,488 people, 36,325 households and 21,613 families residing in the city.  The population density was 2,814.6 people per square mile (1,086.9/km\u00b2).  There were 38,512 housing units at an average density of 1,184.8 per square mile (457.5/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the city was 56% White, 9% African American, 1.56% Native American, 10% Asian, 4% Pacific Islander, 3.13% from other races and 4.25% from two or more races.  Hispanic or Latino of any race were 13% of the population.<ref name=\"Census2000\">{{cite web |year=2000 |title=Profile of General Demographic Characteristics: Everett city, Washington |url=https://www.psrc.org/sites/default/files/everett.pdf |publisher=United States Census Bureau |via=[[Puget Sound Regional Council]] |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere were 36,325 households, out of which 31.9% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 42.1% were married couples living together, 12.5% had a female householder with no husband present, and 40.5% were non-families. 31.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.40 and the average family size was 3.04.<ref name=\"Census2000\"/>\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 25.1% under the age of 18, 12.3% from 18 to 24, 33.3% from 25 to 44, 18.9% from 45 to 64, and 10.3% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 32 years.  For every 100 females, there were 103.5 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 102.8 males.<ref name=\"Census2000\"/>\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $40,100 and the median income for a family was $46,743.  Males had a median income of $35,852 versus $28,841 for females.  The [[per capita income]] for the city was $20,577.  About 10.1% of families and 19.5% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 16% of those under the age of 18 and 12.1% of those ages 65 and older.<ref name=\"Census2000\"/>\n\n===Crime===\n{{Infobox UCR\n|city_name = Everett\n|year = 2015\n|homicide = 5\n|rape = 44\n|robbery = 148\n|aggravated_assault = 225\n|burglary = 974\n|larceny_theft = 4316\n|motor_vehicle_theft = 908\n|arson = 33\n|source_url = https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/seattle/news/press-releases/the-fbi-releases-2015-crime-statistics-for-washington-state\n|source_name = 2015 FBI Crime Statistics\n|notes = 2015 population: 107,219\n}}\n\nThe Everett Police Department has 201 uniformed police officers and five unfilled positions {{as of|2020|lc=y}}.<ref name=\"Herald-Crime20\">{{cite news |last=Watanabe |first=Ben |date=February 17, 2020 |title=Crime is down, but Everett hopes to hire 24 more officers |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/crime-is-down-but-everett-hopes-to-hire-24-more-officers/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> The city had 422 [[violent crime]]s and 6,198 [[property crime]]s reported to law enforcement in 2015.<ref name=\"UCR\">{{cite web |date=September 2016 |title=Table 8 \u2013 Washington: Offenses Known to Law Enforcement by City, 2015 |url=https://ucr.fbi.gov/crime-in-the-u.s/2015/crime-in-the-u.s.-2015/tables/table-8/table-8-state-pieces/table_8_offenses_known_to_law_enforcement_washington_by_city_2015.xls |work=[[Uniform Crime Reports]] |publisher=[[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> The number of reported crimes in Everett has declined since reaching their peak in 2009\u201310, with 610 violent crimes and 7,672 property crimes.<ref name=\"Herald-Crime20\"/> Everett had ranked in the top 20 percent of U.S. cities for reported crimes in reports by [[CQ Press]], which included property crimes and burglary among violent crimes.<ref>{{cite news |last=Holtz |first=Jackson |date=November 23, 2008 |title=List distorts Everett crime statistics |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/list-distorts-everett-crime-statistics/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> It was ranked 49th among cities in Washington for crimes per capita in a 2019 study by the [[National Council for Home Safety and Security]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Clarridge |first=Christine |date=January 29, 2019 |title=These are Washington's safest and least safe cities, according to crime stats |page= |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/crime/is-seattle-safe-you-might-be-better-off-in-snoqualmie-or-sunnyside/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Everett Police Department and Snohomish County Sheriff's Office began criminal investigations against operators and employees of various [[bikini barista]] coffee stands in 2009 for violating adult entertainment laws.<ref name=\"Herald-Bikini20\">{{cite news |last=Davey |first=Stephanie |date=February 4, 2020 |title=Everett bikini baristas file petition to U.S. Supreme Court |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-bikini-baristas-file-petition-to-u-s-supreme-court/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Rikki |date=October 30, 2013 |title=Everett police raid bikini coffee stand; 3 arrested |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-police-raid-bikini-coffee-stand-3-arrested/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The city government passed a [[dress code]] ordinance for food service workers in August 2017, but were met with a lawsuit from stand operators and employees over the constitutionality of the ordinance.<ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Rikki |date=September 11, 2017 |title=Bikini baristas sue Everett, say dress code unfair |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/bikini-baristas-sue-everett-over-new-dress-code-rule/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> The ordinance was suspended by a preliminary injuction from the U.S. District Court in December 2017, but the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit|Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals]] ruled in favor of the city government in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Clarridge |first=Christine |date=August 19, 2019 |title=No new bottom line in Everett's bikini barista brouhaha |page= |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/bikini-baristas-arent-giving-up-after-appeals-court-rules-everett-can-regulate-their-outfits/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> The city government does not plan to enforce the dress code ordinance until the lawsuit is resolved with the lifting of the preliminary injunction.<ref name=\"Herald-Bikini20\"/>\n\nThe city has a high rate of [[opioid abuse]], particularly [[OxyContin]] and [[heroin]], fueled by cross-state drug trafficking.<ref name=\"LAT-Oxy\">{{cite news |last=Ryan |first=Harriet |date=January 19, 2017 |title=City devastated by OxyContin use sues Purdue Pharma, claims drugmaker put profits over citizens' welfare |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-oxycontin-lawsuit-20170118-story.html |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hefley |first1=Diana |last2=North |first2=Scott |date=January 18, 2017 |title=Everett ready to sue OxyContin maker over opioid deaths, crime |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-might-sue-oxycontin-maker-over-opioid-deaths-crime/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> The widespread opioid use also contributed to a 65 percent rise in [[homelessness]] in Everett from 2015 to 2017, straining local [[homeless shelter|shelters]] and supportive housing systems.<ref>{{cite news |last=Le |first=Phuong |date=December 27, 2017 |title=Addiction, mental illness complicate help for the homeless |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/addiction-mental-illness-complicate-help-for-the-homeless/ |work=The Everett Herald |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> The city government filed a lawsuit against OxyContin manufacturer [[Purdue Pharma]] in January 2017, claiming that the company had been [[gross negligence|grossly negligent]] in distributing the drug and containing its effect on Everett residents. The lawsuit also identified a drug trafficking ring based in [[Los Angeles]], large prescriptions by doctors to procure the drug, and direct marketing by Purdue Pharma as contributing factors to the rise in opioid cases.<ref name=\"LAT-Oxy\"/> Everett's lawsuit was joined by complaints from other jurisdictions, including Snohomish County and the Tulalip Tribes, and was heard in the [[United States District Court for the Northern District of Ohio|U.S. District Court of Northern Ohio]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Giordano |first1=Lizz |last2=Haglund |first2=Noah |date=September 1, 2019 |title=Oklahoma's opioid verdict could bolster Everett\u2019s own lawsuit |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/oklahomas-opioid-verdict-could-bolster-everetts-own-lawsuit/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government and politics==\n\nEverett is a first-class city with an organized [[city charter|charter]] and a [[mayor\u2013council government|mayor\u2013council]] form of government.<ref name=\"MRSC-First\">{{cite web |date=March 10, 2020 |title=First Class Cities |url=http://mrsc.org/getdoc/490c32b2-2cd8-480a-92bc-a4ec66fbeb1c/First-Class-Cities-by-Form-of-Government.aspx |publisher=[[Municipal Research and Services Center]] |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The city's [[mayor]] and seven councilmembers are elected [[at-large]] to four-year terms in staggered elections that take place during odd-numbered years. Beginning in 2021, the Everett city council will elect five members from districts and two from at-large seats.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=November 19, 2018 |title=Significant changes coming to Everett's City Council |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/significant-changes-coming-to-everetts-city-council/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The city council meets weekly on Wednesdays and offers live television and web broadcasts via the [[Everett Channel]].<ref>{{cite web |title=City Council |url=https://everettwa.gov/409/City-Council |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The city government is based out of the Wall Street Building in Downtown Everett, a 10-story office tower adjacent to the historic [[Everett City Hall]]\u2014now home to the city police department and city council chambers.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=December 6, 2016 |title=City of Everett tightens Wall Street building security |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-hires-security-for-building-housing-mayor-city-offices/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Debra |date=February 26, 2012 |title=Plan could allow new name for old Everett city hall |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/plan-could-allow-new-name-for-old-everett-city-hall/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Cassie Franklin]], a former city councilmember, was elected as mayor in 2017 and is the second woman and first non-appointee to hold the office.<ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Rikki |date=November 16, 2017 |title=Franklin becomes first woman to be elected mayor of Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/cassie-franklin-becomes-first-woman-to-be-elected-mayor-of-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> The mayor of Everett is responsible for appointing the heads of various city departments, the city clerk, the city treasurer, the [[police chief|police]] and [[fire chief|fire]] chiefs, and members of service commissions and boards.<ref name=\"MRSC-First\"/> The city government has 1,200 employees and an operating budget of $148.7&nbsp;million for 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=January 11, 2019 |title=City of Everett offers buyouts to 330 senior employees |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/city-of-everett-offers-buyouts-to-330-senior-employees/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=November 15, 2019 |title=Everett balances 2020 budget with no new fees or taxes |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-balances-2020-budget-with-no-new-fees-or-taxes/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> It provides a range of municipal services, including police, fire, [[emergency medical services]], public works, a [[housing authority]], zoning and planning, parks and recreation, and some utilities.<ref name=\"CAFR2018\"/>{{rp|2}}<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web |title=About Everett |url=https://everettwa.gov/272/About-Everett |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> Everett also has a [[municipal court]] that was established in 1987 and has two judges who are elected to four-year terms.<ref>{{cite news |last=Haglund |first=Noah |date=December 20, 2013 |title=First woman to serve on Everett Municipal Court |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/first-woman-to-serve-on-everett-municipal-court/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The city government runs its own [[Everett Transit|public transit]] and [[Everett Public Library|library]] systems, which are separate from the countywide [[Community Transit]] and [[Sno-Isle Libraries]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=November 8, 2019 |title=Everett entertains pitch for joining county-wide bus system |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-entertains-pitch-for-joining-county-wide-bus-system/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett is also the [[county seat]] of [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]] and houses several major government facilities on a campus in Downtown Everett. The campus includes the [[Snohomish County Courthouse|county courthouse]], county jail, administrative offices, and the main precinct of the [[Snohomish County Sheriff|county sheriff]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Departments-Offices-Campus Map |url=https://snohomishcountywa.gov/2902/Departments-Offices-CampusMap |publisher=Snohomish County |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kelly |first=Brian |date=June 1, 2005 |title=$175 million later... |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/175-million-later/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt the federal level, Everett is part of the [[Washington's 2nd congressional district|2nd congressional district]], represented by Democrat [[Rick Larsen]] since 2001.<ref name=\"DistrictMap\">{{cite map |date=February 7, 2012 |title=Washington State Legislative & Congressional District Map |url=http://www.redistricting.wa.gov/assets/maps/FoldedMap_State.pdf |inset=[http://www.redistricting.wa.gov/assets/maps/FoldedMap_Insets.pdf Puget Sound & Other Areas] |publisher=[[Washington State Redistricting Commission]] |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Cornfield |first=Jerry |date=January 7, 2019 |title=Now in majority, state\u2019s Democrats ready to use new clout |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/now-in-majority-states-democrats-ready-to-use-new-clout/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> At the state level, most of the city is in the [[Washington's 38th legislative district|38th legislative district]] alongside Marysville and the Tulalip Indian Reservation. The southern neighborhoods of the city, including Silver Lake, are part of the [[Washington's 21st legislative district|21st legislative district]], shared with Edmonds and Mukilteo.<ref name=\"DistrictMap\"/> Everett is also part of the [[Snohomish County Council]]'s 2nd district, which also includes Mukilteo and the Tulalip Indian Reservation.<ref>{{cite map |title=Snohomish County Council Districts |url=http://snohomishcountywa.gov/DocumentCenter/Home/View/49 |publisher=Snohomish County Elections |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Arts===\n[[File:Everett Theater 02.jpg|thumb|The Historic Everett Theatre, opened in 1901]]\n\nEverett is described as a \"largely [[blue-collar]] city\", but is home to a regional arts scene that includes galleries, community theaters, music, and artwork.<ref name=\"Herald-Music\">{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=August 27, 2014 |title=With a change of tune, Snohomish County Music Project thrives |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/with-a-change-of-tune-snohomish-county-music-project-thrives/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wood |first=Kyle R. |date=August 16, 1996 |title=Selling Snohomish County |page=B1 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19960816&slug=2344504 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The city has five major [[performing arts]] venues that host various groups and traveling events.<ref name=\"Times-Venues\">{{cite news |last=Wright |first=Diane |date=June 20, 2007 |title=Take a seat |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/take-a-seat/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 834-seat [[Historic Everett Theatre]] on Colby Avenue opened in 1901 and hosts community theater productions, musical groups, [[improv comedy]], and film screenings.<ref name=\"Herald-Theater\">{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=June 13, 2018 |title=Historic Everett Theatre holds an audition for new investors |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/historic-everett-theatre-seeking-investors/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The city once had a \"theater district\" in downtown that included the Everett, Granada, Balboa, and Roxy theaters, all opened during the early 20th century.{{sfnp|Cameron|LeWarne|May|O'Donnell|2005|p=222}} The Everett Theatre is the last surviving theater from the era, having been partially rebuilt following a fire in December 1923, renovated into a [[Multiplex (movie theater)|triplex]] theater in 1979, closed in 1989, and restored to its original state beginning in 2000.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brooks |first=Diane |date=February 28, 2000 |title=Theater begins to look like old self |page=B1 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=September 7, 2006 |title=Theater switches to edgier material |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/theater-switches-to-edgier-material/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The regional [[Village Theatre]] performs in [[Issaquah, Washington|Issaquah]] and at the Everett Performing Arts Center, a city-owned facility that opened in 1993 and is also home to the Everett Chorale.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fiege |first=Gale |date=January 8, 2015 |title=Five times a year, Village Theatre packs up and heads to Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/five-times-a-year-village-theatre-packs-up-and-heads-to-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Fiege |first=Gale |date=December 2, 2015 |title=Everett Chorale kicks off golden anniversary this weekend |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/everett-chorale-kicks-off-golden-anniversary-this-weekend/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The Village Theatre opened KidStage, a venue for young performers, in 2011 by converting a former [[bank branch]] building adjacent to the Everett Performing Arts Center.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=September 26, 2011 |title=Kids at center stage |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/kids-at-center-stage/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The Everett Civic Auditorium at [[Everett High School (Washington)|Everett High School]] was completed in 1939 and is home to the Everett Philharmonic Orchestra, which was formed in 2010 by musicians from the former Everett Symphony after it ran into financial issues.<ref name=\"Herald-Music\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=February 19, 2010 |title=Everett Symphony musicians form own orchestra |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-symphony-musicians-form-own-orchestra/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city's [[public art]] program is managed by the Everett Cultural Arts Commission, a citizen advisory board established in 1974 alongside a [[percent for art]] program for public projects.<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=February 17, 2019 |title=Everett couple honored for their 'deep passion for the arts' |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/everett-couple-honored-for-their-deep-passion-for-the-arts/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> In addition to public art, the commission manages 16 [[street piano]]s in Downtown Everett that are painted by local artists and available for public use every August.<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=August 8, 2019 |title=Music returns to Everett sidewalks with Street Tunes program |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/music-returns-to-everett-sidewalks-with-street-tunes-program/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Everett's main arts district is on a three-block section of Hoyt Avenue in downtown, which is home to the [[Schack Art Center]] and several sculptures installed in the late 2000s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=February 26, 2013 |title=New lights shine on Everett's art district |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/new-lights-shine-on-everetts-art-district/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The Schack Art Center opened in 2011 as a multipurpose exhibition space and artist workshop, with facilities for various mediums and housing for artists provided by [[Artspace Projects|Artspace]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=April 29, 2011 |title=Art center opens this weekend |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/schack-art-center-opening/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=December 18, 2009 |title=Idamae Schack's generosity built Everett's arts and cultural community |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/jobs-must-be-cut-for-actual-savings/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The center was originally the Arts Council of Snohomish County and named in honor of John and Idamae Schack, longtime supporters of the organization and arts in the region;<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=August 27, 2015 |title=Schacks' quiet generosity leaves huge legacy in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/schacks-quiet-generosity-leaves-huge-legacy-in-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> in its first year, the Schack Art Center had 265 artists on exhibit and 33,000 visitors, helping to revitalize downtown during the [[Great Recession]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=April 28, 2012 |title=The key to Schack Art Center's success |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/the-key-to-schack-art-centers-success/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kareiva |first=Celina |date=February 19, 2012 |title=Everett arts center revitalizes downtown, artists |page=H1 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/thearts/2017517345_schack19.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501081252/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/thearts/2017517345_schack19.html |archivedate=May 1, 2012 |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The Everett area has attracted artists and musicians from Seattle due to its relative affordability and incentives from the city government.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wilkinson |first=Eric |date=November 30, 2016 |title=New CD looks to put Everett on the musical map |url=https://www.king5.com/article/news/local/everett/new-cd-looks-to-put-everett-on-the-musical-map/359623390 |publisher=[[KING-TV|KING 5 News]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Potterf |first=Tina |date=June 15, 2005 |title=Wendy Becker: Everett's arts guru |page=H14 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=20050615&slug=becker15n |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Events and tourism===\n\nThe city hosts several annual events and festivals for local arts and celebrations, usually during the summer months. The city's waterfront hosts an annual parade and [[fireworks]] display on [[Independence Day (United States)|Independence Day]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Davey |first=Stephanie |date=July 5, 2019 |title=July 4th parade is a 'special tradition' for local families |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/july-4th-parade-is-a-special-tradition-for-local-families/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Everett has hosted a downtown [[sausage]] and street festival annually in September since 1977.<ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Evan |date=September 27, 2018 |title=Fill up on German grub at Everett Sausage Fest this weekend |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/fill-up-on-german-grub-at-everett-sausage-fest-this-weekend/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Several annual festivals were established in the 1990s, including a [[film festival]] in February,<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=February 7, 2019 |title=Everett Film Festival marks its 20th year with 10 screenings |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/see-10-short-films-and-documentaries-at-everett-film-festival/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> the Cruzin' to Colby [[classic car]] show in May,<ref>{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=March 29, 2017 |title=Cool cars converge as Cruzin' to Colby returns to Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/cool-cars-converge-as-cruzin-to-colby-returns-to-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> the Sorticulture garden festival in June,<ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Evan |date=June 1, 2019 |title=Sprinklers with style, and much more at Everett's Sorticulture |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/sprinklers-with-style-and-much-more-at-everetts-sorticulture/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> and the Fresh Paint [[art show]] in August.<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=August 16, 2018 |title=Fresh Paint to bring artists, art lovers to waterfront |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/fresh-paint-to-bring-artists-art-lovers-to-waterfront/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The city's largest annual summer festival, the Salty Sea Days, was established in 1970 and included a parade, [[hydroplane race]]s, a classic auto show, and other events. It was originally subsidized using city [[lodging tax]]es until 2003, and shut down three years later.<ref>{{cite news |last=Langston |first=Jennifer |date=August 26, 2003 |title=Puget Sound Journal: Everett's summer fest not worth its salt, some say |page=B3 |url=https://www.seattlepi.com/news/article/Puget-Sound-Journal-Everett-s-summer-fest-not-1122698.php |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Warnick |first=Jennifer |date=March 1, 2005 |title=Group scuttles Salty Sea Days |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/group-scuttles-salty-sea-days/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Everett [[farmers market]] began in 1994 and operates on Sundays from May to October with 200 vendors and about 5,000 weekly visitors.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=July 20, 2019 |title=Farmers Market is leaving Boxcar, moving to downtown Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/farmers-market-is-leaving-boxcar-moving-to-downtown-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> It was originally located at the Port of Everett but moved in 2019 to Wetmore Avenue in downtown because of parking and accessibility issues at the waterfront site.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Debra |date=June 6, 2011 |title=Future murky for Everett waterfront farmers market |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/article/20110606/NEWS01/706069912 |work=The Everett Herald |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728064906/http://www.heraldnet.com/article/20110606/NEWS01/706069912 |archivedate=July 28, 2011 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Herald-FM19\">{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=August 13, 2019 |title=Long parking lines, costs led Everett Farmers Market to move |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/parking-lines-costs-led-to-move-by-everett-farmers-market/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The farmers market also operates popup [[bazaar]]s during the off-season and a Wednesday market at [[Everett Station]] during the summer.<ref>{{cite news |last=Watanabe |first=Ben |date=February 10, 2020 |title=First popup Everett Farmers Market draws hundreds of people |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/first-popup-everett-farmers-market-draws-hundreds-of-people/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The waterfront remains home to a summer [[concert]] series that has been staged annually since 1991.<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=June 20, 2019 |title=A sure sign summer's here: 10 free concerts at Everett marina |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/a-sure-sign-summers-here-10-free-concerts-at-everett-marina/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett's government and the Everett Downtown Association have also launched tourism initiatives that have created new events and promotional branding for Everett.<ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Rikki |date=February 27, 2014 |title=One-man tourism bureau wants world to 'Experience Everett' |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/one-man-tourism-bureau-wants-world-to-experience-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The city government launched a [[logo]] design contest in 2014 that had 850 entries and 5,700 votes from local residents.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=December 4, 2014 |title=New Everett logo chosen from 850 entries |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/new-everett-logo-chosen-from-850-entries/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The winning design was later withdrawn due to its similarity to the logo of financial services company [[Envestnet]] and was replaced by a new brand design in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=October 25, 2015 |title=Everett's new website successful, but logo is no more |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everetts-new-website-successful-but-logo-is-no-more/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=March 2019 |title=Everett Logo |url=https://everettwa.gov/2314/Everett-Logo |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> A [[craft beer]] festival was established in 2012 by the [[Washington Beer Commission]] and was later renamed to the Upper Left Beerfest in 2017 after the city government took over operations.<ref>{{cite news |last=Swaney |first=Aaron |date=September 15, 2017 |title=Upper Left Beerfest raises a glass to the area's good taste |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/upper-left-beerfest-new-festival-to-enter-everetts-beer-scene/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The Fisherman's Village Music Festival, established in 2014, takes place annually over a three-day weekend in May at four stages in Downtown Everett. The music festival includes performances from 50 local and national artists as well as art exhibitions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rietmulder |first=Michael |date=March 29, 2018 |title=With Fisherman's Village Music Festival, Everett out-rocks Seattle one weekend a year |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/with-fishermans-village-music-festival-everett-out-rocks-seattle-one-weekend-a-year/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Evan |date=May 9, 2019 |title=Fisherman's Village Music Festival expands to Everett Station |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/fishermans-village-music-festival-expands-to-everett-station/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Everett area has several major tourist attractions, particularly those themed around aviation. The [[Future of Flight Aviation Center & Boeing Tour|Future of Flight Aviation Center]] at Paine Field, owned by the county government and operated by Boeing, has several aviation exhibits and includes a tour of the Boeing assembly plant. It is the most popular tourist attraction in Snohomish County, with 495,000 total visitors in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gates |first=Dominic |date=February 28, 2018 |title=Boeing, Snohomish County hold key to Future of Flight as aviation center faces turbulent times |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeing-snohomish-county-hold-key-to-future-of-flight-aviation-centers-future/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> The [[Flying Heritage & Combat Armor Museum]] opened in 2008 at a renovated Paine Field hangar and houses a collection of restored 20th century military planes and vehicles.<ref>{{cite news |last=Catchpole |first=Dan |date=April 11, 2017 |title=Growing Flying Heritage Collection now has a new name |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/growing-flying-heritage-collection-now-has-a-new-name/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> The [[Imagine Children's Museum]] opened in 2004 at a renovated bank building in Downtown Everett after relocating from Marysville. It has interactive exhibits designed to teach children about local history, science, and the arts.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dunnewind |first=Stephanie |date=October 16, 2004 |title=Exploring children's museums: They educate and stimulate; they're expanding, and more are opening |page=C1 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=20041016&slug=childmuseum16 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=October 7, 2012 |title=Imagine Children's Museum adds new exhibits |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/life/imagine-children%C2%92s-museum-adds-new-exhibits/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Media===\n\nThe ''[[Everett Herald]]'' is the city's daily newspaper, providing local and national news for 40,000 subscribers in Snohomish County. It began publication on February 11, 1901, emerging as the city's lone daily newspaper from a field of three competitors established in the early 1890s, including the ''Everett News'', ''Everett Times'', and ''Everett Tribune''.<ref name=\"Editions\">{{cite book |last1=Bagwell |first1=Steve |last2=Stapilus |first2=Randy |year=2013 |title=New Editions: The Northwest's newspapers as they were, are, and will be |pages=212\u2013213 |publisher=Ridenbaugh Press |location=Carlton, Oregon |isbn=978-0-945648-10-9 |oclc=861618089}}</ref> The newspaper remained under local ownership until it was purchased by [[The Washington Post Company]] in 1978 and it was sold to [[Sound Publishing]] in 2013.<ref name=\"Editions\"/><ref>{{cite news |date=March 4, 2013 |title=Herald sale to Sound Publishing completed |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/herald-sale-to-sound-publishing-completed/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The ''Herald'' launched its online website on January 5, 1997, the monthly ''Herald Business Journal'' in 1998,<ref>{{cite web |title=The Herald Business Journal |url=http://www.soundpublishing.com/titles/the-herald-business-journal/ |publisher=[[Sound Publishing]] |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> and began publishing a weekly Spanish-language newspaper, ''La Raza del Noroeste'', in April 2006.<ref>{{cite web |title=About the Daily Herald and Heraldnet |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/article/99999999/EXTRAS02/676034648 |publisher=The Everett Herald |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716223513/http://www.heraldnet.com/article/99999999/EXTRAS02/676034648 |archivedate=July 16, 2010 |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Arriola |first=Cindy |date=February 14, 2013 |title=El futuro de \"La Raza\" |language=Spanish |trans-title=The future of \"La Raza\" |url=https://www.larazanw.com/noticias/el-futuro-de-la-raza/ |work=La Raza del Noroeste |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> My Everett News is an independent online news outlet for Everett that was established in 2011 and is affiliated with ''[[The Seattle Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news |date=July 13, 2011 |title=Seattle Times announces more local news partners |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/seattle-times-announces-more-local-news-partners-1/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city is part of the [[Media in Seattle|Seattle\u2013Tacoma media market]], ranked 13th among U.S. metro areas, which includes several major television and radio stations.<ref>{{cite web |date=September 28, 2019 |title=Local Television Market Universe Estimates |page=1 |url=https://www.nielsen.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2019/09/2019-20-dma-ranker.pdf |publisher=[[Nielsen Media Research]] |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> [[KONG-TV]], a Seattle-based broadcast channel that is affiliated with [[KING-TV]], has been licensed to Everett sine 1984 and debuted in 1997.<ref>{{cite news |last=Levesque |first=John |date=July 2, 1997 |title=KING grooms KONG for a Monday debut and a spot on cable |page=D10 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer}}</ref> The City of Everett also runs The Everett Channel (formerly Everett TV), a [[government-access television]] station that broadcasts local events, city meetings, and special programming.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Everett Channel |url=https://everettwa.gov/408/Everett-Channel |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wright |first=Diane |date=July 18, 2007 |title=Everett's little TV station that could |page= |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/everetts-little-tv-station-that-could/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Everett itself has four radio stations.<ref>{{cite news |last=Guiney |first=Kelley |date=January 2, 2010 |title=Neighborhood of the week: North Everett |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/realestate/2010652800_realneighborhood03.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107053938/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/realestate/2010652800_realneighborhood03.html |archivedate=January 7, 2010 |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> The Skotdal family owns two stations in Everett that share facilities with the Everett Post: [[KRKO|KRKO-AM]], which began broadcasting in 1922 and primary plays [[Classic hits]] along with local sports;<ref>{{cite web |last=Blecha |first=Peter |date=December 6, 2010 |title=KRKO: Everett's Historic Radio Station |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/9620 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> and [[KKXA|KKXA-AM]], a country music station launched in 2011.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=October 7, 2016 |title=Two Everett AM radio stations approved to broadcast on FM |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/two-everett-am-radio-stations-approved-to-broadcast-on-fm/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Brown |first=Andrea |date=April 10, 2018 |title=An Everett 'potcast' explains what all the buzz is about |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/what-all-the-buzz-is-about/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> [[KSER|KSER-FM]] is an independent [[public radio]] station founded in 1991 to serve Snohomish County, carrying local news, music programming, and nationally syndicated news.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=March 12, 2016 |title=At 25, Everett's KSER still entertains, informs community |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/at-25-everetts-kser-still-entertains-informs-community/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Everett is also the home to [[KWYZ|KWYZ-AM]] (Radio Hankook), a [[Korean language]] news and entertainment station that launched in 1997 and is broadcast from [[Federal Way, Washington|Federal Way]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Virgin |first=Bill |date=June 10, 1999 |title=Korean-language stations a resource for immigrants |page=C6 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kugiya |first=Hugo |date=July 8, 2014 |title=Radio Hankook: The heart of Korea on Washington radio |url=https://crosscut.com/2014/07/korean-radio-hankook-federal-way-seattle |work=[[Crosscut.com]] |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Libraries===\n[[File:Everett Library 01.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Everett Public Library]] in Downtown Everett, built in 1934 and renovated in 1991]]\n\nThe [[Everett Public Library]] system has two locations with 258,133 total items and serves 45,205 registered members in the city and surrounding communities {{as of|2018|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite web |date=September 2019 |title=2018 Washington Public Library Statistical Report |pages=50\u201356 |url=https://www.sos.wa.gov/_assets/library/libraries/libdev/2018stats.pdf |publisher=[[Washington State Library]] |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> The library was founded in 1894 and moved into a [[Everett Carnegie Library|permanent building]] in 1905. The current downtown library opened in 1934 and was expanded in 1991;<ref>{{cite web |last=Van Wingen |first=Melinda |date=December 3, 2019 |title=Everett Public Library |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/20926 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> a branch library in South Everett opened in 1985 and was renovated in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=December 11, 2019 |title=It's a launch for Everett library's renovated Evergreen Branch |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/its-a-launch-for-everett-librarys-renovated-evergreen-branch/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> In 2017, [[Sno-Isle Libraries]], the countywide library system, opened a demonstration branch at a [[strip mall]] in South Everett to serve the Mariner area.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bray |first=Kari |date=February 9, 2017 |title=Everett community finally gets long-awaited library |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-community-finally-gets-long-awaited-library/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Historic preservation===\n[[File:Henry M. Jackson's Home-1.jpg|thumb|Senator [[Henry M. Jackson]]'s home in North Everett]]\n\nEverett is home to 14 properties listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"LandmarkMap\">{{cite map |date=April 23, 2019 |title=Historic Register Properties & Areas |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/19452/Historic-Register-Properties-and-Areas |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref> The city also maintains its own register of historic places that began in 1987 and has 35 listed properties.<ref name=\"Herald-History17\">{{cite news |date=April 7, 2017 |title=Groups work to preserve Everett's rich history |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/advertising/groups-work-to-preserve-everetts-rich-history/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref> A non-profit preservation group, Historic Everett, was founded in 2002 and hosts educational events and tours of the city.<ref name=\"Herald-History17\"/>\n\nIn addition to historic properties, the city has several designated [[Historic districts in the United States|historic districts]]: [[Hewitt Avenue Historic District]] in Downtown Everett; the [[Rucker Hill Historic District]]; and the [[Swalwell Block]]. Several historic overlay districts are designated by the city government, including the Riverside Overlay, the Norton\u2013Grand Overlay, and the Rucker\u2013Grand Overlay, which includes the home of the former U.S. Senator [[Henry M. Jackson]].<ref name=\"LandmarkMap\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=October 21, 2018 |title=Jackson home stays in family, but many treasures to be sold |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/jackson-home-stays-in-family-but-many-treasures-to-be-sold/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Several properties within the historic districts have undergone renovation and restoration work in the 21st century to preserve their historic value, partially in response to the demolition of other buildings for new construction.<ref>{{cite news |last=Chircop |first=David |date=November 2, 2007 |title=How Everett can keep old buildings amid new |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/how-everett-can-keep-old-buildings-amid-new/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Everett Museum of History was established in 1953 as a countywide historical association and maintained its own museum until 2007. The organization's collections moved between several historic buildings, including the former [[Everett Carnegie Library]] and part of the [[Everett Mall]], while a new location was sought.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=August 28, 2016 |title=Everett Museum of History seeks a forever home |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-museum-of-history-seeks-a-forever-home/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref> A permanent museum at the former downtown offices of the ''Everett Herald'' is planned to open in 2021.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=December 21, 2017 |title=A Christmas present for the keepers of Everett's past |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/a-present-for-the-past/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=https://everett-museum.org/everett-museum-of-history/ |publisher=Everett Museum of History |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:Everett Events Center.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Angel of the Winds Arena]], opened in 2003 for the [[Everett Silvertips]] and other teams]]\n\nEverett is home to two sports venues that are used by professional [[minor league]] teams and for other events.<ref name=\"Times-Sports05\">{{cite news |last=Alexander |first=Brian |date=October 19, 2005 |title=Snohomish County minor league teams are a major success |page=H16 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=20051019&slug=minorleagues19n |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The [[Angel of the Winds Arena]], an indoor arena in downtown which seats 8,149, is home to [[Everett Silvertips]] of the [[Western Hockey League]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Watanabe |first=Ben |date=May 4, 2018 |title=Silvertips fans: Meet the enemy stronghold of Swift Current |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/silvertips-fans-meet-the-enemy-stronghold-of-swift-current/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> It opened in 2003 at a cost of $83&nbsp;million and includes a community [[ice rink]] and a [[convention center]] for use by other events.<ref name=\"Times-Arena03\"/> The arena has also hosted basketball games for the [[Seattle Storm]] of the [[WNBA]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Patterson |first=Nick |date=January 16, 2020 |title=Storm returning to Everett for 8 games in 2020 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/storm-returning-to-everett-for-8-games-in-2020/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> indoor tennis events including the [[2020 Fed Cup]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Patterson |first=Nick |date=February 17, 2020 |title=USTA: Everett aces first time hosting Fed Cup qualifier |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/usta-everett-aces-first-time-hosting-fed-cup-qualifier/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> and two editions of the [[Skate America]] figure skating championships in 2008 and 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last=Patterson |first=Nick |date=October 30, 2018 |title=Can Everett become a regular on the figure-skating circuit? |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/skate-americas-encore-in-everett-deemed-a-success/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The [[Everett AquaSox]] of the [[Northwest League]] play at Funko Field, a 3,682-seat baseball stadium that is part of the [[Everett Memorial Stadium]] complex.<ref>{{cite news |last=Calkins |first=Matt |date=August 2, 2019 |title=As he tries to revive MLB career, Felix Hernandez remains King in Everett |page=C1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/mariners/felix-hernandez-after-rehab-start-in-everett-it-feels-good-to-be-back-on-the-mound/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The Memorial Stadium complex was built in 1947 and also includes a 12,000-seat football and track stadium that is used by the city's various high school teams.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=157}}<ref>{{cite news |date=September 6, 2001 |title=Ticket prices and more for region's football stadiums |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=20010906&slug=stadiumweb06 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city formerly had additional indoor sports teams who played in minor leagues: the [[Snohomish County Explosion]], which played from 2008 to 2010 in the defunct [[International Basketball League]];<ref>{{cite news |last=Lommers |first=Aaron |date=April 8, 2011 |title=New owners bring Explosion back to Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/new-owners-bring-explosion-back-to-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> the [[Everett Hawks]] of the [[National Indoor Football League]] and [[AF2]], who folded in 2007; the [[Everett Raptors]] of the [[Indoor Football League]], who played for one season in 2012;<ref>{{cite news |last=Boyle |first=John |date=February 24, 2012 |title=Everett Raptors make their debut Saturday night |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/everett-raptors-make-their-debut-saturday-night/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> and the [[Washington Stealth]] of the [[National Lacrosse League]], who moved to British Columbia in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |date=June 27, 2013 |title=Stealth moving to Langley, B.C. |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/stealth-moving-to-langley-b-c/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nEverett also hosted several minor league soccer teams, including the [[Seattle BigFoot|Everett BigFoot]] of the third-division [[USISL Pro League]], who began play in 1995 and moved to [[West Seattle]] in 1997.<ref>{{cite news |last=Peoples |first=John |date=February 2, 1995 |title=Bigfoot hoping to leave mark on Everett, soccer landscape |page=C9 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19950202&slug=2102732 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=March 17, 1997 |title=Around the Northwest |page=D8 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> The [[North Sound SeaWolves]] of the [[USL Premier Development League]] began play at [[Mariner High School (Everett, Washington)|Mariner High School]] in 2011 and moved to [[Edmonds, Washington|Edmonds]] the following season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Allende |first=Mike |date=October 13, 2011 |title=SeaWolves fans pick team's new logo |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/seawolves-fans-pick-teams-new-logo/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> Everett Jets FC, an ameatur team based at Memorial Stadium, are set to begin their inaugural 2020 season in the [[Evergreen Premier League]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Patterson |first=Nick |date=January 27, 2020 |title=Community sports roundup: Everett Jets FC to join men's league |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/community-sports-roundup-everett-jets-fc-to-join-mens-league/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Club\n! Sport\n! League\n! Founded\n! Venue\n! Championships\n|-\n| [[Everett AquaSox]]\n| align=center | [[Baseball]]\n| [[Northwest League]]\n| align=center | 1984\n| [[Everett Memorial Stadium|Funko Field]]\n| 1985, 2010\n|-\n| [[Everett Jets FC]]\n| align=center | [[Association football|Soccer]]\n| [[Evergreen Premier League]]\n| align=center | 2020\n| [[Everett Memorial Stadium]]\n| \n|-\n| [[Everett Silvertips]]\n| align=center | [[Ice hockey|Hockey]]\n| [[Western Hockey League]]\n| align=center | 2003\n| [[Angel of the Winds Arena]]\n|\n|}\n\n==Parks and recreation==\n[[File:Everett - Grand Ave Park.jpg|thumb|Grand Ave. Park]]\n\nEverett has more than 40 [[city park|parks]], [[hiking trail|trails]], [[golf course]]s, and [[playground]]s maintained by the city government's Parks and Recreation Department.<ref name=\"Herald-Clark\">{{cite news |last=Chircop |first=David |date=September 20, 2006 |title=Everett's first park comes to life |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everetts-first-park-comes-to-life/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The department manages a total of {{convert|693|acre|ha}} of land, with most areas set aside for nature [[wildlife conservation|conservation]] and others developed for use by residents and visitors.<ref name=\"POPS\">{{cite web |year=2015 |title=Everett, Washington Parks, Recreation and Open Space (PROS) Plan |page=28 |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/6455/PROS-PDF |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The department also organizes recreational activities at city parks and throughout the city, including sports leagues, [[swimming]] lessons, hiking trips, and classes on [[cooking]] and [[gardening]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Jackson |first=Sarah |date=May 2, 2008 |title=Get outdoors: Registration begins May 12 for Everett Parks and Rec programs |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/get-outdoors-registration-begins-may-12-for-everett-parks-and-rec-programs/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Goffredo |first=Theresa |date=January 26, 2009 |title=Everett parks department class makes learning cross-country skiing fun, easy |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/everett-parks-department-class-makes-learning-cross-country-skiing-fun-easy/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city's first park, now known as Clark Park, was established in 1894 and functioned as a [[town square]] with regular concerts and protests until its [[bandstand]] was demolished in 1979.{{sfnp|May|Preboski|1989|pages=12\u201313}} The largest park in Everett, Forest Park, was acquired in late 1894 and was left largely undeveloped until the 1930s.{{sfnp|May|Preboski|1989|p=16}} The parks system includes several facilities with [[Pitch (sports field)|sports fields]] and courts, including Garfield Park, Kasch Park, Henry M. Jackson Park, and Phil Johnson Ballfields.<ref name=\"POPS\"/> The city also operates two public golf courses at American Legion Memorial Park (opened in 1934) and Walter E. Hall Park (opened in 1972).<ref name=\"Herald-Golf\">{{cite news |last=Myhre |first=Rich |date=June 22, 2013 |title=Everett's love affair with golf |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/everetts-love-affair-with-golf/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> A private golf course, the Everett Golf & Country Club, was established in 1910 on {{convert|66|acre|ha}} south of downtown.<ref>{{cite news |last=Myhre |first=Rich |date=May 12, 2010 |title=Everett Golf & Country Club celebrates 100 years of pride and joy |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/everett-golf-country-club-celebrates-100-years-of-pride-and-joy/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe municipal parks system includes several miles of public shoreline access at Howarth Park on Port Gardner Bay, Rotary Park and Langus Riverfront Park on the Snohomish River, and Thornton A. Sullivan Park on Silver Lake.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=June 6, 2015 |title=Days at Snohomish County beaches, parks may take some planning this summer |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/days-at-snohomish-county-beaches-parks-may-take-some-planning-this-summer/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The shoreline parks also include public [[beach]]es and [[boat launch]]es for recreational boating.<ref name=\"POPS\"/> The Port of Everett also has a large public [[marina]] and its own boat launch at 10th Street that also serves a ferry to [[Jetty Island]].<ref>{{cite news |date=July 3, 2018 |title=Everett's economic anchor: Big ships, big marina, big impact |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/everetts-economic-anchor-big-ships-big-marina-big-impact/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Benbow |first=Mike |date=January 12, 2010 |title=$3 parking fee to be added at Everett boat launch |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/3-parking-fee-to-be-added-at-everett-boat-launch/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The state and county governments also maintain their own parks in the Everett area, including the jointly maintained [[Spencer Island Regional Park]].<ref name=\"POPS\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Kelley |first=Tina |date=March 13, 1998 |title=Spencer Island birds rule over factories and freeway |page= |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19980313&slug=2739333 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The city government is also responsible for maintaining a section of the [[Interurban Trail (Snohomish County)|Interurban Trail]], which connects Everett to Lynnwood, [[Mountlake Terrace, Washington|Mountlake Terrace]], [[Shoreline, Washington|Shoreline]], and Seattle.<ref name=\"Herald-Interurban\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Debra |date=October 9, 2011 |title=Danger on trails |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/danger-on-trails/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> North Everett is ringed by the [[Mill Town Trail]], a {{convert|6|mi|km|adj=mid|spell=in}} multi-use pathway with interpretive signs to commemorate the city's industrial history.<ref name=\"Herald-WaterfrontHist\"/>\n\n===Major parks===\n\nForest Park, located southwest of Downtown Everett is the largest park in the city system, at {{convert|197|acre|ha}}.<ref name=\"POPS\"/>{{rp|52}} The park is situated along Pigeon Creek, with recreational facilities on a plateau overlooking the ravine and several miles of hiking trails. It was acquired by the city in 1894 and named Forest Park in 1913. A public [[zoo]] was established at Forest Park in 1914 by parks director Oden Hall, who collected animals through trades and gifts from other zoos and traveling circuses. The zookeeper position was eliminated in 1958 and the zoo was demolished in 1962 after three [[bond issue]]s to upgrade the facilities failed.{{sfnp|May|Preboski|1989|p=16}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=June 4, 2015 |title=Nostalgia tinged with sadness: The story of Forest Park Zoo |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/nostalgia-tinged-with-sadness-the-story-of-forest-park-zoo/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Forest Park's main facilities were built during the 1930s by the [[Works Progress Administration]], including the Floral Hall, playgrounds, terrace hillsides, and picnic shelters.<ref name=\"Herald-WPAForest\"/> A public [[swimming pool]] was opened at Forest Park in 1975 and replaced by a permanent structure in 1984.{{sfnp|May|Preboski|1989|p=19}} Major renovations of the facilities in the park were completed in 1997 and 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Watanabe |first=Ben |date=January 4, 2020 |title=Popular Forest Park playground to close 4 months for upgrade |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/forest-park-playground-to-close-for-major-renovation/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe largest park in North Everett is [[American Legion Memorial Park]], a {{convert|140|acre|ha|adj=mid}} open space located on the peninsula's northwest bluff at the site of a former [[Snohomish people|Snohomish]] village and [[smelter]].{{sfnp|May|Preboski|1989|pages=76\u201378}} The majority of the park is occupied by a golf course that was built by the [[American Legion]] and transferred to the city government alongside the rest of the park in 1935.<ref name=\"Herald-Golf\"/> The [[Evergreen Arboretum and Gardens|Evergreen Arboretum]] was built in 1963 at the northwest edge of the golf course, alongside a [[picnic shelter]] and the county's history museum.{{sfnp|May|Preboski|1989|pages=76\u201378}} A [[scenic viewpoint]] on the park grounds with views of the [[Olympic Mountains]] was named Hibulb Lookout in 2014, commemorating the historic Snohomish village at the site.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=December 12, 2014 |title=Everett bluff and trail get new names |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-bluff-and-trail-get-new-names/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Jetty Island]] is an [[artificial island]] located in Port Gardner that is {{convert|2|mi|km}} long and is home to sandy beaches and wildlife habitats. The island was formed from dredging of the [[Snohomish River]] in the early 20th century and acquired by the [[Port of Everett]] in 1929.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brown |first=Andrea |date=July 5, 2017 |title=The ferry is running! How to enjoy Everett's Jetty Island |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/the-riviera-of-everett-jetty-island-season-opens-july-5/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The city began operating a seasonal ferry between the island and a waterfront parking area in 1985; the ferry now runs from July to September, serving 50,000 visitors annually.<ref name=\"Herald-Jetty18\">{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Joseph |date=July 11, 2018 |title=Jetty Island opens for family-friendly fun |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/jetty-island-opens-for-the-season/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=McQuaide |first=Mike |date=July 28, 2010 |title=Everett's Jetty Island is an oasis of sand, sunshine and sweet memories |page= |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/outdoors/2012469134_nwwjettyisland29.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903115111/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/outdoors/2012469134_nwwjettyisland29.html |archivedate=September 3, 2011 |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Jetty Island is home to more than 115 identified bird species, salmon habitats, and mollusks.<ref name=\"Herald-Jetty18\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Stevick |first=Eric |date=August 17, 2007 |title=Digging into Jetty Island |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/digging-into-jetty-island/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Everett High School-1.jpg|thumb|[[Everett High School (Washington)|Everett High School]] (part of Everett Public Schools)]]\n\nThe city's public education system is managed by [[Everett Public Schools (Washington)|Everett Public Schools]] (officially the Everett School District), which has 26 schools, 2,000 staff members, and an enrollment of 20,000 students.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cornfield |first=Jerry |date=October 29, 2019 |title=In Everett school races, they agree more than they don't |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/in-everett-school-races-they-agree-more-than-they-dont/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Times-Cohn\">{{cite news |date=November 18, 2016 |title=Everett schools chief honored as state Superintendent of Year |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/education/everett-schools-chief-named-state-supe-of-2017/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=November 21, 2016}}</ref> The school district covers {{convert|52|sqmi|sqkm}}, including most of Everett, the city of [[Mill Creek, Washington|Mill Creek]], and the unincorporated area of [[Silver Firs, Washington|Silver Firs]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Census 2010: Everett School District |url=http://data.spokesman.com/census/2010/washington/school-districts/everett-school-district-wa/ |work=[[The Spokesman-Review]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110304004210/http://data.spokesman.com/census/2010/washington/school-districts/everett-school-district-wa/ |archivedate=March 4, 2011 |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The southern and western neighborhoods of Everett are served by the [[Mukilteo School District]], which also has its own high school ([[Mariner High School (Everett, Washington)|Mariner]]) in the area.<ref>{{cite map |date=December 21, 2017 |title=Snohomish County School Districts Map |url=http://www.snoco.org/docs/scd/PDF/PDS_CFP/Snohomish%20County%20School%20District.pdf |publisher=Snohomish County |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett Public Schools has three high school campuses: [[Everett High School (Washington)|Everett High School]] near downtown, [[Cascade High School (Everett, Washington)|Cascade High School]] near Casino Corner, and [[Henry M. Jackson High School]] in Mill Creek.<ref name=\"Herald-HighSchool19\">{{cite news |last=Bryan |first=Zachariah |date=May 22, 2019 |title=After year of debate, Everett has new high school boundaries |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/after-year-of-debate-everett-has-new-high-school-boundaries/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The school district was recognized in 2016 for its high [[graduation]] rates of 90 percent for four-year students and 94.5 percent for five-year students.<ref name=\"Times-Cohn\"/> A fourth high school campus, planned to cost $220&nbsp;million to build, was part of a [[bond measure]] in February 2018 that was rejected by voters, resulting in boundary changes for the existing schools.<ref name=\"Herald-HighSchool19\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Cornfield |first=Jerry |date=September 22, 2019 |title=Trying again. Everett schools eye a $317M bond in 2020 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/trying-again-everett-schools-eye-a-317m-bond-in-2020/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The school district also has five [[middle school]]s and 18 [[elementary school]]s in Everett and Mill Creek.<ref>{{cite web |title=2019-20 Boundary Map |url=https://www.everettsd.org/Page/29519 |publisher=[[Everett Public Schools (Washington)|Everett Public Schools]] |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Stevick |first=Eric |date=December 8, 2018 |title=Meet Tambark Creek. Everett has a new kid on the block |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/meet-tambark-creek-everett-has-a-new-kid-on-the-block/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The city is also home to two [[alternative school]]s: Sequoia High School, operated by Everett Public Schools;<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mulligan |first1=Mark |last2=Mulligan |first2=Annie |date=June 28, 2013 |title=If students have the will, Sequoia High has the way |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/if-students-have-the-will-sequoia-high-has-the-way/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> and ACES High School, operated by the Mukilteo School District.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hutton |first=Caleb |date=December 6, 2018 |title=Teen guilty of plotting a massive school shooting in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-teen-with-gun-guilty-of-plotting-school-shooting/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Everett area is also home to several [[private school]] systems operated by religious organizations and independent educators, including those that cater to commuters from around the county. The largest private high school in the county is [[Archbishop Murphy High School]], a Catholic school located in southeastern Everett, with an enrollment of 500 students.<ref>{{cite news |last=Slager |first=Melissa |date=December 9, 2006 |title=Private school enrollment rises |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/stories/06/12/09/100loc_b1schools001.cfm |work=The Everett Herald |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061214170329/http://www.heraldnet.com/stories/06/12/09/100loc_b1schools001.cfm |archivedate=December 14, 2006 |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Other major private religious schools include the [[Everett Christian School]], Cedar Park Christian School, and Northshore Christian Academy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Koenig |first=Sarah |date=January 10, 2008 |title=Cedar Park takes over North Sound Christian Schools |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/uncategorized/cedar-park-takes-over-north-sound-christian-schools/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Higher education===\n\n[[Everett Community College]] (EvCC) is a two-year public [[community college]] that has enrolled 19,000 students from around Snohomish County and 463 total faculty.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=October 14, 2015 |title=Developer to build dormitory near Everett Community College |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/developer-to-build-dormitory-near-everett-community-college/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=College Navigator: Everett Community College |url=https://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?id=235149 |work=[[National Center for Education Statistics]] |publisher=[[Institute of Education Sciences]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The college's main campus is located <!--spans {{convert||acre|ha}}--> in North Everett on the south side of Legion Memorial Golf Course.<ref name=\"Times-WSU11\">{{cite news |last=Long |first=Katherine |date=May 23, 2011 |title=Steps taken toward creating WSU branch campus in Everett |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2015129940_wsu24m.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202073035/http://old.seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2015129940_wsu24m.html |archivedate=February 2, 2017 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> It was established in 1941 at a former downtown elementary school and moved to its North Everett location in 1958, where it has since expanded several times.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=210\u2013211}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Slager |first1=Melissa |last2=Warnick |first2=Jennifer |date=August 13, 2005 |title=EvCC carving a place to grow |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/evcc-carving-a-place-to-grow/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCivic and business leaders from the Everett area began lobbying the state legislature for a four-year college in the 1990s, proposing a branch of an existing state college to serve Snohomish, Island, and Skagit counties.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brooks |first=Diane |date=December 2, 1994 |title=Bid for college alive in Everett |page=B1 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> A site in [[Bothell, Washington|Bothell]] was instead chosen for a [[University of Washington Bothell|northern branch campus]] for the [[University of Washington]] (UW), but only 27 percent of its students were from Snohomish County.<ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Lynn |date=August 17, 2005 |title=Push for 4-year college revs up |page=H18 |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/education/2002442337_4year17n.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306202952/http://old.seattletimes.com/html/education/2002442337_4year17n.html |archivedate=March 6, 2018 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Stevick |first=Eric |date=August 22, 2005 |title=Ideas floated for new university |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/ideas-floated-for-new-university/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> In 2007, the state legislature authorized planning funds for a UW branch campus in Snohomish County and a site near [[Everett Station]] was named as a finalist alongside candidates in Lake Stevens and Marysville.<ref name=\"Times-WSU11\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Perry |first=Nick |date=January 6, 2008 |title=UW Everett: ambitious, but dogged by doubts |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/uw-everett-ambitious-but-dogged-by-doubts/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The [[University of Washington North Sound|branch campus project]] was shelved by the state legislature in 2008 amid a funding shortfall for the education system.<ref name=\"Herald-Degrees08\">{{cite news |last=Stevick |first=Eric |date=November 23, 2008 |title=College degrees available in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/college-degrees-available-in-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Washington State University Everett]] opened in 2017 as a branch campus of WSU and is located adjacent to the EvCC campus in North Everett.<ref name=\"Times-WSU17\">{{cite news |last=Long |first=Katherine |date=August 11, 2017 |title=WSU's new building: 'the biggest thing Everett has ever done in terms of its future' |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/education/wsus-new-building-the-biggest-thing-everett-has-ever-done-in-terms-of-its-future/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The branch campus was conceived as a replacement for the UW proposal and included a WSU takeover of the [[University Center of North Puget Sound]], an alternative degrees program at EvCC, in 2014.<ref name=\"Times-WSU11\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Harper |first=Christina |date=June 30, 2014 |title=WSU taking over University Center at EvCC |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/wsu-taking-over-university-center-at-evcc/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The EvCC campus also houses a branch of [[Western Washington University]], which it established in 1986.<ref>{{cite web |title=Everett |url=https://www.wwu.edu/everett |publisher=[[Western Washington University]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Haglund |first1=Noah |last2=Stevick |first2=Eric |date=August 16, 2017 |title=At long last, WSU Everett's new building is open for business |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/at-long-last-wsu-everetts-new-building-open-for-business/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEverett is also home to several private and specialized colleges, including [[City University of Seattle|City University]] and [[Everest College]] near the Everett Mall.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 27, 2011 |title=Snohomish County colleges |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/snohomish-county-colleges/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=November 13, 2017 |title=Altierus to close Everett college, layoff 29 |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/altierus-to-close-everett-college-layoff-29/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The city also has branch campuses for [[Embry\u2013Riddle Aeronautical University]] near the Boeing assembly plant and [[Columbia College (Missouri)|Columbia College]] at Naval Station Everett.<ref>{{cite web |title=Locations: Everett, WA |url=https://worldwide.erau.edu/locations/everett |publisher=[[Embry\u2013Riddle Aeronautical University]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=August 26, 2015 |title=Columbia College celebrates 20 years in Snohomish County |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/columbia-college-celebrates-20-years-in-snohomish-county/ |work=The Everett Herald Business Journal |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Everett's two major [[Lutheran]] churches operated a pair of short-lived private colleges in the early 20th century, Bethania College and Columbia College.{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|pages=210\u2013211}} [[Henry Cogswell College]], a private institution, moved from Kirkland to Everett in 1996 and closed in 2006.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brooks |first=Diane |date=March 21, 1996 |title=4-year school to locate in Everett |page=B3 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19960321&slug=2320138 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stevick |first1=Eric |last2=Chircop |first2=David |date=June 29, 2006 |title=Cogswell College will close |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/cogswell-college-will-close/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> In the 2010s, [[Bryman College]] and [[Trinity Lutheran College (Washington)|Trinity Lutheran College]] both closed their Everett campuses.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=January 12, 2016 |title=Trinity Lutheran College in downtown Everett to close |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/trinity-lutheran-college-in-downtown-everett-to-close/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Infrastructure==\n\n===Transportation===\n[[File:Everett Station building.jpg|thumb|[[Everett Station]], the city's [[Amtrak]] and [[Sounder commuter rail]] station that also serves local and express buses]]\n\nThe city is located along [[Interstate 5 in Washington|Interstate 5]] (I-5), a major north\u2013south freeway that connects Everett to [[Seattle]] and [[Vancouver]], British Columbia. The Everett\u2013Seattle section of I-5 is rated as one of the most congested in the United States during commuting hours, with an average of 94 minutes to travel {{convert|24|mi|km}} and 182,000 daily vehicles in South Everett.<ref name=\"Times-Traffic18\"/> The city also has several major highways with intercity connections, including [[U.S. Route 2 in Washington|U.S. Route 2]] to [[Wenatchee, Washington|Wenatchee]] via [[Stevens Pass]]; [[Washington State Route 99|State Route 99]] from the Everett Mall to Seattle; [[Washington State Route 526|State Route 526]] to Mukilteo; [[Washington State Route 527|State Route 527]] from the Everett Mall to Mill Creek; and [[Washington State Route 529|State Route 529]] from the waterfront to Marysville.<ref name=\"WSDOT-Map\"/>\n\nEverett has several public transit and intercity transport services that intersect at [[Everett Station]], a multimodal train and bus station that opened in 2002.<ref name=\"Times-Station03\"/> The station is served by two [[Amtrak]] routes: [[Amtrak Cascades|''Cascades'']], which connects Vancouver to Seattle and [[Portland, Oregon]]; and the ''[[Empire Builder]]'', which travels from Seattle to [[Chicago]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Cantwell |first=Brian J. |date=December 10, 2015 |title=Amtrak restores train service through Washington state |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/life/travel/amtrak-restores-service-through-washington-state/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Everett is also the northern terminus of the [[Sounder commuter rail]] system, which is operated by [[Sound Transit]] and travels south to Seattle during [[peak hour]]s with stops in Mukilteo and Edmonds.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lindblom |first=Mike |date=October 16, 2012 |title=Too many empty seats on Sounder north line |page=A1 |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2019441910_sounder16m.html |work=The Seattle Times |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514123023/http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2019441910_sounder16m.html |archivedate=May 14, 2013 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The station is served by intercity buses from [[Greyhound Lines]], [[BoltBus]], and [[Northwestern Trailways]], which connect Everett to cities in the Pacific Northwest.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sheets |first=Bill |date=February 6, 2012 |title=Everett Station celebrates 10 years and 17 million visits |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-station-celebrates-10-years-and-17-million-visits/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Podsada |first=Janice |date=March 8, 2019 |title=BoltBus links Everett to Seattle and other big I-5 cities |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/discount-bus-service-launches-from-everett-station/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The passenger trains operate on tracks owned by [[BNSF Railway]], which operates freight service and maintains a major railyard in Northeast Everett.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=January 18, 2015 |title=Railroad loop proposed on Everett's Smith Island |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/railroad-loop-proposed-on-everetts-smith-island/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city-run [[Everett Transit]] system was established in 1969, replacing a private operator that had opened the first [[streetcar]] lines in the city in 1893.<ref>{{cite news |date=November 30, 2008 |title=Everett Transit rolls back fares for 115th birthday |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/around-the-county-346/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The countywide [[Community Transit]] system, based in Everett, connects to surrounding cities and operates a commuter bus network.<ref>{{cite map |date=September 2019 |title=Community Transit System Map |url=https://www.communitytransit.org/docs/default-source/mappdfs/19septmaps/systemmappdfs/mapsystemsept2019.pdf |publisher=[[Community Transit]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Its [[bus rapid transit]] system, [[Swift Bus Rapid Transit|Swift]] has two lines that travel through the city: the [[Swift Blue Line|Blue Line]] from Downtown Everett to [[Shoreline, Washington|Shoreline]] via State Route 99; and the [[Swift Green Line|Green Line]], which connects the Boeing plant to Mill Creek and northern Bothell.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=March 21, 2019 |title=From Bothell to Boeing: Green Line bus route begins Sunday |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/major-changes-coming-to-community-transit-in-march/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Sound Transit also provides [[Sound Transit Express|express bus service]] to [[Bellevue, Washington|Bellevue]] during peak hours and Downtown Seattle at all hours.<ref>{{cite web |date=December 2017 |title=2017 Service Implementation Plan |pages=116\u2013117, 140\u2013141 |url=https://www.soundtransit.org/sites/default/files/2018-service-implementation-plan.pdf |publisher=[[Sound Transit]] |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The agency plans to extend its [[Link light rail]] service to Downtown Everett in 2036, as part of the [[Sound Transit 3]] plan passed by voters in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haglund |first1=Noah |last2=Giordano |first2=Lizz |date=June 25, 2018 |title=It's getting real: Light rail is coming to the 'burbs |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/its-getting-real-light-rail-is-coming-to-the-burbs/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> From 1910 to 1939, Everett was connected with Seattle by an [[interurban]] railway, which was later replaced by the [[Interurban Trail (Snohomish County)|Interurban Trail]].<ref name=\"Herald-Interurban\"/>\n\nEverett's airport, [[Paine Field]], is operated by Snohomish County primarily for aerospace businesses and general aviation. The airport was opened in 1936 and was used as a military base and commercial airport until 1966, when Boeing selected it for the site of a major assembly plant.<ref>{{cite news |date=August 7, 2004 |title=Paine Field's journey to flight |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/paine-fields-journey-to-flight/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Commercial passenger service to Paine Field resumed on March 4, 2019, after the construction of a new terminal operated by a private company.<ref name=\"Times-Paine\"/> The nearest major airports are [[Boeing Field]] in Seattle and [[Seattle-Tacoma International Airport]] in southern King County.<ref name=\"Times-Paine\"/> A private passenger ferry from the Port of Everett provides access to [[Gedney Island|Hat Island]] in Possession Sound.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=July 31, 2018 |title=Hat Island: The somewhat secret, other-worldy Northwest gem |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/close-yet-another-world-its-quite-a-voyage-to-hat-island/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Utilities===\n\n[[Electric power]] for Everett buildings is provided by the [[Snohomish County Public Utility District]] (PUD), a consumer-owned [[public utility]] that serves all of Snohomish County.<ref>{{cite web |date=October 2018 |title=Quick Facts for Snohomish County PUD |url=https://www.snopud.com/Site/Content/Documents/custpubs/MiniQF_1018.pdf |publisher=[[Snohomish County Public Utility District]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129142056/https://www.snopud.com/Site/Content/Documents/custpubs/MiniQF_1018.pdf |archivedate=November 29, 2018 |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The privately run [[Puget Sound Energy]] provides [[natural gas]] service to the city's residents and businesses.<ref>{{cite web |year=2013 |title=Puget Sound Energy service area |url=http://pse.com/aboutpse/PseNewsroom/MediaKit/1213_ServiceAreaMap_web.pdf |publisher=[[Puget Sound Energy]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170128213047/https://pse.com/aboutpse/PseNewsroom/MediaKit/1213_ServiceAreaMap_web.pdf |archivedate=January 28, 2017 |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The city government contracts with Rubatino Refuse Removal and [[Waste Management (corporation)|Waste Management]] for curbside [[municipal solid waste|garbage]], [[single-stream recycling|recycling]], and [[yard waste]] collection and disposal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Garbage, Recycling & Compost |url=https://everettwa.gov/637/Garbage-Recycling-Compost |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Everett's municipal [[wastewater]] and [[sewage]] system, which is combined with [[stormwater]] treatment, includes {{convert|145|mi|km}} of pipes that primarily feed into the [[Everett Water Pollution Control Facility]] on Smith Island and empties in the Snohomish River delta.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=December 4, 2014 |title=$320M fix prescribed for Everett's aging sewers |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/320m-fix-prescribed-for-everett%C2%92s-aging-sewers/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Sanders |first=Julia-Grace |date=September 12, 2019 |title=Stench wrinkles noses in some north Everett neighborhoods |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/odor-overwhelms-some-north-everett-neighborhoods/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe City of Everett maintains a [[tap water]] system that supplies 80 percent of Snohomish County through interlocal agreements with other municipalities and [[water district]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sheets |first=Bill |date=October 13, 2011 |title=Environmental plan earns Sultan River dam a new 45-year license |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/environmental-plan-earns-sultan-river-dam-a-new-45-year-license/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=November 2004 |title=Where Does Your Water Come From? |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/824/Where-Does-Your-Water-Come-From-PDF |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The system primarily sources its water from [[Spada Lake]], an artificial reservoir on the [[Sultan River]] created by the [[Culmback Dam]] located {{convert|25|mi|km}} east of Everett in the Cascade Mountains. The water is treated at a [[water purification|filtration plant]] at Lake Chaplain, the system's secondary water source, which has a capacity of {{convert|134|e6USgal|kl}} per day and typically handles {{convert|50|e6gal|kl|abbr=unit}} per day.<ref>{{cite news |last=Winters |first=Chris |date=September 8, 2016 |title=Anticipating growth, Everett looks to boost water flow |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-to-test-increasing-water-flow-to-customers/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The Sultan River basin has been used as the main source of the city's water since 1917 and uses a {{convert|25|mi|km|adj=mid}} network of pipes to reach Everett; the modern Spada Lake reservoir was formed in 1965 by the construction of the Culmback Dam, co-owned by Everett and the Snohomish County PUD.{{sfnp|Dorpat|McCovy|1998|p=207}}{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=187}}\n\nThe city is covered by several telecommunications companies that provide [[telephone]], [[broadband internet]], and other services. [[Frontier Communications Northwest|Frontier Communications]] is the largest telecommunications provider in the city and inherited its legacy system from [[GTE|GTE Northwest]] and [[Verizon]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Podsada |first=Janice |date=June 3, 2019 |title=A new-wave broadband firm dials up Frontier Communications |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/a-new-wave-broadband-firm-dials-up-frontier-communications/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Other major providers in the Everett area include [[Xfinity|Comcast Xfinity]], [[CenturyLink]], and [[Wave Broadband]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Everett Comprehensive Plan Capital Facilities and Utilities Element |page=36 |url=https://everettwa.gov/DocumentCenter/View/4861/Chapter-06-Capital-Facilities-and-Utilities-PDF |publisher=City of Everett |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Healthcare===\n\nEverett is home to [[Providence Regional Medical Center Everett]], a system of two general hospitals operated by [[Providence Health & Services]]. The hospital system was formed in 1994 by the merger of two existing hospitals in Everett: the Everett General Hospital, opened in January 1894 as the city's first hospital;{{sfnp|O'Donnell|1993|p=211}} and Providence Hospital, established in 1905 near Downtown Everett.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Providence Story |url=https://washington.providence.org/locations-directory/r/regional-medical-center/about/history |publisher=[[Providence Health & Services]] |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Muhlstein |first=Julie |date=August 27, 2014 |title=Spirit of giving is a cornerstone of Snohomish County history |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/spirit-of-giving-is-a-cornerstone-of-snohomish-county-history/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The existing Providence Hospital was renamed the Providence Pacific Campus, while the former General Hospital became the Colby Campus, which was expanded in 2011 with a 12-story medical tower.<ref name=\"Herald-Providence11\"/> The Providence campuses have a combined capacity of 571 beds and 3,300 employees.<ref name=\"Herald-Providence11\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=January 16, 2017 |title=Everett Providence hospital seeks state OK for 70 more beds |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-providence-hospital-seeks-state-ok-for-70-more-beds/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe city also has several medical services with [[clinic]]s and specialized facilities operated by Providence and other providers. [[Kaiser Permanente]] has a five-story medical tower in Downtown Everett with a walk-in clinic, specialty services, and an [[urgent care]] clinic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Everett Medical Center |url=https://wa.kaiserpermanente.org/html/public/locations/everett |publisher=[[Kaiser Permanente]] |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The building originally opened for [[Group Health Cooperative|Group Health]] in 1994 to consolidate its three clinics in Everett and is planned to be expanded in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Alexander |first=Karen |date=April 30, 1993 |title=Group Health sets Everett groundbreaker |page=D8 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Giordano |first=Lizz |date=October 2, 2019 |title=Kaiser Permanente plans big growth spurt in Everett |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/kaiser-permanente-plans-big-growth-spurt-in-everett/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> [[The Everett Clinic]] is based in the city and operates medical facilities across Snohomish County, serving 320,000 patients.<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=February 29, 2016 |title=DaVita HealthCare Partners completes Everett Clinic purchase |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/davita-healthcare-partners-completes-everett-clinic-purchase/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The system was founded in 1924 and acquired in 2016 by [[DaVita Inc.]]; it was then sold to [[UnitedHealth Group]]'s [[Optum]] a year later.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Jim |date=December 6, 2017 |title=DaVita to sell off medical groups including The Everett Clinic |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/business/davita-to-sell-off-medical-groups-including-the-everett-clinic/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The non-profit Community Health Center of Snohomish County operates four medical clinics in Everett, providing services to primarily low-income and uninsured patients.<ref>{{cite news |last=Salyer |first=Sharon |date=January 16, 2018 |title=New Everett clinic to ease long wait times for appointments |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/community-health-center-opening-its-seventh-clinic/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n{{main|List of people from Everett, Washington}}\n\nEverett was the hometown of U.S. Senator [[Henry M. Jackson]], Washington governors [[Roland H. Hartley]] and [[Monrad Wallgren]], and several members of the U.S. Congress and Washington state legislature.<ref>{{cite news |date=April 23, 2008 |title=Seems Like Yesterday |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/seems-like-yesterday-1298/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The city has also produced several [[American football]] coaches under tutelage of Everett High School coach [[Jim Ennis (American football)|Jim Ennis]], including [[Jim Lambright]], [[Mike Price]], and [[Dennis Erickson]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Boyle |first=John |date=August 30, 2011 |title=Coaching close to home |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/coaching-close-to-home/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Christilaw |first=Steve |date=August 10, 1990 |title=Legendary Everett coach dies\u2014Ennis inspired many, friends say |page= |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19900810&slug=1087044 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Sister cities==\n\nEverett has the following [[Town twinning|sister city]] relationships:<ref>{{cite web |title=Washington's Sister Cities Relationships |url=https://www.ltgov.wa.gov/washington-sister-cities |publisher=[[Lieutenant Governor of Washington]] |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* {{flagdeco|JPN}} [[Iwakuni]], [[Yamaguchi Prefecture|Yamaguchi]], Japan (since 1962)<ref>{{cite news |last=Fiege |first=Gale |date=July 23, 2012 |title=Everett celebrates 50 years with Japanese sister city |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/everett-celebrates-50-years-with-japanese-sister-city/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n* {{flagdeco|IRL}} [[Sligo]], [[County Sligo]], Ireland\n* {{flagdeco|RUS}} [[Sovetskaya Gavan]], [[Khabarovsk Krai]], Russia (since 1991)<ref>{{cite news |last=Shaw |first=Linda |date=August 21, 1991 |title=Soviet radio operator reports quiet in Everett's sister city |page=B1 |url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19910821&slug=1301058 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last1=Cameron |first1=David A. |last2=LeWarne |first2=Charles P. |last3=May |first3=M. Allan |last4=O'Donnell |first4=Jack C. |last5=O'Donnell |first5=Lawrence E. |year=2005 |title=Snohomish County: An Illustrated History |publisher=Kelcema Books LLC |location=Index, Washington |isbn=978-0-9766700-0-1 |oclc=62728798}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last1=Dorpat |first1=Paul |authorlink1=Paul Dorpat |last2=McCovy |first2=Genevieve |year=1998 |title=Building Washington: A History of Washington State Public Works |publisher=Tartu Publications |location=Seattle |isbn=0-9614357-9-8 |oclc=40406154}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last1=May |first1=Allan |last2=Preboski |first2=Dale |year=1989 |title=The History of Everett Parks: A Century of Service and Vision |publisher=[[The Donning Company]] |location=Norfolk, Virginia |isbn=0-89865-794-6 |oclc=20453314}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=O'Donnell |first=Lawrence E. |year=1993 |title=Everett Past and Present: A Centennial History of Everett |publisher=K&H Printers |location=Everett |isbn=978-0-89716-275-3 |oclc=436832753}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Prosser |first=William Farrand |authorlink=William Farrand Prosser |year=1903 |title=A History of the Puget Sound Country |publisher=[[Lewis Publishing Company]] |location=New York |oclc=14570355 |url=https://archive.org/details/ahistorypugetso00prosgoog/ |via=[[The Internet Archive]] |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Whitfield |first=William M. |year=1926 |title=History of Snohomish County, Washington |publisher=Pioneer Historical Publishing Company |location=Chicago |oclc=8437390 |url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/102122401 |via=[[HathiTrust]] |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}\n{{refend}}\n\n===Further reading===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Clark |first=Norman H. |year=1970 |title=Mill Town: A Social History of Everett, Washington, From Its Earliest Beginnings on the Shores of Puget Sound to the Tragic and Infamous Event Known as the Everett Massacre |publisher=[[University of Washington Press]] |location=Seattle |isbn=978-0-295-95241-3 |oclc=28005191}}\n{{refend}}\n\n===Archives===\n{{refbegin}}\n* [http://digital.lib.washington.edu/findingaids/view?docId=EverettEducationAssociation3849.xml Everett Education Association Records.] 1937\u20132002. 28.06 cubic feet. At the [http://www.lib.washington.edu/specialcoll/laws Labor Archives of Washington, University of Washington Libraries Special Collections.]\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{EB1911 Poster|Everett, Washington}}\n* {{wikivoyage-inline|Everett (Washington)|Everett, Washington}}\n* {{official website|https://www.everettwa.gov/}}\n* {{dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Washington/Localities/E/Everett}}\n\n{{Everett, Washington}}\n{{Snohomish County, Washington